{"title_page": "Sunderland", "text_new": "{{About|the city in England}}{{Merge from|Sunderland Blitz|date=March 2020|discuss=Talk:Sunderland#Merge_proposal_of_Sunderland_Blitz}}{{More citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Sunderland\n|country = England\n|region= North East England\n|static_image_name=SunderlandMontage.jpg\n|static_image_width=280\n|static_image_caption=Clockwise, from top: Echo 24 and the [[Wearmouth Bridge]], Roker Lighthouse, the [[National Glass Centre]], [[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]], Fulwell Mill and [[Penshaw Monument]]\n|population = 174,286\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref name=\"BUA\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1119884905|title=Sunderland Built-up area|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n|population_demonym=[[Mackem]]\n|os_grid_reference= NZ395575\n|coordinates = {{coord|54.9061|-1.38113|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position=  left\n|post_town= SUNDERLAND\n|postcode_area= SR\n|postcode_district = SR1\u2013SR6\n|dial_code= 0191\n|constituency_westminster= [[Houghton and Sunderland South (UK Parliament constituency)|Houghton and Sunderland South]]\n|constituency_westminster1=[[Sunderland Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland Central]]\n|constituency_westminster2=[[Washington and Sunderland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Washington and Sunderland West]]\n|london_distance= 240&nbsp;mi&nbsp;(387&nbsp;km)&nbsp;[[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n|metropolitan_borough= [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]]\n|metropolitan_county = [[Tyne and Wear]]\n}}\n'''Sunderland''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Sunderland.ogg|\u02c8|s|\u028c|n|d|\u0259r|l|\u0259|n|d}}) is a city at the centre of the [[City of Sunderland]] [[metropolitan borough]], in [[Tyne and Wear]], England, 12 miles northeast of [[Durham, England|Durham]] and 10 miles southeast of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], at the mouth of the [[River Wear]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/roker.htm|title=Roker (Whitburn South) Beach|accessdate=18 August 2017 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/seaburn-beach.htm|title=Seaburn Beach (Whitburn North)|accessdate=18 August 2017 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/hendon-south-sunderland.htm|title=Hendon South Beach (Sunderland)|accessdate=2 January 2018 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in [[County Durham]], there were three original settlements by the mouth of the River Wear on the site of modern-day Sunderland. On the north side of the river, [[Monkwearmouth]] was settled in 674 when [[Ecgfrith of Northumbria|King Ecgfrith of Northumbria]] granted land to [[Benedict Biscop]] to found [[Monkwearmouth\u2013Jarrow Abbey|Monkwearmouth Monastery]]. In 685, Ecgfrith further granted Biscop the land adjacent to the monastery on the south side of the river. As the river separated this land from the monastic community, it was henceforth referred to as the \"sunder-land\", and would grow as a fishing settlement before being granted a charter in 1179.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://englandsnortheast.co.uk/Sunderland.html|title=Old Sunderland History|website=englandsnortheast.co.uk|access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref> West of the medieval village of Sunderland on the south bank, [[Bishopwearmouth]] was founded in 930.\n\nSunderland grew as a port, trading [[coal]] and [[salt]]. Ships began to be built on the river in the 14th century. By the 19th century, the port of Sunderland had absorbed Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth, owing to the growing economic importance of the shipbuilding docks. Following the decline of the city's traditional industries in the late 20th century, the area grew into a commercial centre for the automotive industry, science and technology and the service sector.\n\n[[Bede]], sometimes called the father of English history, began his monastic career at Monkwearmouth monastery in Sunderland, before moving to the newly founded Jarrow monastery in 685 (these monasteries together formed the dual [[Monkwearmouth-Jarrow Abbey]]). It therefore seems likely that he was born in or near Sunderland. Indeed, Bede later wrote that he was \"\u00e1cenned on ''sundorlande'' \u00fe\u00e6s ylcan mynstres\" (born in a ''separate land'' of this same monastery); here, \"sundorlande\" translates literally as \"separate land\" but could refer to the village of Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bosworthtoller.com/058721 |title=Sundor-land (supplementary) |last=Bosworth |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Bosworth |editor-last=Toller |editor-first=Thomas Northcote |editor-link=Thomas Northcote Toller |editor2-last=Christ |editor2-first=Sean |editor3-last=Tich\u00fd |editor3-first=Ond\u0159ej |publisher=Faculty of Arts, [[Charles University in Prague]] |date=March 21, 2010 |website=[[An Anglo-Saxon Dictionary]] Online.  |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bosworthtoller.com/029360 |title=Sundor-land |last=Bosworth |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Bosworth |editor-last=Toller |editor-first=Thomas Northcote |editor-link=Thomas Northcote Toller |editor2-last=Christ |editor2-first=Sean |editor3-last=Tich\u00fd |editor3-first=Ond\u0159ej |publisher=Faculty of Arts, [[Charles University in Prague]] |date=March 21, 2010 |website=[[An Anglo-Saxon Dictionary]] Online.  |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, it is possible that Sunderland was later named in honour of Bede's connections to the area, by people familiar with this statement of his.\n\nA person from Sunderland is sometimes known as a [[Mackem]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2005/06/21/wordhunt_feature.shtml|title=The Mackem Wordhunt|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=BBC|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/bulletin_board/18/messages/814.html |title=The word Mackem origins|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=Phrases.org website|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandsnortheast.co.uk/SunderlandMackems.html|title=Sunderland Mackem Origin|accessdate=19 August 2017 |publisher=englandsnortheast.co.uk|year=2016}}</ref> However, as this term originated as recently as the early 1980s, its use and acceptance by Sunderland residents, particularly among the older generations, is not universal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wp.sunderland.ac.uk/seagullcity/mackem/|title=Mackem|accessdate=19 August 2017 |publisher=Seagull City|year=2017}}</ref> At one time, Sunderland-built ships were called \"Jamies\", in contrast with those from Tyneside, which were known as \"Geordies\", although in the case of \"Jamie\" it is not known whether this was ever extended to people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/sunderland-mackems/|title=Sunderland : 'Mackems'|publisher=England's North East|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Northumbria.rise.600.700.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The areas that are now Sunderland were once part of the Kingdom of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]].]]\n\n===Early history===\n{{Main|Monkwearmouth\u2013Jarrow Abbey}}\nThe earliest inhabitants of the Sunderland area were [[Stone Age]] [[hunter-gatherer]]s and artifacts from this era have been discovered, including [[microliths]] found during excavations at [[St Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Sunderland |edition=2nd |year=2001 |isbn=0-9525122-6-2 |author=Glen Lyndon Dodds |page=5}}</ref> During the final phase of the Stone Age, the [[Neolithic period]] (c. 4000 \u2013 c. 2000 BC), [[Hastings Hill]], on the western outskirts of Sunderland, was a focal point of activity and a place of burial and ritual significance. Evidence includes the former presence of a [[cursus]] monument.<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Sunderland |edition=2nd |year=2001 |isbn=0-9525122-6-2 |author=Glen Lyndon Dodds |page=6}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed the [[Brigantes]] inhabited the area around the [[River Wear]] in the pre- and post-[[Roman Empire|Roman]] era. There is a long-standing local legend that there was a Roman settlement on the south bank of the River Wear on what is the site of the former Vaux Brewery, although no archaeological investigation has taken place.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3200659.stm|title=Brewery may hold Roman answers|accessdate=22 July 2009 |publisher=BBC News|date=2 September 2003}}</ref>\n\n====Early Middle Ages: Anglo-Saxon Northumbria====\n[[File:st peters sunderland.jpg|thumb|left|250px|St Peter's Church in Monkwearmouth. Only the porch and part of the west wall are what remain of the original monastery built in 674.]]\nRecorded settlements at the mouth of the Wear date to 674, when an [[Anglo-Saxon]] nobleman, [[Benedict Biscop]], granted land by King [[Ecgfrith of Northumbria]], founded the Wearmouth\u2013Jarrow (''St. Peter's'') [[monastery]] on the north bank of the river \u2013 an area that became known as Monkwearmouth. Biscop's monastery was the first built of stone in [[Northumbria]]. He employed glaziers from [[France]] and in doing so he re-established [[glass making]] in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/CustomPages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31748|title=Museum and Winter Gardens \u2013 Look At Glass|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo|year=2005 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080513072206/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/CustomPages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31748 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 May 2008}}</ref>\nIn 686 the community was taken over by [[Ceolfrid]], and Wearmouth\u2013Jarrow became a major centre of learning and knowledge in [[Anglo-Saxon England]] with a library of around 300 volumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weardaleway.wanadoo.co.uk/history1.html|title=Sunderland History|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Weardaleway website|year=2005|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131032803/http://www.weardaleway.wanadoo.co.uk/history1.html|archive-date=31 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Codex Amiatinus]], described by White as the 'finest book in the world',<ref>[[Henry Julian White|H. J. White]], ''The Codex Amiatinus and its Birthplace'', in: Studia Biblica et Ecclesiasctica (Oxford 1890), Vol. II, p. 273.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09227b.htm |title=Libraries |work=Catholic Encyclopedia |accessdate=23 January 2007}}</ref> was created at the monastery and was likely worked on by [[Bede]], who was born at Wearmouth in 673.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedesworld.co.uk/academic-bede.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030604082808/http://bedesworld.co.uk/academic-bede.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 June 2003|title=Academic \u2013 The Venerable Bede|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Bede's World museum|year=2008}}</ref> This is one of the oldest monasteries still standing in England.  While at the monastery, Bede completed the ''[[Historia ecclesiastica gentis Anglorum]]'' ''(The Ecclesiastical History of the English People)'' in 731, a feat which earned him the title ''The father of English history.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/exhibns/month/jan2001.html|title=Book of the Month, Bede Wrings on the Calendar|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=University of Glasgow|year=2001}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 8th century, the [[Vikings]] raided the coast, and by the middle of the 9th century, the monastery had been abandoned. Lands on the south side of the river were granted to the [[Bishop of Durham]] by [[Athelstan|Athelstan of England]] in 930; these became known as Bishopwearmouth and included settlements such as [[Ryhope]] which fall within the modern boundary of Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/implementation/conservation/conservationwalks/bishopwearmouth/bishop.origins.asp |title=Origins of Bishopwearmouth |accessdate=23 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201702/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/implementation/conservation/conservationwalks/bishopwearmouth/bishop.origins.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wearsideonline.com/ryhope_village.html|title=Ryhope Village|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Wearsideonline website|year=2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316021942/http://www.wearsideonline.com/ryhope_village.html|archive-date=16 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Medieval developments after the Norman conquest====\nIn 1100, Bishopwearmouth parish included a [[fishing]] village at the southern mouth of the river (now the East End) known as 'Soender-land' (which evolved into 'Sunderland').<ref>{{cite news |title=What's in a name? |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=1512&ArticleID=1962253 |work=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=17 January 2007  }}{{dead link|date=October 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> This settlement was granted a [[charter]] in 1179 by [[Hugh Pudsey]], then the [[Bishop of Durham]] (who had quasi-[[monarchical]] power within the [[County Palatine of Durham|County Palatine]]);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/page42.htm|title=The North East England History Pages|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=David Simpson|work=The Millennium History of North East England|year=1991}}</ref> the charter gave its merchants the same rights as those of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]], but it nevertheless took time for Sunderland to develop as a [[port]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle Coal |url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/NewcastleCoal.html |website=England's North East |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> Fishing was the main commercial activity at the time: mainly [[herring]] in the 13th century, then [[salmon]] in the 14th and 15th centuries.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\">{{cite book |last1=Pevsner |first1=Nikolaus |last2=Williamson |first2=Elizabeth |title=The Buildings of England: County Durham |date=1983 |publisher=Penguin |location=London |edition=2nd}}</ref> From 1346 [[shipbuilding|ships were being built]] at Wearmouth, by a merchant named Thomas Menville,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissunderland.com/history/a_shipbuilding_tradition.asp |title=Sunderland Ship Building |access-date=3 April 2008 |work=This is Sunderland website |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814171112/http://www.thisissunderland.com/history/a_shipbuilding_tradition.asp |archive-date=14 August 2007 }}</ref> and by 1396 a small amount of coal was being exported.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" />\n\nRapid growth of the port was initially prompted by the salt trade.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Salt exports from Sunderland are recorded from as early as the 13th century, but In 1589, [[Salt pan (evaporation)|salt pans]] were laid at Bishopwearmouth Panns (the modern-day name of the area the pans occupied is Pann's Bank, on the river bank between the city centre and the East End).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.localhistories.org/sunderland.html|title=A Brief History of Sunderland|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Tim Lambert|year=2008}}</ref> Large vats of [[seawater]] were heated using coal; as the water evaporated the salt remained. As coal was required to heat the salt pans, a [[coal mining]] community began to emerge. Only poor quality coal was used in salt panning; better quality coal was traded via the port, which subsequently began to grow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/coal/1100_1500/index.html |title=North East History, Early Coal Mining |access-date=3 April 2008 |work=The Northern Echo |year=2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927173408/http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/coal/1100_1500/index.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===17th century===\nBoth salt and coal continued to be exported through the 17th century, but the coal trade grew significantly (2-3,000 tons of coal were exported from Sunderland in the year 1600; by 1680 this had increased to 180,000 tons).<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Because of the difficulty for colliers trying to navigate the shallow waters of the Wear, coal mined further inland was loaded onto keels (large, flat-bottomed boats) and taken downriver to the waiting colliers. The keels were manned by a close-knit group of workers known as '[[keelmen]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/didyouknow/12.html|title=Did you know?|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=North East History website|year=2003}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn 1634 a charter was granted by Bishop [[Thomas Morton (bishop)|Thomas Morton]], which [[Municipal corporation|incorporated]] the inhabitants of the '[[Ancient borough|antient borough]]' of Sunderland as the 'Mayor, Aldermen and Commonality' of the Borough and granted the privilege of a market and an annual fair. While, as a consequence, a [[mayor]] and twelve [[aldermen]] were appointed, and a common council established, their establishment does not seem to have survived the ensuing [[English Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" />\n\nBefore the 1st English civil war the North, with the exclusion of [[Kingston upon Hull]], declared for the King. In 1644 the North was captured by parliament.<ref name=civilwar>{{cite web | last = History.com Staff | title = English civil wars | website = history.com | publisher = A+E Networks | year = 2009 | url = http://www.history.com/topics/british-history/english-civil-wars | accessdate = 29 July 2015 }}</ref> The villages that later become Sunderland, were taken in March 1644.<ref name=\"civWar1644\">{{cite book | last = Dodds | first = Derek | title = Northumbia\u2026 (Battlefield Britain) | publisher = Leo Cooper Ltd (20 Oct 2005) | date = 20 October 2005 | location = England | page = 139 | url = https://www.amazon.co.uk/Northumbria-War-Conflict-Northumberland-Battlefield/dp/1844151492/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1433176389&sr=1-1&keywords=9781844151493| isbn = 1844151492}}</ref> One artifact of the English civil war near this area was the long trench; a tactic of later warfare.<ref name=\"civWar1644\"/> In the village of [[Offerton, Tyne and Wear|Offerton]] roughly three miles inland from the area, skirmishes occurred.<ref>{{cite news |title=''A History of Sunderland'' (second edition, 2001), Glen Lyndon Dodds, pp. 46\u201348}}</ref><ref name=tren>{{cite web | title = Offerton, site of Civil War skirmish - Details| website = twsitelines.info| publisher = | year = | url = http://www.twsitelines.info/SMR/25| accessdate = 19 August 2016 }}</ref> Parliament also blockaded the [[River Tyne]], crippling the Newcastle coal trade which allowed the coal trade of the area to flourish for a short period.\n\nIn 1669, after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]], King [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] granted [[letters patent]] to one Edward Andrew, [[Esq.]] to 'build a pier and erect a lighthouse or lighthouses and cleanse the harbour of Sunderland', and authorised the levying of a [[tonnage]] [[Duty (economics)|duty]] on shipping in order to raise the necessary funds;<ref name=\"Sykes1833\">{{cite book |last1=Sykes |first1=John |title=Local Records: Or, Historical Register of Remarkable Events, which Have Occurred in Northumberland and Durham, Newcastle Upon Tyne, and Berwick Upon Tweed (vol. 1) |url=https://archive.org/details/localrecordsorh02sykegoog |date=1833 |publisher=J. Sykes |location=Newcaste |page=[https://archive.org/details/localrecordsorh02sykegoog/page/n435 114]}}</ref> however it took time before these improvements were realized.\n\nThere is evidence of a growing number of shipbuilders or boatbuilders being active on the River Wear in the late 17th century: among others, the banking family Goodchilds opened a building yard in 1672 (it eventually closed when the bank went out of business in 1821); and in 1691 one Thomas Burn aged 17 is recorded as having taken over the running of a yard from his mother.<ref name=\"JAMarr\">{{cite web |last1=Marr |first1=J. A. |title=A History of Shipbuilding on the Wear |url=http://www.searlecanada.org/sunderland/sunderland160.html |website=The Sunderland Site |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===18th century===\n[[File:10 Church Street (13920301659).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Rare surviving early 18th-century merchant's house (later used as a warehouse) in Church Street, Sunderland.]]\n\n====River works====\nThe River Wear Commission was formed in 1717 in response to the growing prosperity of Sunderland as a port.<ref name=\"PoSHistory\">{{cite web |title=Port History |url=https://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/port-history |website=Port of Sunderland |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> Under the Board of Commissioners (a committee of local land owners, ship owners, colliery owners and merchants) a succession of civil engineers adapted the natural riverscape to meet the needs of maritime trade and shipbuilding. Their first major harbour work was the construction in stone of the South Pier (later known as the Old South Pier), begun in 1723 with the aim of diverting the river channel away from [[sandbanks]];<ref name=\"Jones2014\">{{cite book|last1=Jones|first1=Robin|title=Lighthouses of the North East Coast|date=2014|publisher=Halsgrove|location=Wellington, Somerset}}</ref> the building of the South Pier continued until 1759. By 1748 the river was being manually dredged.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\" /> A northern counterpart to the South Pier was not yet in place; instead, a temporary breakwater was formed at around this time, consisting of a row of piles driven into the seabed interspersed with old keelboats. From 1786 work began on a more permanent North Pier (which was later known as the Old North Pier): it was formed from a wooden frame, filled with stones and faced with masonry, and eventually extended {{convert|1,500|ft|abbr=on}} into the sea. The work was initially overseen by Robert Stout (the Wear Commissioners' Engineer from 1781 to 1795). In 1794 a lighthouse was built at the seaward end, by which time around half the pier had been enclosed in masonry;<ref name=\"Jones2014\" /> it was completed in 1802.\n\nBy the start of the 18th century the banks of the Wear were described as being studded with small shipyards, as far as the tide flowed.<ref name=\"JAMarr\" /> After 1717, measures having been taken to increase the depth of the river, Sunderland's shipbuilding trade grew substantially (in parallel with its coal exports).<ref name=\"Davis1962,2012\">{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Ralph |title=The Rise of the English Shipping Industry in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=62 |edition=2nd}}</ref> A number of warships were built, alongside many commercial sailing ships. By the middle of the century the town was probably the premier shipbuilding centre in Britain.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Encyclopaedia Britannica: Micropaedia |date=1983}}</ref> By 1788 Sunderland was Britain's fourth largest port (by measure of tonnage) after London, Newcastle and Liverpool; among these it was the leading coal exporter (though it did not rival Newcastle in terms of home coal trade).<ref name=\"Davis1962,2012\" /> Still further growth was driven across the region, towards the end of the century, by London's insatiable demand for coal during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]].<ref name=\"JAMarr\" />\n\nSunderland's third-biggest export, after coal and salt, was glass.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> The town's first modern glassworks were established in the 1690s and the industry grew through the 17th century.<ref name=\"BBCGlassmaking\">{{cite web |title=Glassmaking on Wearside |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2008/02/04/glassmaking_wearside_04022008_feature.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> Its flourishing was aided by trading ships bringing good-quality sand (as [[ballast]]) from [[the Baltic]] and elsewhere which, together with locally available limestone (and coal to fire the furnaces) was a key ingredient in the [[glassmaking]] process. Other industries that developed alongside the river included [[lime burning]] and [[pottery making]] (the town's first commercial pottery manufactory, the Garrison Pottery, had opened in old Sunderland in 1750).<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\n[[File:The Ropery, Sunderland (geograph 3880645).jpg|thumb|right|Grimshaw and Webster's Patent Ropery of 1797: the world's oldest factory for machine-made rope.]]\nThe world's first steam [[dredger]] was built in Sunderland in 1796-7 and put to work on the river the following year.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\">{{cite journal |last1=Skempton |first1=A. W. |title=A History of the Steam Dredger, 1797\u20131830 |journal=Transactions of the Newcomen Society |date=1974 |volume=47 |issue=1 |pages=97\u2013116}}</ref> Designed by Stout's successor as Engineer, Jonathan Pickernell jr (in post from 1795 to 1804), it consisted of a set of 'bag and spoon' dredgers driven by a tailor-made 4-horsepower [[Boulton & Watt]] beam engine. It was designed to dredge to a maximum depth of {{convert|10|ft|abbr=on}} below the waterline and remained in operation until 1804, when its constituent parts were sold as separate lots.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\" /> Onshore, numerous small industries supported the business of the burgeoning port. In 1797 the world's first patent ropery (producing machine-made [[rope]], rather than using a [[ropewalk]]) was built in Sunderland, using a steam-powered hemp-spinning machine which had been devised by a local schoolmaster, Richard Fothergill, in 1793;<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> the ropery building still stands, in the Deptford area of the city.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Websters Ropery (Grade II listing) |num=1207121 |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Urban developments====\n[[File:HolyTrinitySunderland-apse.jpg|thumb|left|Holy Trinity church, built in 1719]]\nIn 1719, the parish of Sunderland was carved from the densely populated east end of Bishopwearmouth by the establishment of a new parish church, [[Holy Trinity Church, Sunderland]] (today also known as Sunderland Old Parish Church). Later, in 1769, St John's Church was built as a [[chapel of ease]] within Holy Trinity parish; built by a local coal fitter, John Thornhill, it stood in Prospect Row to the north-east of the parish church. (St John's was demolished in 1972.)<ref>{{cite web |title=Photo: blue plaque |url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3327052 |website=Geograph |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> By 1720 the port area was completely built up, with large houses and gardens facing the Town Moor and the sea, and labourers' dwellings vying with manufactories alongside the river.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> The three original settlements of Wearmouth (Bishopwearmouth, Monkwearmouth and Sunderland) had begun to combine, driven by the success of the port of Sunderland and salt panning and shipbuilding along the banks of the river. Around this time, Sunderland was known as 'Sunderland-near-the-Sea'.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shegog |first=Eric |url=http://www2.citysun.ac.uk/minster/history.htm |title=Sunderland Minster |publisher=City of Sunderland College |access-date=9 December 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627223638/http://www2.citysun.ac.uk/minster/history.htm |archive-date=27 June 2008  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plan of Sunderland, Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth, 1817.jpg|thumb|right|Early 19th century map showing the 18th-century barracks, battery and piers to the east, with the bridge and nearby 'Pann Field' to the west.]]\nBy 1770 Sunderland had spread westwards along its High Street to join up with Bishopwearmouth.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> In 1796 Bishopwearmouth in turn gained a physical link with Monkwearmouth following the construction of a bridge, the [[Wearmouth Bridge]], which was the world's second iron bridge (after the famous span at [[Ironbridge]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hodstw.org.uk/sunderland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918193101/https://www.hodstw.org.uk/sunderland |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 September 2015 |title=Short History of Sunderland |publisher=www.hodstw.org.uk |date= |access-date=3 June 2016 }}</ref> It was built at the instigation of [[Rowland Burdon (died 1838)|Rowland Burdon]], the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[County Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|County Durham]], and described by [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] as being 'a triumph of the new metallurgy and engineering ingenuity [...] of superb elegance'.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Spanning the river in a single sweep of {{convert|236|ft}}, it was over twice the length of the earlier bridge at Ironbridge but only three-quarters the weight. At the time of building, it was the biggest single-span bridge in the world;<ref>{{cite web |work=Wearside Onliine |title=Sunderland Wearmouth Bridge |url=http://www.wearsideonline.com/Sunderland_Wearmouth_Bridge.html |access-date=24 September 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127114349/http://www.wearsideonline.com/sunderland_wearmouth_bridge.html |archive-date=27 November 2011  }}</ref> and because Sunderland had developed on a plateau above the river, it never suffered from the problem of interrupting the passage of high-masted vessels.\n\n====Defences====\nDuring the [[War of Jenkins' Ear]] a pair of [[Gun battery|gun batteries]] were built (in 1742 and 1745) on the shoreline to the south of the South Pier, to defend the river from attack (a further battery was built on the cliff top in Roker, ten years later).<ref name=\"LimeLand\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland Under Attack |url=http://www.limestonelandscapes.info/media/12325/Sunderland-Under-Attack/pdf/SunderlandUnderAttack.pdf |website=Limestone Landscapes |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> One of the pair was washed away by the sea in 1780, but the other was expanded during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and became known as the Black Cat Battery.<ref name=\"VCHDefPort\">{{cite web |title=Defending the Port |url=https://www.victoriacountyhistory.ac.uk/explore/items/defending-port |website=Victoria County History |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> In 1794 [[Sunderland Barracks]] were built, behind the battery, close to what was then the tip of the headland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandsnortheast.co.uk/Sunderland.html|title=Sunderland : 'Old Sunderland'|publisher=Wearside History|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:Sunderland Harbour, 19th century (Entrance to Sunderland Harbour) by Stuart Henry Bell.jpg|thumb|right|View from the South Pier in the first half of the 19th century.]]\nIn 1802 a new, {{convert|72|ft|abbr=on}} high octagonal stone lighthouse was built on the end of the newly finished North Pier, designed by the chief Engineer Jonathan Pickernell. At the same time he built a lighthouse on the South Pier, which showed a red light (or by day a red flag) when the tide was high enough for ships to pass into the river.<ref name=\"Jones2014\" /> From 1820 Pickernell's lighthouse was lit by gas from its own gasometer.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" /> In 1840 work began to extend the North Pier to {{convert|1,770|ft|abbr=on}} and the following year its lighthouse was moved in one piece, on a wooden cradle, to its new seaward end, remaining lit each night throughout the process.<ref name=\"Jones2014\" />\n\n====Local government====\n[[File:The Exchange Building (14103741331).jpg|thumb|left|The Exchange Building (1812-14) in High Street East.]]\nIn 1809 an [[Act of Parliament]] was passed creating an Improvement Commission, for 'paving, lighting, cleansing, watching and otherwise improving the town of Sunderland';<ref name=\"Burnett1830\">{{cite book |last1=Burnett |first1=James |title=The history of the town and port of Sunderland, and the parishes of Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth |date=1830 |publisher=J. S. Burnett |location=Sunderland |page=44}}</ref> this provided the beginnings of a structure of [[local government]] for the township as a whole.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\">{{cite book |last1=Johnson |first1=Michael |last2=Potts |first2=Graham |title=The Architecture of Sunderland 1700-1914 |date=2013 |publisher=The History Press |location=Stroud, Gloucs.}}</ref> Commissioners were appointed, with the power to levy contributions towards the works detailed in the Act, and in 1812-14 the Exchange Building was built, funded by public subscription, to serve as a combined Town Hall, Watch House, Market Hall, Magistrate's Court, Post Office and News Room. It became a regular gathering place for merchants conducting business, and the public rooms on the first floor were available for public functions when not being used for meetings of the Commissioners. By 1830 the Commissioners had made a number of improvements, ranging from the establishment a police force to installing gas lighting across much of the town.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" />\n\nIn other aspects, however, [[Local government]] was still divided between the three parishes (Holy Trinity Church, Sunderland, [[Sunderland Minster|St. Michael's, Bishopwearmouth]], and [[St Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth|St. Peter's, Monkwearmouth]]) and when [[cholera]] broke out in 1831, the \"select vestrymen\", as the church councilmen were called, were unable to cope with the [[epidemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/longview/longview_20030415.shtml|title=BBC Diary of an Epidemic|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=BBC website|year=2003}}</ref> Sunderland, a main trading port at the time, was the first British town to be struck with the 'Indian cholera' epidemic.<ref>''Diary of an Epidemic (Cholera)'', [[BBC Radio 4]], [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/longview/longview_20030415.shtml]</ref> The first victim, William Sproat, died on 23 October 1831. Sunderland was put into quarantine, and the port was blockaded, but in December of that year the disease spread to [[Gateshead]] and from there, it rapidly made its way across the country, killing an estimated 32,000 people; among those to die was Sunderland's Naval hero [[Jack Crawford (sailor)|Jack Crawford]]. (The novel ''The Dress Lodger'' by American author [[Sheri Holman]] is set in Sunderland during the epidemic.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Jack%20Crawford.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011202836/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Jack%20Crawford.pdf|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 October 2007|title=Who was Jack Crawford?|access-date=3 April 2008 |publisher=Sunderland Council |year=2005|format=PDF }}</ref>\n\nDemands for [[democracy]] and organised town government saw the three parishes incorporated as the Borough of Sunderland in 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2003/3/10/100809.html|title=Burning Questions|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=The Northern Echo|year=2003}}</ref> Later, the Sunderland Borough Act of 1851 abolished the Improvement Commission and vested its powers in the new Corporation.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" />\n\n====Coal, staiths, railways and docks====\n[[File:Sunderland dock (opening 1850).jpg|thumb|right|The opening of Hudson Dock on 20 June 1850; on the left the staiths of the York, Newcastle & Berwick Railway.]]\nIn the early nineteenth century 'the three great proprietors of collieries upon the Wear [were] [[Lord Durham]], the [[Marquis of Londonderry]] and the [[Hetton-le-Hole|Hetton]] Company'.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" /> In 1822 the [[Hetton colliery railway]] was opened, linking the company's collieries with [[staith]]s ('Hetton Staiths') on the riverside at Bishopwearmouth, where [[coal drops]] delivered the coal directly into waiting ships. Engineered by [[George Stephenson]], it was the first railway in the world to be operated without animal power, and at the time (albeit briefly) was the longest railway in the world.<ref name=\"ETHetColRly\">{{cite web |title=Hetton Colliery Railway |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1464 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref> At the same time Lord Durham began establishing rail links to an adjacent set of staiths ('Lambton Staiths'). Lord Londonderry, on the other hand, continued conveying his coal downriver on keels; but he was working on establishing his own separate port down the coast at [[Seaham Harbour]].\n\n[[File:North Dock, Sunderland (19873625392).jpg|thumb|left|North Dock in 1957; the steam-powered wood yard to the right remained operational till 1990.<ref>{{cite web |title=Armstrong, Addison & Co, Timber Merchants, Sunderland |url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/7046356b-9144-4a29-a0e7-fbaf8170d2c4 |website=The National Archives |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>]]\nAlthough the volume of coal exports were increasing, there was a growing concern that without the establishment of a purpose-built dock Sunderland would start losing trade to Newcastle and [[Hartlepool]].<ref name=\"ETNthDock\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland North Dock, site of |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1133 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The colliery rail links were on the south side of the river, but Sir [[Sir Hedworth Williamson, 7th Baronet|Hedworth Williamson]], who owned much of the land on the north bank, seized the initiative. He formed the Wearmouth Dock Company in 1832, obtained a Royal Charter for establishing a dock at Monkwearmouth riverside, and engaged no less a figure than [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]] to provide designs (not only for docks but also for a double-deck [[suspension bridge]] to provide a rail link to the opposite side of the river). Building of the dock went ahead (albeit the smallest of Brunel's proposals) but not of the bridge; the resulting North Dock, opened in 1837, soon proved too small at {{convert|6|acre}}, and it suffered through lack of a direct rail link to the colliery lines south of the Wear (instead, it would be linked, by way of the [[Brandling Junction Railway]] from 1839, to collieries in the Gateshead area).<ref name=\"ETNthDock\" />\n\nAlso in Monkwearmouth, further upstream, work began in 1826 on sinking a pit in the hope of reaching the seams of coal (even though, at this location, they were deep underground). Seven years later, coal was struck at 180 fathoms;<ref name=\"DMM\">{{cite web |title=Wearmouth Colliery |url=http://www.dmm.org.uk/colliery/w001.htm |website=Durham Mining Museum |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> digging deeper, the Bensham seam was found the following year at 267 fathoms and in 1835 [[Wearmouth Colliery]], which was then the deepest mine in the world, began producing coal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wearmouth Colliery |url=https://www.aditnow.co.uk/documents/Wearmouth-Coal-Mine/Wearmouth-Colliery.pdf |website=AditNow: the site for mine explorers and mining historians |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> When the superior Hutton seam was reached, at a still greater depth in 1846, the mine (which had begun as a speculative enterprise by Messrs Pemberton and Thompson) began to be profitable.\n\n[[File:Sunderland Docks Office (13920362930).jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland Dock Company offices (1850 by John Murray) and the [[Gladstone Bridge (Sunderland)|Gladstone Swing Bridge]] of 1874.]]\nMeanwhile, south of the river, the [[Durham & Sunderland Railway]] Co. built a railway line across the Town Moor and established a passenger terminus there in 1836. In 1847 the line was bought by [[George Hudson]]'s [[York and Newcastle Railway]]. Hudson, nicknamed 'The Railway King', was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sunderland (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland]] and was already involved in a scheme to build a dock in the area. In 1846 he had formed the [[Sunderland Docks|Sunderland Dock Company]], which received parliamentary approval for the construction of a dock between the South Pier and Hendon Bay.<ref name=\"SundEcho16.3.17\">{{cite web |title=On the waterfront: First sea link with the docks |url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/on-the-waterfront-first-sea-link-with-the-docks-357798 |website=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The engineer overseeing the project was John Murray; the foundation stone for the entrance basin was laid in February 1848, and by the end of the year excavation of the new dock was largely complete, the spoil being used in the associated [[land reclamation]] works. Lined with limestone and entered from the river by way of a [[half tide dock|half tide basin]], the dock (later named Hudson Dock) was formally opened by Hudson on 20 June 1850.<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland South Docks |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1134 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> Most of the dockside to the west was occupied with coal staiths linked to the railway line, but there was also a warehouse and granary built at the northern end by [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]] in 1856 (this, along with a second warehouse dating from the 1860s, was demolished in 1992).<ref>{{cite web |title=Nos 1 & 2 Warehouses, North Hudson Docks, Sunderland, Tyne & Wear |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/services-skills/education/educational-images/nos-1-2-warehouses-north-hudson-docks-sunderland-tyne-wear-3055 |website=Historic England |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:An Aerial view of Sunderland (9105585273).jpg|thumb|left|River Wear (top) in 1969, with Hudson Dock, Hendon Dock and associated rail links to the south.]]\nIn 1850-56 a half-tidal sea-entrance was constructed at the south-east corner of the dock, protected by a pair of breakwaters, to allow larger ships to enter the dock direct from the [[North Sea]]. At the same time (1853\u201355) Hudson Dock itself was extended southwards and deepened, and, alongside the entrance basin to the north, the first of a pair of public [[graving docks]] was built.<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\" /> In 1854 the Londonderry, Seaham & Sunderland Railway opened, linking the Londonderry and South Hetton collieries to a separate set of staiths at Hudson Dock South. It also provided a passenger service from Sunderland to Seaham Harbour.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colliery Railways: Londonderry Seaham & Sunderland 1854/55 |url=https://durhamrecordsonline.com/library/colliery-railways-londonderry-seaham-sunderland-185455/ |website=Durham Records Online |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1859 the docks were purchased by the River Wear Commissioners. Under Thomas Meik as engineer the docks were further extended with the construction of Hendon Dock to the south (1864\u201367). (Hendon Dock was entered via Hudson Dock South, but in 1870 it too was provided with a half-tidal sea-entrance providing direct access from the North Sea.) Under Meik's successor, Henry Hay Wake, Hudson Dock was further enlarged and the entrances were improved:<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\" /> in 1875 lock gates were installed (along with a [[swing bridge]]) at the river entrance, to allow entry at all states of the tide; they were powered by [[hydraulic machinery]], installed by [[Sir William Armstrong]] in the adjacent dock office building.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Swing-bridge, lock and walls of north end of Dock |num=1207097 |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> Similarly, a new [[sea lock]] was constructed at the south-east entrance in 1877\u201380.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Swing-bridge at east side with ashlar walls |num=1279892 |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The breakwater (known as the 'Northeast Pier') which protected the sea entrance to the docks was provided with a lighthouse ({{convert|29|ft|abbr=on}} high and of lattice construction, since demolished) which [[Chance Brothers]] equipped with a [[Fifth order Fresnel lens|fifth-order optic]] and clockwork [[Occulting Light|occulting mechanism]] in 1888;<ref name=\"Chance1919\">{{cite book |last1=Chance |first1=James Frederick |title=A History of the Firm of Chance Brothers & Co. |date=2018 |publisher=Society of Glass Manufacturers |location=Sheffield |page=182}}</ref> it displayed a [[sector light]]: white indicating the fairway and red indicating submerged hazards.<ref>{{cite book |title=British Islands Pilot, vol. VII |publisher=Government Printing Office |location=Washington DC |page=299}}</ref>\n\nBy 1889 two million tons of coal per year was passing through the dock.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tyne and Wear HER(2874): Sunderland, South Dock (Hudson Dock) - Details |url=https://twsitelines.info/SMR/2874 |website=SiteLines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The eastern wharves, opposite the coal staiths, were mainly occupied by saw mills and timber yards, with large open spaces given over to the storage of [[pit prop]]s for use in the mines;<ref>[[Commons:File:Insurance Plan of Sunderland; sheet 13-1 (BL 148858).tiff|Map, 1894]]</ref> while to the south of Hendon Dock, the Wear Fuel Works distilled [[coal tar]] to produce pitch, oil and other products.<ref>[[Commons:File:Insurance Plan of Sunderland; sheet 14-1 (BL 148860).tiff|Map detail, 1894]]</ref>\n\nAfter completion of the dock works, H. H. Wake embarked on the construction of [[Roker Pier]] (part of a scheme to protect the river approach by creating an outer harbour). Protection of a different kind was provided by the Wave Basin Battery, armed with four [[RML 80 pounder 5 ton gun]]s, constructed just inside the Old South Pier in 1874.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Wave Basin Battery adjacent to old South Pier |num=1207135 |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIncreasing industrialisation had prompted affluent residents to move away from the old port area, with several settling in the suburban terraces of the Fawcett Estate and [[Mowbray Park]]. The area around Fawcett Street itself increasingly functioned as the civic and commercial town centre. In 1848 George Hudson's [[York, Newcastle and Berwick Railway]] built a passenger terminus, [[Monkwearmouth Station Museum|Monkwearmouth Station]], just north of Wearmouth Bridge; and south of the river another passenger terminus, in Fawcett Street, in 1853. Later, [[Thomas Elliot Harrison]] (chief engineer to the [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]) made plans to carry the railway across the river; the [[Wearmouth Railway Bridge]] (reputedly 'the largest Hog-Back iron girder bridge in the world') opened in 1879.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> In 1886-90 a new Town Hall was built in Fawcett Street, just to the east of the railway station, designed by [[Brightwen Binyon]].<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" />\n\n====\"The greatest shipbuilding port in the world\"====\n[[File:William Pile's Shipyard, North Sands, Sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|[[William Pile (shipbuilder)|William Pile]]'s Shipyard at North Sands, {{circa|1830}}; described as the greatest ship designer of his age, he built more than 100 ships in wood and almost as many in iron.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\">{{cite web |title=Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 2 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/6957/11-Shipbuilding-on-the-Wear-Part-2/pdf/Shipbuilding_on_the_Wear_Part_2.pdf |website=Sunderland Council |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>]]\nSunderland's shipbuilding industry continued to grow through most of the 19th century, becoming the town's dominant industry and a defining part of its identity.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> By 1815 it was 'the leading shipbuilding port for wooden trading vessels' with 600 ships constructed that year across 31 different yards.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\">{{cite web |title=Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 1 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/6958/10-Shipbuilding-on-the-Wear-Part-1/pdf/10_Shipbuilding_Part_1.pdf |website=Sunderland Council |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> By 1840 the town had 76 shipyards and between 1820 and 1850 the number of ships being built on the Wear increased fivefold. From 1846 to 1854 almost a third of the UK's ships were built in Sunderland, and in 1850 the ''Sunderland Herald'' proclaimed the town to be the greatest shipbuilding port in the world.<ref name=\"Clarke1997\">{{cite book |last1=Clarke |first1=Joseph Finbar |title=Building Ships on the North-East Coast |date=1997 |publisher=Bewick Press |page=93}}</ref>\n\nDuring the century the size of ships being built increased and technologies evolved: in 1852 the first iron ship was launched on Wearside, built by marine engineer [[George Clark & NEM|George Clark]] in partnership with shipbuilder John Barkes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunderland, Hudson Dock, George Clark Engine Works - Details |url=https://twsitelines.info/SMR/16317 |website=SiteLines |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref> Thirty years later Sunderland's ships were being built in steel<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> (the last wooden ship having been launched in 1880).<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" /> As the century progressed, the shipyards on the Wear decreased in number on the one hand, but increased in size on the other, so as to accommodate the increasing scale and complexity of ships being built.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" />\n\nShipyards founded in the 19th century, and still operational in the 20th, included:<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\" />\n* Sir James Laing & Sons (established by Philip Laing at Deptford in 1818, renamed Sir James Laing & sons in 1898)\n* [[Austin & Pickersgill|S. P. Austin]] (established in 1826 at Monkwearmouth, moving across the river to a site alongside Wearmouth Bridge in 1866)\n* [[Bartram & Sons]] (established at [[North Hylton|Hylton]] in 1837, moved to South Dock in 1871)\n* [[William Doxford & Sons]] (established at Cox Green in 1840, moved to [[Pallion]] in 1857)\n* [[Austin & Pickersgill|William Pickersgill]]'s (established at [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] in 1845)\n* [[J. L. Thompson & Sons]] (yard established at North Sands by Robert Thompson in 1846, taken over by his son Joseph in 1860, another son (also Robert) having established his own yard at Southwick in 1854)\n* [[John Crown & Sons]] (yard established at Monkwearmouth by Luke Crown (or Crone) by 1807, taken over by his grandson Jackie in 1854)\n* [[Short Brothers of Sunderland|Short Brothers]] (established by George Short in 1850, moved to Pallion in 1866)\n* [[John Priestman|Sir J Priestman]] (established at Southwick in 1882)\n\nAlongside the shipyards, marine engineering works were established from the 1820s onwards, initially providing engines for [[paddle steamers]]; in 1845 a ship named ''Experiment'' was the first of many to be converted to [[screw steamer|steam screw propulsion]].<ref name=\"JAMarr\" /> Demand for steam-powered vessels increased during the [[Crimean War]]; nonetheless, sailing ships continued to be built, including fast [[fully-rigged]] [[composite ship|composite]]-built [[Clipper|clippers]], including the [[City of Adelaide (1864)|''City of Adelaide'']] in 1864 and [[Torrens (clipper ship)|''Torrens'']] (the last such vessel ever built), in 1875.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\" />\n\n====Other industries====\n[[File:Commemorative plates Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens (8096466202).jpg|thumb|left|Commemorative plate, with pink '[[lustreware|splash lustre]]', depicting Wearmouth Bridge of 1796.]]\nBy the middle of the century glassmaking was at its height on Wearside. [[Hartley Wood and Co|James Hartley & Co.]], established in Sunderland in 1836, grew to be the largest glassworks in the country and (having patented an innovative production technique for [[rolled plate glass]]) produced much of the glass used in the construction of [[the Crystal Palace]] in 1851.<ref name=\"SundIndust\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland Industries |url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/sunderland-industries/ |website=England's North East |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> A third of all UK-manufactured plate glass was produced at Hartley's by this time.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> Other manufacturers included the Cornhill Flint Glassworks (established at Southwick in 1865), which went on to specialise in [[pressed glass]], as did the Wear Flint Glassworks (which had originally been established in 1697).<ref name=\"BBCGlassmaking\" /> In addition to the plate glass and pressed glass manufacturers there were 16 bottle works on the Wear in the 1850s, with the capacity to produce between 60 and 70,000 bottles a day.<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\nLocal potteries also flourished in the mid-19th century, again making use of raw materials (white clay and stone) being brought into Sunderland as ballast on ships. Sunderland pottery was exported across Europe, with [[Sunderland Lustreware]] proving particularly popular in the home market; however the industry sharply declined later in the century due to foreign competition, and the largest remaining manufacturer (Southwick Pottery) closed in 1897.<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\n====Victoria Hall Disaster====\n{{Main|Victoria Hall disaster}}\n[[File:Victoria Hall Memorial.png|upright|thumbnail|right|The memorial to the Victims of the Victoria Hall Disaster in Mowbray Park]]\nVictoria Hall was a large [[concert hall]] on Toward Road facing [[Mowbray Park]]. The hall was the scene of a [[Tragedy (event)|tragedy]] on 16 June 1883 when 183 children died.<ref name=\"vic\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland's Victoria Hall Stampede |url=http://www.north-country.co.uk/victoria.htm |work=North Country Web |access-date=27 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108182434/http://www.north-country.co.uk/victoria.htm |archive-date=8 January 2007  }}</ref> During a [[variety show]], children rushed towards a staircase for treats.<ref>{{cite web |title=Victims of the Victoria Hall Calamity |url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/DUR/Sunderland/VictoriaHall.html |work=Genuki |accessdate=27 January 2007}}</ref> At the bottom of the staircase, the door had been opened inward and bolted in such a way as to leave only a gap wide enough for one child to pass at a time.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Victoria Hall Disaster 1883 |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Victorian%20Hall%20Disaster.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711002529/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Victorian%20Hall%20Disaster.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 July 2007 |work=City of Sunderland Library |access-date=27 January 2007|format=PDF }}</ref> The children surged down the stairs and those at the front were [[Human crush|trapped and crushed]] by the weight of the crowd behind them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/GIVE-THEM-A-FITTING-MEMORIAL.589296.jp|title=Give them a fitting memorial|newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]]|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Carol Roberton|year=2000}}</ref>\n\nThe [[asphyxiation]] of 183 children aged between three and 14 is the worst disaster of its kind in British history.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Victoria Hall Disaster of 1883 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A882173 |work=BBC h2g2 |accessdate=26 May 2007}}</ref> The memorial, a grieving mother holding a dead child, is located in Mowbray Park inside a protective canopy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Toy Tragedy Children Honoured|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1925815.stm|work=BBC News|date=12 May 2002 |accessdate=27 January 2007}}</ref> Newspaper reports triggered a mood of national outrage and an inquiry recommended that public venues be fitted with a minimum number of outward opening [[emergency exit]]s, which led to the invention of 'push bar' emergency doors. This law remains in force. Victoria Hall remained in use until 1941 when it was destroyed by a [[Nazi Germany|German]] bomb.<ref>{{cite book|first=Bryan |last=Talbot |authorlink=Bryan Talbot |title=Alice in Sunderland: An Entertainment |year=2007 |publisher=Jonathon Cape |location=London|isbn=0-224-08076-8|pages=58\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===20th and 21st centuries===\n[[File:Deptford, Sunderland 14.9.1917.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland in 1917]]\nThe public transport network was enhanced in 1900 - 1919 with an [[Sunderland Corporation Tramways|electric tram system]]. The trams were gradually replaced by buses during the 1940s before being completely axed in 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeastfilmarchive.com/videos/12751/going-places-story-sunderland-transport|title=Yorkshire Film Archive -|website=Northeastfilmarchive.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> In 1909 the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] was built, linking [[Deptford, Sunderland|Deptford]] and [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SINE Project: Structure details for Queen Alexandra Bridge |work=University of Newcastle upon Tyne |url=http://sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=1242 |access-date=12 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125023527/http://sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=1242 |archive-date=25 January 2009  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Women working in the shipyard (10817948524).jpg|thumb|right|King George V visiting women workers at Sir James Laing & Sons shipyard, 15 June 1917.]]\nThe First World War led to a notable increase in shipbuilding but also resulted in the town being targeted by a [[Zeppelin]] raid in 1916.  The Monkwearmouth area was struck on 1 April 1916 and 22 lives were lost.  Many citizens also served in the armed forces during this period, over 25,000 men from a population of 151,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson |first=Tony |url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/monkwearmouth-station-museum-sunderland-hosts-7184023 |title=Monkwearmouth Station Museum in Sunderland hosts First World War poster exhibition |publisher=The Journal |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the First World War, and on through the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Great Depression]] of the 1930s, shipbuilding dramatically declined: the number of shipyards on the Wear went from fifteen in 1921 to six in 1937.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" /> The small yards of J. Blumer & Son (at North Dock) and the Sunderland Shipbuilding Co. Ltd. (at Hudson Dock) both closed in the 1920s, and other yards were closed down by [[National Shipbuilders Securities]] in the 1930s (including Osbourne, Graham & Co., way upriver at North Hylton, Robert Thompson & Sons at Southwick, and the 'overflow' yards operated by [[Swan, Hunter & Wigham Richardson]] and [[William Gray & Company|William Gray & Co.]]).<ref>[http://www.searlecanada.org/sunderland/sunderland037.html Map, with dates]</ref>\n\n[[File:Wearmouth Bridge to the Sea 2nd March 1967.jpg|thumbnail|left|Sunderland viewed from above in 1967]]\nWith the outbreak of [[World War II]] in 1939, Sunderland was a key target of the [[Germany|German]] [[Luftwaffe]], who claimed the lives of 267 people<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/ten-interesting-facts-about-sunderland-1342150|title=Ten interesting facts about Sunderland|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=1 January 2012|publisher=|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> in the town, caused damage or destruction to 4,000 homes, and devastated local industry. After the war, more housing was developed. The town's boundaries expanded in 1967 when neighbouring [[Ryhope]], [[Silksworth]], [[Herrington]], [[South Hylton]] and [[Castletown, Tyne and Wear|Castletown]] were incorporated into Sunderland.\n\nDuring the second half of the 20th century shipbuilding and coalmining declined; shipbuilding ended in 1988 and coalmining in 1993. At the worst of the unemployment crisis up to 20% of the local workforce were unemployed in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U4JWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NEENAAAAIBAJ&pg=1235,602714&dq=britain+million+unemployment&hl=en|title=The Leader-Post - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:NMUK.JPG|thumb|right|400px|Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK Ltd in Sunderland. Factory complex, including wind turbines, taken from Penshaw Monument]]\nAs the former heavy industries declined, new industries were developed (including electronic, chemical, paper and motor manufacture) and the service sector expanded during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/A-good-little-runner-.1616180.jp|title=A Good Little Runner|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Kevin Clark|year=2006|work=Sunderland Echo}}</ref> In 1986 Japanese car manufacturer [[Nissan]] opened its [[Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK]] factory in Washington, which has since gone on to become the UK's largest car factory.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/car-manufacturers/nissan/9753733/The-history-of-Nissans-Sunderland-factory.html |title=The history of Nissan's Sunderland factory |work=The Daily telegraph |location=London |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1990, the banks of the Wear were regenerated with the creation of housing, retail parks and business centres on former shipbuilding sites. Alongside the creation of the [[National Glass Centre]] the [[University of Sunderland]] has built a new campus on the [[St Peter's, Sunderland|St. Peter's site]]. The clearance of the [[Vaux Breweries]] site on the north west fringe of the city centre created a further opportunity for development in the city centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Centre-will-be-a-glass.817088.jp|title=Centre will be a glass act again|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Laura White|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|title=Sir Tom gets own campus!|accessdate=3 April 2008|work=Sunderland Echo|year=2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201083138/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|archive-date=1 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/HAVE-YOUR-SAY-ON-VAUX.589897.jp|title=Have your say on Vaux site|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2003}}</ref>\n\nSunderland received city status in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.localhistories.org/sunderland.html|title=A History of Sunderland|work=localhistories.org}}</ref> Like many cities, Sunderland comprises a number of areas with their own distinct histories, [[Fulwell, Sunderland|Fulwell]], Monkwearmouth, [[Roker]], and [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] on the northern side of the Wear, and Bishopwearmouth and Hendon to the south. On 24 March 2004, the city adopted St. Benedict Biscop as its [[patron saint]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Saint-that-nice--our.918420.jp|title=Saint that nice \u2013 our own patron|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2005}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1937wembleylapofhonour.jpg|thumb|left|FA cup winners, Wembley 1937.]]\nThe 20th century saw [[Sunderland A.F.C.]] established as the Wearside area's greatest claim to sporting fame. Founded in 1879 as Sunderland and District Teachers A.F.C. by [[schoolmaster]] [[James Allan (footballer, born 1857)|James Allan]], Sunderland joined [[The Football League]] for the [[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391 season]]. By 1936 the club had been league champions on five occasions. They won their first [[FA Cup]] in [[1937 FA Cup Final|1937]], but their only post-[[World War II]] major honour came in 1973 when they won a [[1973 FA Cup Final|second FA Cup]]. They have had a checkered history and dropped into the old third division for a season and been relegated thrice from the [[Premier League]], twice with the lowest points ever,<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/HonoursDetail/0,,10281~1690850,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704093811/http://www.safc.com/page/HonoursDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1690850%2C00.html|date=4 July 2011}}</ref> earning the club a reputation as a [[yo-yo club]]. After 99 years at the historic [[Roker Park]] stadium,<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0,,10281~1697691,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901082800/http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1697691%2C00.html|date=1 September 2010}}</ref> the club moved to the 42,000-seat [[Stadium of Light]] on the banks of the River Wear in 1997. At the time, it was the largest stadium built by an English football club since the 1920s, and has since been expanded to hold nearly 50,000 seated spectators.<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0,,10281~1697689,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901082756/http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1697689%2C00.html|date=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMany fine old buildings remain despite the bombing that occurred during World War II.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rare images recall wartime blitz |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/4434123.stm |accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=12 April 2005}}</ref> Religious buildings include Holy Trinity Church, built in 1719 for an independent Sunderland, St. Michael's Church, built as Bishopwearmouth Parish Church and now known as Sunderland Minster and St. Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth, part of which dates from AD 674, and was the original monastery. St. Andrew's Roker, known as the \"Cathedral of the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]\", contains work by [[William Morris]], [[Ernest Gimson]] and [[Eric Gill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/Roker39s-39cathedral-of-arts-and.1392538.jp|title=Roker's 'cathedral of arts and crafts' |accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Sarah Stoner |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2006}}</ref> [[St Mary's Church, Sunderland|St Mary's Catholic Church]] is the earliest surviving Gothic revival church in the city.<ref>[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-391394-church-of-st-mary-and-attached-railings-#.VmxkFxorKqA Church of St Mary and Attached Railings, Sunderland] from British listed buildings, retrieved 12 December 2015</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Borough of Sunderland COA.png|upright|thumb|The [[Sunderland coat of arms|coat of arms of the former County Borough of Sunderland]].]]\n[[File:Sunderlandciviccentre2.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland Civic Centre (right background) with Mowbray Park to the left. This road was the route of the old [[A19 road|A19]] until the 1970s {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}.]]\nSunderland was created a [[municipal borough]] of [[County Durham]] in 1835. Under the [[Local Government Act 1888]], it was given the status of a County Borough, independent from [[county council]] control. In 1974, under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the county borough was abolished and its area combined with that of other districts to form the Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland in Tyne and Wear. In 1986, [[Tyne and Wear County Council]] was abolished, and Sunderland became a [[unitary authority]], once again independent from county council control. The metropolitan borough was granted [[city status in the United Kingdom|city status]] after winning a competition in 1992 to celebrate the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen's]] 40th year on the throne. The population of the city taken at the 2011 Census was 275,506.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1946157068|title=Sunderland Local Authority|fewer-links=y|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough it is a [[unitary authority]], many public services in the [[City of Sunderland]] are provided in cooperation with neighbouring local authorities. For instance, the [[Northumbria Police]] covers the five (now independent) boroughs of Tyne and Wear, plus the neighbouring county of [[Northumberland]]. The [[Tyne and Wear Fire and Rescue Service]] covers the five boroughs only.\n\nSince 2014, the [[City of Sunderland]] has been a member of the [[North East Combined Authority]], which is an alliance of the five former boroughs of [[Tyne and Wear]] and the neighbouring counties of [[Northumberland]] and [[County Durham]]. However, Sunderland is still a unitary authority; [[combined authority|combined authorities]] are voluntary alliances, in which local authorities agree to pool certain responsibilities and receive delegated functions from central government. For instance, the [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]], better known by its brand name Nexus, is now an executive body of the [[North East Combined Authority]].\n\n[[File:Durham - John Speed Map.jpg|thumb|alt=Historic map of County Durham.|Historic map of County Durham. Sunderland was part of [[County Durham]] until the local government changes in 1974. The [[River Wear]] is seen here passing through the city of [[Durham, England|Durham]], before reaching the North Sea in Sunderland.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Timeline\n! Years      !! Title                !! Parent or alliance\n|-\n| 674 - 866 || Monkwearmouth (or Wearmouth) || [[Kingdom of Northumbria]]<ref>Monkwearmouth was settled shortly after the unification of the kingdoms of [[Bernicia]] and [[Deira]] into [[Northumbria]] in AD 654.</ref><ref>In AD 866, [[Great Heathen Army|Vikings]] invaded southern Northumbria (formerly [[Deira]]), creating the kingdom of [[Jorvik]] (York). During this period, [[Jorvik]] made numerous incursions into [[Bernicia]] (the part of Northumbria north of the [[River Tees|Tees]]), and largely subjugated the [[Angles|Anglian]] kingdom.</ref>\n|-\n| 883 - 930 || Monkwearmouth (or Wearmouth) || Liberty of [[Saint Cuthbert]]'s Land<ref>Saint Cuthbert's Land, between the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] and the [[River Tees|Tees]], became a distinct political entity in AD 883. [[Wessex]] united with [[Northumbria]] and defeated [[Jorvik]] in AD 927, creating the [[Kingdom of England]].</ref>\n|-\n| 930 - 995 || Monkwearmouth and Bishopwearmouth || Liberty of [[Saint Cuthbert]]'s Land\n|-\n| 995 - 1179 || Monkwearmouth and Bishopwearmouth || [[Liberty of Durham]]<ref>[[Durham, England|Durham]] was founded in AD 995.</ref>\n|-\n| 1179 - 1293 || Sunderland || [[Liberty of Durham]]\n|-\n| 1293 - 1835 || Sunderland || [[County Palatine of Durham]]\n|-\n| 1835 - 1888 || Municipal Borough of Sunderland    || [[County Durham]]<ref>Durham ceased to be a [[county palatine]] in 1836.</ref>\n|-\n| 1888 - 1974 || County Borough of Sunderland       || [[County Durham]]\n|-\n| 1974 - 1992 || Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland || [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|-\n| 1992 - 2014 || City of Sunderland                 || [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|-\n| 2014\u2013present || City of Sunderland              || [[North East Combined Authority]] (an alliance)\n|}\n\nSunderland has the motto of ''Nil Desperandum Auspice Deo'' or ''Under God's guidance we may never despair''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/pages/Press/pritem.asp?Id=10190|title=STILL TIME TO SEE SUNDERLAND SHINE|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Sunderland Council|year=2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124205855/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/pages/Press/pritem.asp?Id=10190|archive-date=24 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{wide image|Sunderland panoramic riverside.jpg|900px|Sunderland riverside at sunset}}\n{{See also|List of places in Sunderland}}\n[[File:Wearmouth Bridge, Sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|The Wearmouth Bridge (right) and railway bridge (left). This road was the route of the old A19, now it is the A1018.]]\nMuch of the city is located on a low range of hills running parallel to the coast. On average, it is around 80 metres [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. Sunderland is divided by the River Wear which passes through the middle of the city in a deeply incised valley, part of which is known as the Hylton gorge. The three road bridges connecting the north and south portions of the city are the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] at Pallion, the [[Wearmouth Bridge]] just to the north of the city centre and most recently the [[Northern Spire Bridge]] between Castletown and Pallion. To the west of the city, the [[Hylton Viaduct]] carries the [[A19 road|A19]] dual-carriageway over the Wear (see map below).\n\nMost of the suburbs of Sunderland are situated towards the west of the city centre with 70% of its population living on the south side of the river and 30% on the north side. The city extends to the seafront at Hendon and Ryhope in the south and [[Seaburn]] in the north.\n\n===Suburbs===\nSome, mainly local authority-built, Sunderland suburbs have most streets beginning with the same letter:\n* '''A''': [[Farringdon, Sunderland|Farringdon]]\n* '''B''': [[Town End Farm]] and [[Barnes, Sunderland|Barnes]]\n* '''C''': [[Hylton Castle (suburb)|Hylton Castle]]\n* '''D''': Dykelands Road area of [[Seaburn]]\n* '''E''': [[Carley Hill]]\n* '''F''': [[Ford Estate]]\n* '''G''': [[Grindon, Sunderland|Grindon]]\n* '''H''': [[Hylton Lane]] / [[Havelock, Tyne and Wear|Havelock]] / Humbledon\n* '''J''': [[John Street, Sunderland]]\n* '''K''': [[Downhill, Sunderland|Downhill]]\n* '''M''': [[Moorside, Sunderland|Moorside]] and [[Millfield, Tyne and Wear]]\n* '''P''': [[Pennywell]] and [[Plains Farm]] and [[Pallion]]\n* '''R''': [[Redhouse, Sunderland|Red House]]\n* '''S''': [[Springwell, Sunderland|Springwell]], [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]]\n* '''T''': [[Thorney Close]]\n* '''W''': [[Witherwack]]\n\nIn Marley Pots, the streets are all associated with trees, e.g. Maplewood, Elmwood etc.\nIn Millfield, the streets are all associated with plants, e.g. Chester, Fern, Rose, Hyacinth etc.\n\n===Definitions of Sunderland===\nThere are two definitions for Sunderland. The smaller Urban Subdivision follows the boundaries of what is considered the city itself, however, the USD alone has not been given city status. The larger metropolitan borough contains other settlements with a separate identity such as [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], but has been given official city status, with all individual settlements being the responsibility of Sunderland city council.\n\n===Green belt===\n{{main|North East Green Belt}}\nThe town is bounded by the Tyne & Wear Green Belt,<ref name=\"sunderland-belt\">{{cite web|title=GREEN BELT REVIEW STAGE 1 \u2013 CORE STRATEGY GROWTH OPTIONS STAGE, MARCH 2016 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/18571/SD43-Sunderland-Green-Belt-Review-Stage-1-Core-Strategy-Growth-Options-Stge-March-2016-/pdf/SD43_Sunderland_Green_Belt_Review_Stage_1_-_Core_Strategy_Growth_Options_Stage_March_2016.pdf|website=www.sunderland.gov.uk}}</ref> with its portion in much of its surrounding rural area of the borough. It is a part of the local [[development plan]], of which its stated aims<ref name=\"sunderland-belt\"/> are as follows:\n\n''A Green Belt will be maintained which will:-''\n\n''(i) Check the unrestricted sprawl of the built up area of Sunderland;''<br/>\n''(ii) Assist in safeguarding the city\u2019s countryside from further encroachment;''<br/>\n''(iii) Assist in the regeneration of the urban area of the city;''<br/>\n''(iv) Preserve the setting and special character of Springwell Village;''<br/>\n''(iv) Prevent the merging of Sunderland with Tyneside, Washington, Houghton-le-Spring and Seaham, and the merging of Shiney Row with Washington, Chester-le-Street and Bournmoor.''\n\nIn the Sunderland borough boundary, as well as the aforementioned areas, landscape features and facilities such as much of the River Don and Wear basins, the George Washington Hotel Golf and Spa complex, Sharpley Golf Course, Herrington Country Park, Houghton Quarry and Penshaw Hill are within the green belt area.\n\n==Climate==\nSunderland has a temperate [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfb'').  Its location in the [[rain shadow]] of the [[Pennines]], as well as other mountain ranges to the west, such as those of the [[Lake District]] and southwestern Scotland, make Sunderland one of the least rainy cities of Northern England. The climate is heavily moderated by the adjacent [[North Sea]], giving it cool summers, and winters that are mild considering its latitude. The closest weather station is in [[Tynemouth]], about {{convert|8|mi|km}} north of Sunderland. As a result, Sunderland's coastline is likely slightly milder given the more southerly position. Another relatively nearby weather station in [[Durham, England#Climate|Durham]] has warmer summer days and colder winter nights courtesy of its inland position.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Tynemouth, 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n| Jan high C = 7.2\n| Feb high C = 7.3\n| Mar high C = 9.0\n| Apr high C = 10.3\n| May high C = 12.7\n| Jun high C = 15.6\n| Jul high C = 18.1\n| Aug high C = 18.1\n| Sep high C = 16.1\n| Oct high C = 13.2\n| Nov high C = 9.7\n| Dec high C = 7.4\n|year high C = 12.1\n| Jan low C = 2.2\n| Feb low C = 2.2\n| Mar low C = 3.3\n| Apr low C = 4.8\n| May low C = 7.2\n| Jun low C = 10.0\n| Jul low C = 12.3\n| Aug low C = 12.3\n| Sep low C = 10.4\n| Oct low C = 7.7\n| Nov low C = 4.9\n| Dec low C = 2.5\n|year low C = 6.7\n| Jan precipitation mm = 45.5\n| Feb precipitation mm = 37.8\n| Mar precipitation mm = 43.9\n| Apr precipitation mm = 45.4\n| May precipitation mm = 43.2\n| Jun precipitation 