-\n||Redhill||align=right|11,867\n|-\n||St Peter's||align=right|11,760\n|-\n||Southwick||align=right|11,634\n|-\n||'''Northside total:'''||align=right|'''59,459'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;\n|-\n||Barnes||align=right|12,030\n|-\n||Doxford||align=right|11,318\n|-\n||Hendon||align=right|11,551\n|-\n||Millfield||align=right|10,277\n|-\n||Pallion||align=right|10,385\n|-\n||Ryhope||align=right|11,217\n|-\n||St Anne's||align=right|11,409\n|-\n||St Chad's||align=right|10,922\n|-\n||St Michael's||align=right|11,626\n|-\n||Sandhill||align=right|11,319\n|-\n||Silksworth||align=right|11,245\n|-\n||'''Southside total:'''||align=right|'''123,299'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;\n|-\n||'''City total:'''||align=right|'''182,758'''\n|}\n\nAt 3,874 [[hectares]], Sunderland is the 45th largest {{citation needed|date=March 2015}} urban area in England by measure of area, with a population density of 45.88 people per hectare.\n\nAccording to statistics<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunderland 2001 Census Statistics|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/dfc-sunderland.pdf|accessdate=18 January 2007|format=PDF |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711002534/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/dfc-sunderland.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 11 July 2007}}</ref> based on the 2001 census, 60% of homes in the Sunderland [[metropolitan area]] are [[Owner Occupied|owner occupied]], with an average household size of 2.4 people. Three percent of the homes have no permanent residents.\n\nThe most ethnically diverse ward of the city was the (now defunct)<ref>The Thornholme ward no longer existed in the [[United Kingdom Census 2011]]</ref> Thornholme area which had a population of 10,214 in 2001. This ward, which included Eden Vale, Thornhill, as well as parts of Hendon, Ashbrooke and the city centre, has long been the focus of Wearside's Bangladeshi community. In Thornholme, 89.4% are white (86.3% White British), 7.8% are Asian and 1.3% are mixed-race.<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941170&c=thornholme&d=14&e=15&g=370084&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462122135203&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47 |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Nowadays the [[Barnes, Sunderland|Barnes ward]], which contains part of former Thornholme ward, has the highest percentage (5.4%) of Bangladeshi residents in the city, with people of this ethnicity being the ward's only significant ethnic minority. The 2001 census also recorded a substantial concentration of Greek nationals, living mainly in Central and Thornholme wards. The least ethnically diverse wards are in the north of the city. The area of [[Castletown, Sunderland|Castletown]] is made up of 99.3% white, 0.4% Asian and 0.2% mixed-race.\n\nThe Sunderland USD had a population of 174,286 in 2011 compared with 275,506 for the wider city. Both of these figures are a decrease compared with 2001 figures that showed the Sunderland USD had a population of 182,758 compared with 280,807 for the wider city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/asv2htm.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205650/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/asv2htm.aspx |archive-date=30 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Millfield, Tyne and Wear|Millfield ward]], which contains the western half of the city centre, was the most ethnically diverse ward in Sunderland. Millfield is a multiracial area with large Indian and Bangladeshi communities, being the centre of Wearside's Bangladeshi community along with neighbouring Barnes. The ward's ethnicity was, in 2011, 76.4% White (73.5% White British), 17.6% Asian and 2.5% Black.<ref>{{cite web|title = Millfield - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/millfield-e05001161#sthash.k4D5ViU8.uuCzDyBH.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref> Other wards with high ethnic minority populations include [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]], Barnes, St Michael's and St Peter's. In 2011, the least ethnically diverse ward was the Northside suburb Redhill which was 99.0% White (98.3% White British), 0.3% Asian and 0.1% Black.<ref>{{cite web|author=Good Stuff IT Services |url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/redhill-e05001163#sthash.Dnm2WCse.dpbs |title=Redhill - UK Census Data 2011 |publisher=Ukcensusdata.com |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> This ward has so few ethnic minorities that it can even be compared to rural wards in Cumbria and it also proves there is a lot of contrast between areas when it comes to ethnicity.\n\nHere is a table comparing Sunderland and the wider City of Sunderland Metropolitan Borough as well as [[North East England]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!2011 Census Ethnic Groups\n!White British\n!Asian\n!Black\n|-\n|Sunderland (Urban Subdivision)\n|93.4%\n|3.6%\n|0.6%\n|-\n|[[Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland]]\n|94.8%\n|2.6%\n|0.5%\n|-\n|[[North East England]]\n|93.6%\n|2.8%\n|0.5%\n|-\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title = Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.uKxpOFke.ELqplSD3.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119884905|title=Custom report - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/north-east-e12000001#sthash.ykCPT4B2.dpbs|title=North East - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref>\n\nThe Sunderland Urban Subdivision is made up of all the wards listed on the table on the right hand side. In the Sunderland Urban Subdivision, 6.6% of the population were from an ethnic minority group (non white British) compared with 5.2% in the surrounding borough. Sunderland is less ethnically diverse than [[Gateshead]] and [[South Shields]], mainly because of many outlying suburbs to the south, north and west of the city such as St Chad's, [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] and [[Fulwell, Sunderland|Fulwell]] which have very high White British populations. The [[Sunderland Central]] Parliament constituency largely omits these areas. However, in 2001, the Sunderland USD was 96.6% White British, so the ethnic minority population is increasing.\n\n===Religion===\nThe area is part of the [[Church of England|Anglican]] [[Diocese of Durham]]. It has been in the [[Roman Catholic]] [[Diocese of Hexham and Newcastle]]<ref name=rcdhn2017>{{cite web | url = http://www.rcdhn.org.uk/churches07/churchtowns.php | title = RCDHN | website = rcdhn.org.uk| publisher = rcdhn.org.uk | access-date = 29 January 2017 | quote = }}</ref> since the [[Catholic Church hierarchy|Catholic hierarchy]] was restored in 1850. The 2011 census recorded that 70.2% of the population identified as Christian, 1.32% as Muslim, 0.29% as Sikh, 0.22% as Hindu, 0.19% as Buddhist, 0.02% as Jewish, and 21.90% as having no religion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.8BxUZ8zv.dpbs|title=Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|last=Services|first=Good Stuff IT|website=UK Census Data|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nJewish heritage in the city, once part of a thriving community, can be dated back to around 1750, when a number of Jewish merchants from across the UK and Europe settled in Sunderland,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seligman.org.il/sunderland_jews.html|title=Sunderland Jews|website=www.seligman.org.il|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> eventually forming a congregation in 1768. A [[rabbi]] from [[Holland]] was established in the city in 1790. After a rapid growth in numbers during the latter half of the nineteenth century, the Jewish community in Sunderland reached its height in the mid 1930s, when around 2,000 Jews were recorded to be living in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seligman.org.il/sunderland_jews.html|title=Sunderland Jews|last=Seligman|first=Jon|website=www.seligman.org.il|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref> The community has been in slow decline since the mid-20th century. Many Sunderland Jews left for stronger Jewish communities in Britain or to Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.999sunderland.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912072202/http://www.999sunderland.com/ |archive-date=12 September 2007  }}</ref> The Jewish primary school, the Menorah School, closed in July 1983. The [[synagogue]] on Ryhope Road, opened in 1928, closed at the end of March 2006.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/wear/hi/people_and_places/religion_and_ethics/newsid_8197000/8197862.stm|title=BBC - Wear - Jewish community gradually fades|date=12 August 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> (See also [[Jews and Judaism in North East England]]) The Jewish population of the Sunderland Metropolitan Borough is continually diminishing, as the Jewish population fell from 114 people in 2001, to 76 people in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title = Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.uKxpOFke.IyxsRnyA.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, following the grant of City status to Sunderland, the erstwhile [[parish church]] of Bishopwearmouth (St Michael's) was redesignated as [[Sunderland Minster]] with a city-wide role. It was believed to have been the first creation of a [[Minster (church)|minster church]] in England since the [[Reformation in England|Reformation]].<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" />\n\n====Alexander Boddy and the Early Development of Pentecostalism in Britain====\nThe Reverend [[Alexander Boddy]] (who lived 1854-1930) was appointed vicar of All Saints Church (Church of England) in the [[Monkwearmouth]] area of Sunderland in 1884.  During his ministry at Monkwearmouth, Boddy was influenced by the [[1904-1905 Welsh revival]] and also by the British-born Norwegian preacher [[Thomas Ball Barratt]] (T.B. Barratt). In the early years of the 20th century All Saints, Monkwearmouth became an important centre for the development of the Pentecostal Movement in Britain.\n\n==Economy==\n{{Further|List of companies in the City of Sunderland}}\n\n===Regeneration===\nSince the mid-1980s Sunderland has undergone massive regeneration {{citation needed|date=July 2015}}, particularly around the central business district and the river corridor, following the industrial decline of the 1970s and early 1980s.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Sunderland's economic situation began to improve following the collapse of the local shipbuilding industry. Japanese car manufacturer [[Nissan]] opened the [[Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK]] factory in 1986, and the first [[Nissan Bluebird]] car was produced later that year.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> The factory and its supplier companies remain the largest employers in the region, with current cars produced there including the [[Nissan Qashqai]], the [[Nissan Juke]] and the electric [[Nissan Leaf|Nissan LEAF]]. As of 2012 over 500,000 cars are produced annually, and it is the UK's largest car factory.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAlso in the late 1980s, new [[Service industry|service industries]] moved into sites such as the [[Doxford International Business Park]] in the south west of the city, attracting national and international companies. Sunderland was named in the shortlist of the top seven \"intelligent cities\" in the world for the use of [[information technology]], in 2004 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Pages/press/pritem.asp?Id=1021 |title=TOP OF THE WORLD |publisher=Sunderland City Council |date=20 January 2005 |accessdate=9 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070312062944/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Pages/press/pritem.asp?Id=1021 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 12 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe former shipyards along the Wear were transformed with a mixture of residential, commercial and leisure facilities including St. Peter's Campus of the University of Sunderland, University accommodation along the Fish Quay on the South side of the river, the North Haven housing and marina development, the [[National Glass Centre]], the [[Stadium of Light]] and Hylton Riverside Retail Park. Also in 2007, the Echo 24 luxury apartments opened on Pann's Bank overlooking the river. In 2008 the [[Sunderland Aquatic Centre]] opened adjacent to the Stadium of Light, containing the only [[Olympic-size swimming pool]] between [[Leeds]] and [[Edinburgh]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\nIn 2000, [[the Bridges]] [[shopping mall|shopping centre]] was extended towards Crowtree Road and the former Central [[Bus station|Bus Station]], attracting national [[chain store]]s. This was followed by adjacent redevelopments on Park Lane.\n\nSunderland Corporation's massive post-war housing estate developments at [[Farringdon, Sunderland|Farringdon]], [[Pennywell]] and [[Grindon, Sunderland|Grindon]] have all passed into the ownership of [[Gentoo Group|Gentoo]] (previously 'Sunderland Housing Group'), a private company and a [[Registered Social Landlord]].\n\n[[Sunderland A.F.C.]] has been a major symbol of the area and a contributor to the local economy since the late [[19th century]]. The club was one of the most successful and best supported clubs in the English game during this era, with its home at [[Roker Park]] holding more than 70,000 spectators at its peak. However, the [[FA Cup]] triumph of 1973 would prove to be the club's only postwar major trophy to date, and after its relegation in 1958 the club frequently bounced between the top two divisions of English football, and in 1987 and again in 2018 suffered relegation to the third tier of English football. The club played at Roker Park for 99 years until the completion of the new [[Stadium of Light]] at [[Monkwearmouth]] on the banks of the [[River Wear]] in 1997. The new stadium seated more than 42,000 on its completion, and has since been expanded to hold some 49,000 spectators. Sunderland's relatively high attendances have been a major boost to the local economy - averaging at more than 30,000 even during the club's current spell in the third tier of English football.\n\nIn 2004, redevelopment work began in the Sunniside area in the east-end of the city centre, including a [[multiplex cinema]], a [[multi-storey car park]], restaurants, a [[casino]] and [[tenpin bowling]]. Originally the River Quarter, the site was renamed Limelight in 2005, and renamed in 2008, when it became Sunniside Leisure. Sunniside Gardens were landscaped, and a number of new cafes, bars and restaurants were opened. Up-market residential apartments were developed, including the Echo 24 building.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/sunniside/ |title=Sunniside |publisher=[[Sunderland arc]]|date=6 January 2009 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226232909/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/sunniside/ |archive-date=26 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSunderland City Council's Unitary Development Plan (UDP) outlines ambitious regeneration plans for a number of sites around the city.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/planningandenvironment/planningpolicy/udp/udp/udphome-page.asp |title=Sunderland Unitary Development Plan |date=6 January 2009 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330043523/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/Environment/PlanningandEnvironment/PlanningPolicy/UDP/UDP/udphome-page.asp |archive-date=30 March 2009  }}</ref>\nThe plans are supported by [[Sunderland Arc]], an urban regeneration company funded by the City council, [[One NorthEast]] and the [[Homes and Communities Agency]].\n\n;Vaux and Farringdon Row\nSince the closure of the [[Vaux Breweries|Vaux brewery]] in 1999, a {{convert|26|acre|ha|adj=on|abbr=off}} [[brownfield land|brownfield site]] has lain dormant in the centre of Sunderland. The land is subject to dispute between supermarket chain [[Tesco]], who bought the site in 2001, and Sunderland arc, who submitted plans for its redevelopment in 2002.<ref name=\"Vaux Site FAQ\">{{cite news |url=http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/faqs.aspx |title=Vaux Site FAQ |date=4 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226201305/http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/faqs.aspx |archive-date=26 February 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During formal negotiations, Tesco stated they would be willing to sell the land to arc, if an alternative city centre site could be found. Possibilities include Holmeside Triangle, and the Sunderland Retail Park in Roker. Arc hope to begin development in 2010.<ref name=\"Vaux Site FAQ\"/>\nArc's plans for the site were approved by the Secretary of State in 2007, and include extensive office space, [[hotel]]s, leisure and retail units, residential apartments and a new \u00a350&nbsp;m [[Crown and Magistrates court]]. The central public arcade will be located under an expansive glass canopy. It is hoped an \"[[evening economy]]\" can be encouraged which will complement the city's nightlife.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/this-is-the-opportunity.aspx |title=Vaux Site Opportunity |date=4 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226201316/http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/this-is-the-opportunity.aspx |archive-date=26 February 2009  }}</ref> In 2013 in the area opposite the Vaux site, Sunderland City Council announced the [[Keel Square]] project, a new public space designed to commemorate Sunderand's maritime heritage, which was completed in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/business/images-of-sunderland-s-new-11-8million-square-1-6149182|title=Images of Sunderland\u2019s new \u00a311.8million square|date=16 October 2013|accessdate=9 August 2014 |publisher=Sunderland Echo}}</ref> Construction commenced in 2014.\n;Stadium Village\nRedevelopment of the Monkwearmouth Colliery site, which sits on the north bank of the river Wear opposite the Vaux site, began in the mid-1990s with the creation of the [[Stadium of Light]]. In 2008, it was joined by the [[Sunderland Aquatic Centre]].\nThe Sheepfolds industrial estate occupies a large area of land between the Stadium and the [[Wearmouth Bridge]].\n[[Sunderland Arc]] were in the process of purchasing land in the Sheepfolds, with a view to relocate the businesses and redevelop the site. The emphasis of development plans included further sporting facilities, in order to create a ''Sports Village''. Other plans included a hotel, residential accommodation, and a [[footbridge]] linking the site with the Vaux development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/stadiumVillage/sheepfolds/index.aspx |title=Stadium Park Development |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025004930/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/stadiumVillage/sheepfolds/index.aspx |archive-date=25 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n;Grove and Transport Corridor\nThe Sunderland Strategic Transport Corridor (SSTC) is a proposed transport link from the A19, through the city centre, to the port. A major phase of the plan was the creation of a new bridge, the [[Northern Spire Bridge]], which links the [[A1231 road|A1231]] Wessington Way on the north of the river with the Grove site in Pallion, on the south of the river.\nIn 2008, Sunderland City Council offered the residents of Sunderland the opportunity to vote on the design of the bridge. The choices were a {{Convert|180|m|ft|-1|adj=on}} iconic [[cable-stayed bridge]], which would result in a temporary increase in [[council tax]], or a simple [[road bridge|box structure]] which would be within the council's budget.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/newbridge/ |title=New Bridge |date=10 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118050641/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/newbridge/ |archive-date=18 November 2009  }}</ref>\nThe results of the consultation were inconclusive, with residents keen to have an iconic bridge, but reluctant to have a subsequent increase in tax to fund it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Next-step-in-road-to.4747133.jp |title=Next step in road to iconic Wear bridge|date=1 December 2008 |accessdate=10 March 2009}}</ref>\nRegardless of the ultimate design of the new bridge, the landing point will be the former Grove Cranes site in [[Pallion]]. Plans for this site focus around the creation of a new residential area, with homes, community buildings, commercial and retail space.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/groves/ |title=Gorve Site |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226232800/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/groves/ |archive-date=26 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n;The Port\nThe Port of Sunderland, owned by the city council, has been earmarked for medium-term redevelopment with a focus on mixed-use industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/portofsunderland/ |title=Port of Sunderland |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227122242/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/portofsunderland/ |archive-date=27 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Ship building and coal mining===\n[[File:Shipbuilding during the First World War Q20119.jpg|thumbnail|left|A group of boys who worked on the construction of a Standard ship at a yard in Sunderland during the First World War.]]\n[[File:Radiant II is launched into the River Wear (14508024713).jpg|thumb|right|A ship (''Radiant II'') launched into the River Wear by [[Austin & Pickersgill]], 29 March 1961.]]\nOnce hailed as the \"Largest Shipbuilding Town in the World\",<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Shipbuilding in the North East|work=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/ship-building/background.shtml|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> ships were built on the Wear from at least 1346<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2008/01/16/shipbuilding_has_been_20_years_feature.shtml|title=History of shipbuilding on Wearside|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> onwards and by the mid-18th century Sunderland was one of the chief shipbuilding towns in the country. [[Sunderland Docks]] was the home of operations for the [[shipbuilding]] industry on [[Wearside]]. The Port of Sunderland was significantly expanded in the 1850s with the construction of Hudson Dock to designs by River Wear Commissioner's Engineer John Murray, with consultancy by [[Robert Stephenson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SINE Project: Structure details for South Dock: Hudson Dock|work=University of Newcastle upon Tyne|url=http://www.sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=505|access-date=22 November 2006|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060616184050/http://www.sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=505|archive-date=16 June 2006}}</ref> One famous vessel was the [[Torrens (clipper ship)|''Torrens'']], the clipper in which [[Joseph Conrad]] sailed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/opinion/the-clipper-ship-torrens-1-1147795|title=The clipper ship Torrens|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> and on which he began his first novel. She was one of the most famous ships of her time and can claim to be the finest ship ever launched from a Sunderland yard. {{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:An Aerial view of Sunderland (9105585273).jpg|left|thumb|221x221px|[[Sunderland Docks]] in 1969.]]\nBetween 1939 and 1945 the Wear yards launched 245 merchant ships totalling 1.5 million tons, a quarter of the merchant tonnage produced in the UK at this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/ship-building/background.shtml|title=BBC - Nation on Film - Shipbuilding - Background|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> Competition from overseas caused a downturn in demand for Sunderland built ships toward the end of the 20th century. The last shipyard in Sunderland closed on 7 December 1988.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sunderland Public Library Service|title=LOCAL STUDIES CENTRE FACT SHEET NUMBER 10:Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 1|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=6958&p=0|access-date=27 August 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902021657/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=6958&p=0|archive-date=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nSunderland, part of the Durham coalfield, has a coal-mining heritage that dates back centuries. At its peak in 1923, 170,000 miners were employed in County Durham alone,<ref>{{cite web|title=Rise and Fall of Coal Mining|work=North East England History|url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/CoalMiningandRailways.htm|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> as labourers from all over Britain, including many from [[Scotland]] and [[Ireland]], entered the region. As demand for coal slipped following [[World War II]], mines began to close across the region, causing mass unemployment. The last [[coal mine]] closed in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/lifestyle/retro/exhibition-digs-into-sunderland-s-mining-history-1-7374451|title=Exhibition digs into Sunderland\u2019s mining history|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911013557/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/lifestyle/retro/exhibition-digs-into-sunderland-s-mining-history-1-7374451|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The site of the last coal mine, [[Wearmouth Colliery]], is now occupied by the [[Stadium of Light]], and a miner's [[Davy lamp]] monument stands outside of the ground to honour the site's mining heritage. Documentation relating to the region's coalmining heritage are stored at the [[North East England Mining Archive and Resource Centre]] (NEEMARC).\n\n===Other industry===\n[[File:Sunderland Liebherr Riverside.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Liebherr]] crane factory is the last remaining heavy industry on the River Wear in Sunderland.]]\n\nAs with the coal-mining and shipbuilding, overseas competition has forced the closure of all of Sunderland's glass-making factories. [[Corning Glass Works]], in Sunderland for 120 years, closed on 31 March 2007<ref>{{cite web\n|title=End of an era as glass firm sets closure date\n|work=[[The Northern Echo]]\n|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/business/news/display.var.1124976.0.end_of_era_as_glass_firm_sets_closure_date.php\n|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> and in January 2007, the [[Pyrex]] manufacturing site also closed,<ref>{{cite news|title=Energy costs close glass factory|work=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/6271617.stm|date=17 January 2007|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> bringing to an end commercial glass-making in the city. However, there has been a modest rejuvenation with the opening of the [[National Glass Centre]] which, amongst other things, provides international glass makers with working facilities and a shop to showcase their work, predominantly in the artistic rather than functional field.\n\n[[Vaux Breweries]] was established in the town centre in the 1880s and for 110 years was a major employer. Following a series of consolidations in the British [[Brewing industry]], however, the brewery was finally closed in July 1999.<ref>{{cite web|last=Journal |first=The |url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/culture/restaurants-bars/painful-anniversary-vaux-brewery-sunderland-4480444 |title=Painful Anniversary for Vaux Brewery, Sunderland - journallive Administrator |publisher=The Journal |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>  Vaux in Sunderland and [[Wards Brewing Company|Wards]] in [[Sheffield]] had been part of the Vaux Group, but with the closure of both breweries it was re-branded The Swallow Group, concentrating on the hotel side of the business. This was subject to a successful take-over by [[Whitbread|Whitbread PLC]] in the autumn of 2000. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}} It is now a brownfield site and this is a derelict site in an urban area.\n\nIn 1855, [[John Candlish]] opened a bottleworks, producing glass bottles, with 6 sites at nearby [[Seaham]] and at Diamond Hall, Sunderland.\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Sunderland}}\n[[File:St peters campus.jpg|thumb|St Peter's Riverside Campus at Monkwearmouth]]\n\nSunderland Polytechnic was founded in 1969, becoming the [[University of Sunderland]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=University history |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university|work=Sunderland University |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> The institution currently has over 17,000 students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Facts, Figures, Accolades, the University's vision |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts |work=Sunderland University |date=2 January 2008 |access-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318005834/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/ |archive-date=18 March 2008 }}</ref> The university is split into two campuses; the City Campus (site of the original Polytechnic) is just to the west of the city centre, as is the main university library and the main administrative buildings. The 'Award-Winning' St Peter's Riverside Campus is located on the north banks of the river Wear, next to the National Glass Centre and houses the School of Business, Law and Psychology, as well as Computing and Technology and The Media Centre.<ref>{{cite news |title=The University |url=\nhttp://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/campuses/|work=Sunderland University, Our Campuses |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Sunderland was named the top university in England for providing the best student experience by ''[[The Times Higher Education Supplement]]'' (THES) in 2006. Since 2001 Sunderland has been named the best new university in England by ''[[The Guardian]]'' and Government performance indicators showed Sunderland as the best new university in England for the quality, range and quantity of its research.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards and Accolades 2007/8 |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/accolades |work=Sunderland University website |date=2 January 2008 |access-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080427134351/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/accolades/ |archive-date=27 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sunderland College]] is a [[further education]] establishment with five campuses located at the Bede centre on [[A690|Durham Road]], [[Shiney Row]], Hylton, Doxford International Business Park and 'Phoenix House' in the city centre. It has over 14,000 students, and based on exam results is one of the most successful colleges.<ref>{{cite web |title=City of Sunderland College |url=http://www.citysun.ac.uk/opencms/opencms/website/home/pressoffice/factsandstatistics/index.html |accessdate=18 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061207074028/http://www.citysun.ac.uk/opencms/opencms/website/home/pressoffice/factsandstatistics/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 7 December 2006}}</ref> St Peter's Sixth Form College, next to St Peter's Church and the University, opened in September 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Work begins on \u00a36&nbsp;m campus college |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/7168780.stm |work=BBC News |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 January 2008}}</ref> The college is a partnership between the three Sunderland North schools and City of Sunderland College.<ref>{{cite web |title=St Peter's Sixth Form College |url=http://www.stpeterssixthformcollege.ac.uk/ |access-date=3 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080127163823/http://www.stpeterssixthformcollege.ac.uk/ |archive-date=27 January 2008  }}</ref>\n\nThere are eighteen [[secondary school]]s in the Sunderland area, predominantly comprehensives. According to exam results, the most successful was [[St Robert of Newminster Catholic School]], a coeducational secondary school and sixth form in Washington.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/education/school_tables/secondary/12/html/eng_maths_394.stm?compare=|title=Secondary school league tables in Sunderland|last=|first=|date=23 April 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> However, comprehensive schools also thrive, notably the Roman Catholic single-sex schools [[St Anthony's Girls' Catholic Academy|St. Anthony's]] (for girls) and [[St Aidan's Catholic School|St. Aidan's]] (for boys). Both continue to attain high exam results. There are seventy-six [[primary school]]s in Sunderland. According to the 'Value Added' measure, the most successful is Mill Hill Primary School, in [[Doxford Park]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Primary Schools in Sunderland League Table |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/06/school_tables/primary_schools/html/va_394.stm |accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nSunderland voted for [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on European Union membership]] by 61% of the vote; an unexpectedly high margin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/how-world-reacted-sunderland-voted-17654528|title=How the world reacted when Sunderland voted to leave the European Union|last=Lindsay|first=Kali|date=2020-01-31|website=nechronicle|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Freytas-Tamura|first=Kimiko de|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/28/world/europe/european-union-brexit-sunderland-britain-cameron.html|title=Pro-\u2018Brexit\u2019 City of Sunderland Glad to Poke Establishment in the Eye|date=2016-06-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New Statesman]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/07/how-sunderland-became-poster-child-brexit|title=How Sunderland became a poster child for Brexit|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> and [[The Daily Telegraph]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wallace|first=Tim|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/12/06/special-report-sunderland-aiming-poster-city-brexit/|title=Special report: Sunderland aiming to be the \u2018poster city for Brexit\u2019|date=2019-12-06|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> have described Sunderland as the [[Poster child|poster city]] for Brexit.\n\nFor decades, Sunderland has been an electoral stronghold of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nSunderland is currently represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] by three Labour Members of Parliament; [[Bridget Phillipson]], [[Julie Elliott]] and [[Sharon Hodgson]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n![[Houghton and Sunderland South (UK Parliament constituency)|Houghton and Sunderland South]]\n![[Sunderland Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland Central]]\n![[Washington and Sunderland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Washington and Sunderland West]]\n|-\n|[[Bridget Phillipson]]\n|[[Julie Elliott]]\n|[[Sharon Hodgson]]\n|-\n|[[File:Official portrait of Bridget Phillipson MP crop 2.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Julieface.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Official portrait of Mrs Sharon Hodgson MP crop 2.jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|}\n\n==Transport==\n{{Main|Transport in Tyne and Wear}}\n\n===Metro===\n[[File:Sunderland_Metro_Map.png|thumb|780px|Sunderland-oriented Metro map. Dashed lines indicate omitted stations.]]\n[[File:Pallion station 02.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pallion Metro station]] on the Tyne and Wear Metro is a small suburban station in Sunderland.]]\nIn May 2002 the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] was extended to Sunderland in an official ceremony attended by The Queen, twenty-two years after it originally opened in Newcastle upon Tyne. The Green line now stretches deeper into [[South Tyneside]] and into Sunderland, incorporating [[Seaburn]], [[Millfield]], [[Pallion]], as well as [[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland's mainline railway station]] and stations at the [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane Transport Interchange]] and both campuses of the [[University of Sunderland]] before terminating at [[South Hylton]]. The trains run every 12\u201315 minutes (depending on time of day) and call at all stations. All-zones Metro tickets cost \u00a35.20 for a daily and \u00a322.40 for a weekly, as of October 2019.<ref>https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro-day-ticket</ref><ref>https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro-season-ticket</ref>\n\nIn March 2014 Metro owner Nexus proposed an extension of the network by the creation of an \"on-street\" tram link which would connect the city centre to [[South Shields]] to the north and Doxford Park to the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/business/new-south-tyneside-metro-and-tram-link-up-plans-revealed-1-6525102 |title=New South Tyneside Metro and tram link-up plans revealed |publisher=Shields Gazette |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\nSunderland is served by [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]], which is a 55-minute Metro ride from Sunderland city centre; there is a Metro train connecting with the airport every 12\u201315 minutes in both directions until about 11pm, Monday-Sunday.\n\n===Rail===\n===National Rail===\n[[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland station]] has 5 direct trains to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] on weekdays (5 on Saturday / 4 on Sunday), taking about 3 hours 30 minutes. [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] is a 30-minute [[Tyne & Wear Metro]] ride (see above) from Sunderland city centre, and has connecting services to London every half hour that take approximately 2 hours 45 minutes and also regular services to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]], [[Glasgow Central railway station|Glasgow]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]], [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]], [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]], [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham]] and beyond.\n\n[[File:Sunderland station Metro platforms.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland railway and Metro station]].]]\n[[File:GRAND CENTRAL 2 Launch Day.JPG|thumbnail|right|[[Grand Central (train operating company)|Grand Central]] operate five daily services from [[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland]] to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross']]]]\nSunderland station opened in 1879<ref name=\"disused-stations.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/s/sunderland_central/ |title=Sunderland Central Station |publisher=Disused Stations |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> but was completely redesigned to facilitate football teams and officials from countries who were drawn to play at [[Roker Park]] during England's hosting of the [[1966 World Cup]]. It is situated on an underground level.<ref name=\"disused-stations.org.uk\"/> It was renovated in 2005, backed by the artistic team which designed the stations along the Wearside extension of the [[Tyne & Wear Metro]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title= New look arriving|work=Sunderland Echo|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/New-look-will-be-arriving.1010574.jp|date=27 April 2005|accessdate=3 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= New rail service launch delayed|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6168002.stm|date=21 November 2006|accessdate=22 November 2006}}</ref> It is situated on the [[Durham Coast Line]] served by direct [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] services to Newcastle, [[Hartlepool railway station|Hartlepool]], [[Stockton railway station (County Durham)|Stockton]] and [[Middlesbrough railway station|Middlesbrough]], as well as further afield to [[Hexham railway station|Hexham]], [[Carlisle railway station|Carlisle]] and the Gateshead [[MetroCentre railway station|MetroCentre]]. These services run hourly in each direction, cut from half-hourly on 12 December 2005 (but towards Newcastle there is also the option of taking the Metro - see the Metro subsection above).\n\nFrom 1998 to 2004, Northern Spirit and subsequently [[Arriva Trains Northern]] ran bihourly direct trains from Sunderland to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] via [[Durham railway station|Durham]], [[Darlington railway station|Darlington]], [[York railway station|York]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] and [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester]]. The services were withdrawn due to a change of franchise which saw the [[First TransPennine Express]] route gain a franchise in its own right, distinct from the Regional Railways network which Arriva had inherited. Services now terminate at Newcastle, and a separate service also travels to Middlesbrough, but both only stretch as far as [[Manchester Airport railway station|Manchester Airport]].\n\nIn 2006, [[Grand Central (train operating company)|Grand Central]] announced plans to operate a direct service between Sunderland and [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] via [[York railway station|York]], a service which had been stripped from Wearside twenty years earlier. A scaled-down service of one train each day began in December 2007, twelve months after the initial launch date, due to delays caused by restoring rolling stock and a protracted court case against [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] (which Grand Central won). The service increased to three departures daily each way on 1 March 2008, connecting a line which can run from Edinburgh to London. The service has proved so popular that daily fourth and fifth direct trains are now in operation.\n\nWhen [[Virgin Trains East Coast]] were announced as the winners of the [[InterCity East Coast]] franchise in November 2014 their plans included a daily service from Sunderland to London Kings Cross that commenced in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stagecoach.com/media/news-releases/2014/2014-11-27.aspx |title=Stagecoach-Virgin company awarded InterCity East Coast rail franchise - Stagecoach Group |publisher=Stagecoach.com |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Main roads in sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of the main roads through Sunderland.]]\nThe fastest, largest and busiest road is the [[A19 road|A19]], which is a [[dual carriageway]] running north-to-south along the western edge of the urban area, crossing the River Wear at Hylton, and providing access north to the [[Tyne Tunnel]], joining up with the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] to Edinburgh, and south through [[Teesside]], joining up with the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1M]] via the [[A168 road|A168]] at [[Thirsk]], providing an entirely [[grade separated]] connection between Sunderland and the [[M1 motorway]]. The A19 originally ran through Sunderland city centre until the bypass was built in the 1970s; this route is now the A1018.\n\nThere are four main roads which support the city centre. The [[A690 road|A690]] ''Durham Road'' terminates in the city centre, and runs to [[Crook, County Durham]] via the city of Durham.\n\nThe [[A1231 road|A1231]] (Sunderland Highway) begins in the city centre, crosses the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] and runs west through [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]] to the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]]. Most of this road is [[national speed limit]] [[dual carriageway]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nThe [[A1018 road|A1018]] and [[A183 road (England)|A183]] roads both start in the centre of South Shields and enter Sunderland from the north, before merging to cross the Wearmouth Bridge. The A1018 follows a direct route from Shields to Sunderland, the A183 follows the coast. After crossing the bridge, the A1018 follows a relatively straight path to the south of Sunderland where it merges with the A19. The A183 becomes ''Chester Road'' and heads west out of the city to the A1 at [[Chester-le-Street]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn Autumn 2007 the ''Southern Radial Route'' was opened. This is a bypass of the A1018 through Grangetown and Ryhope \u2013 a stretch that commonly suffered from [[traffic congestion|congestion]], especially during [[rush hour]]. The bypass starts just south of Ryhope, and runs parallel to the cliff tops into Hendon, largely avoiding residential areas.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nSunderland strategic transport corridor project, is an ongoing investment to the city's road infrastructure. The scheme will improve transport links around the city ensuring continuous dual carriageway between the A19 road and the port of Sunderland. The scheme also includes the building of a new wear bridge between Pallion on the south embankment and Castletown to the north.\n\n===Bus===\n[[File:Buses in Park Lane Interchange - geograph.org.uk - 1748466.jpg|thumbnail|right|[[Go North East]] buses in [[Park Lane Interchange]]]]\nA multimillion-pound [[transport interchange]] at [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]] was opened on 2 May 1999 by the then ''[[Brookside]]'' actor [[Michael Starke (actor)|Michael Starke]]. With 750,000 passengers per year it is the busiest bus and coach station in Britain after [[Victoria Coach Station]] in [[Central London]], and has won several awards for innovative design.<ref name=\"didyouknow\">{{cite news|title=Did you know? Sunderland facts|work=Sunderland Echo News|url=http://www.wear1.co.uk/didyouknow.html|date=21 November 2006|accessdate=22 November 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070802181549/http://www.wear1.co.uk/didyouknow.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 August 2007}}</ref> The majority of bus services in Sunderland are provided by [[Stagecoach North East|Stagecoach in Sunderland]] and [[Go North East]], with a handful of services provided by [[Arriva North East]]. Besides these, there are also inter state and inter city route buses mainly operated by [[National Express Coaches|National Express]] and [[Megabus (Europe)|Megabus]] . A new Metro station was built underneath the bus concourse to provide a direct interchange as part of the extension to South Hylton in 2002.\n\n===Cycle===\nThere are a number of cycle routes that run through and around Sunderland. The [[National Cycle Network]] National Route 1 runs from Ryhope in the south, through the centre of the city, and then along the coast towards South Shields.\nBritain's most popular long-distance [[Segregated cycle facilities|cycle route]] \u2013 The 'C2C' [[Sea to Sea Cycle Route]] \u2013 traditionally starts (or ends) when the cyclist dips their wheel in the sea on Roker beach. The '[[W2W]]' 'Wear-to-[[Walney]]' route, and the 'Two-Rivers' (Tyne and Wear) route also terminate in Sunderland.\n\n===The Port===\n[[File:Sunderland harbour.jpg|thumb|Sunderland harbour viewed from the north dock]]\nThe Port of Sunderland is the second largest municipally owned port in the U.K.<ref name=\"pos1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk | title=Port of Sunderland | publisher=Port of Sunderland | accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The port offers a total of 17 quays<ref name=\"pos-quays\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/port_map.php | title=Port of Sunderland - Port Map | publisher=Port of Sunderland | access-date=6 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814055615/http://portofsunderland.org.uk/port_map.php | archive-date=14 August 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> handling cargoes including forest products, non-ferrous metals, steel, aggregates and refined oil products, limestone, chemicals and maritime cranes.<ref name=\"pos1\"/> It also handles offshore supply vessels and has ship repair and [[drydock]]ing facilities.\n\nThe river berths are deepwater and [[tide|tidal]], while the South Docks are entered via a lock with an 18.9 m beam restriction.<ref name=\"pos-southdock\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/south_docks.php | title=Port of Sunderland - South Docks | publisher=Port of Sunderland | access-date=6 July 2014 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814055945/http://portofsunderland.org.uk/south_docks.php | archive-date=14 August 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Dialect and accent===\n{{Main|Mackem}}\nThe dialect of Sunderland is known as [[Mackem]], and contains a large amount of vocabulary and distinctive words and pronunciations not used in other parts of the United Kingdom. The Mackem dialect has much of its origins in the language spoken by the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] population. Although the accent has so much in common with the more popular [[Geordie]], the dialect spoken in Sunderland is quite distinctive from the dialect spoken in Newcastle.\n\nA few Sunderland dialect words:\n*Nee - No\n*Bosh - Problem\n*Marra - Mate\n*Ha'way - Come on ( Not to be confused with Geordie's Howay)\n*Knack - Hurt\n*Git - Very (Used to emphasize something so 'very good' becomes 'git good')\n*Claes - Clothes\n\n===Attractions===\nNotable attractions for visitors to Sunderland include the 14th century [[Hylton Castle]] and the beaches of Roker and Seaburn.\nThe [[National Glass Centre]] opened in 1998, reflecting Sunderland's distinguished history of glass-making. Despite sustained support from the [[Arts Council]] the centre has struggled to meet visitor targets since it opened.<ref>{{cite news |title=Another new head for Glass Centre |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3861253.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=2 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n[[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]], on Borough Road, was the first municipally funded museum in the country outside London.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It houses a comprehensive collection of the locally produced [[Sunderland Lustreware]] pottery. The City Library Arts Centre, on Fawcett Street, housed the Northern Gallery for Contemporary Art until the library was closed in January 2017.  The library service was relocated to the Museum and Winter Gardens and the Gallery for Contemporary Art transferred to Sunderland University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/our-region/sunderland/closure-date-set-for-sunderland-s-city-library-1-8190155|title=Closure date set for Sunderland\u2019s City Library|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe city possesses a number of public parks. Several of these are historic, including [[Mowbray Park]], [[Roker Park (park)|Roker Park]] and [[Barnes Park]]. In the early 2000s, [[Herrington Country Park]] was opened opposite [[Penshaw Monument]]. The city's parks have secured several awards for its commitment to preserving natural facilities, receiving the [[Britain in Bloom]] collective in 1993, 1997 and 2000.\n\n===Events===\n[[File:Red Arrows Sunderland Airshow 2009 (2).jpg|thumb|right|The Red Arrows display team perform at the 2009 Sunderland International Airshow]]\nEach year on the last weekend in July, the city hosts the [[Sunderland International Airshow]]. It takes place primarily along the sea front at Roker and Seaburn.\n\nSunderland also hosts the free International Festival of Kites, Music and Dance, which attracts kite-makers from around the world to Northumbria Playing Fields, Washington.\n\nEvery year the city hosts a large [[Remembrance Day]] memorial service, the largest in the UK outside [[London]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=North honours fallen war heroes |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6141372.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=17 January 2007 | date=12 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nSunderland's inaugural film festival took place in December 2003 at the ''Bonded Warehouse'' on Sunderland riverside, in spite of the lack of any cinema facilities in the city at that time, featuring the films of local and aspiring directors as well as reshowings of acclaimed works, such as [[Alan Bleasdale]]'s [[The Monocled Mutineer]], accompanied by analysis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/features/featurepages/0,,1099724,00.html|title=The show must go on  | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Simon | last=Hattenstone | date=5 December 2003 | accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref> By the time of the second festival commencing on 21 January 2005, a new cinema multiplex had opened in Sunderland to provide a venue which allowed the festival to showcase over twenty films.\n\nSunderland celebrates an annual Restaurant week, where city centre restaurants provide some of the best plates at low costs.<ref>https://sunderlandvibe.com/sunderland-restaurant-week-2020-what-to-expect/</ref>\n\n===Literature and art===\n[[File:Sunderlandstreets2.jpg|thumb|Sunniside district in the city centre.]]\n[[Lewis Carroll]] was a frequent visitor to the area. He wrote most of ''[[Jabberwocky]]'' at [[Whitburn, South Tyneside|Whitburn]] as well as \"[[The Walrus and the Carpenter]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Walrus and the Carpenter |url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/Sunderland%20and%20East%20Durham.htm|work=Sunderland and East Durham History |accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> Some parts of the area are also widely believed to be the inspiration for his Alice in Wonderland stories, such as Hylton Castle and Backhouse Park.<ref>''Alice in Sunderland'', Bryan Talbot, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-59307-673-3}}</ref> There is a statue to Carroll in Whitburn library. Lewis Carroll was also a visitor to the Rectory of Holy Trinity Church, Southwick; then a township independent of Sunderland. Carroll's connection with Sunderland, and the area's history, is documented in [[Bryan Talbot]]'s 2007 graphic novel ''[[Alice in Sunderland]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ross |last=Robertson |title=News focus: Alice in Pictureland |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2181289&SectionID=1512 |work=Sunderland Echo |date=27 March 2007 |accessdate=29 March 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070402012743/http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2181289&SectionID=1512 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 April 2007}}</ref> More recently, Sunderland-born [[Terry Deary]], writer of the series of ''[[Horrible Histories]]'' books, has achieved fame and success, and many others such as thriller writer [[Sheila Quigley]], are following his lead.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grandmother has write stuff|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3004139.stm |work=BBC News |date=6 May 2003 |accessdate=28 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Salford-born painter [[L. S. Lowry]] was a frequent visitor, staying in the Seaburn Hotel in Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters of Art |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/mk4custompages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31751|work=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=18 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231083815/http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/mk4custompages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31751 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 31 December 2006}}</ref> Many of his paintings of seascapes and shipbuilding are based on Wearside scenes. The [[Northern Gallery for Contemporary Art]] on Fawcett Street and [[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]] showcase exhibitions and installations from up-and-coming and established artists alike, with the latter holding an extensive collection of Lowry. The National Glass Centre on Liberty Way also exhibits a number of glass sculptures.\n\n===Media, film and television===\nSunderland has two local newspapers: the daily evening tabloid ''The [[Sunderland Echo]]'', founded in 1873, and the ''Sunderland Star'' \u2013 a [[Free daily newspaper|free newspaper]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Newspaper Report for the publication: Sunderland Star |work=The Newspaper Society |url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1012 |access-date=6 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714180613/http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1012 |archive-date=14 July 2007  }}</ref>\n\nIt also has its own commercial station, [[Sun FM]], formerly an independent station but now owned by [[Nation Broadcasting]] who acquired the station from the [[UKRD Group]], a student-led community radio station, [[Spark Sunderland|Spark]], and a hospital radio station \u2013 [[Radio Sunderland for Hospitals]], and can receive other north-eastern independent radio stations [[Metro Radio]], [[Greatest Hits North East]], [[Capital North East]] and [[Smooth Radio North East]].\nThe current regional BBC radio station is [[BBC Radio Newcastle]]. The regional DAB multiplex for the Sunderland area is operated by Bauer DIGITAL RADIO LTD. \u2013 owned by Bauer Digital Radio plc.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The city is covered by [[BBC North East and Cumbria]] and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Tyne Tees Television|Tyne Tees]] franchise, which has a regional office in the University's Media Centre.<ref>{{cite web |title=Julia Barthram |work=ITV Tyne Tees |url=http://www.tynetees.tv/Julia_Barthram.htm |access-date=6 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308122635/http://www.tynetees.tv/Julia_Barthram.htm |archive-date=8 March 2007  }}</ref>\n\nSunderland's first film company was established in 2008; and is known as \"Tanner Films Ltd\" and is based in the [[Sunniside, Sunderland|Sunniside]] area of the city. The companies first film, \"King of the North\" starring [[Angus MacFadyen]] and set in the [[Hetton-le-Hole]] area of the city; is currently under production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/6million-film-deal-for-North.5295605.jp|title=$6million film deal for North East murder film|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Bands and musicians from Yorkshire and North East England}}\nSunderland musicians that have gone on to reach international fame include [[David A. Stewart|Dave Stewart]] of the [[Eurythmics]] and all four members of [[Kenickie]], whose vocalist [[Lauren Laverne]] later became known as a TV presenter. In recent years, the [[underground music]] scene in Sunderland has helped promote the likes of [[Frankie & the Heartstrings]], [[The Futureheads]], [[The Golden Virgins]] and [[Field Music]].\n\nOther Mackem musicians include punk rockers [[The Toy Dolls]] (\"Nellie the Elephant\", December 1984), oi! punk band [[Red Alert (band)|Red Alert]], punk band [[Leatherface]], the lead singer of dance outfit [[Olive (band)|Olive]], [[Ruth Ann Boyle]] (\"You're Not Alone\", May 1997) and [[A Tribe of Toffs]] (\"[[John Kettley is a Weatherman]]\", December 1988).\n\nIn May 2005, Sunderland played host to [[BBC Radio 1]]'s [[Big Weekend]] concert at [[Herrington|Herrington Country Park]], attended by 30,000 visitors and which featured [[Foo Fighters]], [[Kasabian]], [[KT Tunstall]], [[Chemical Brothers]] and [[The Black Eyed Peas]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Radio 1's Big Weekend: Penshaw Monument, Herrington Park, Sunderland |work=BBC Radio 1 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend05 |accessdate=26 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Local boys shine at Sunderland's Big Weekend |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2005/05/10/stage_two_sunday_review_feature.shtml |accessdate=26 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Sunderland [[Stadium of Light]], home to [[Sunderland AFC]], is recognised internationally as a major stadium concert venue. Headlining acts have included [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], [[Take That]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Coldplay]], [[Bruce Springsteen|Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[Rihanna]], [[One Direction]], [[Foo Fighters]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce]]. The Empire Theatre sometimes plays host to music acts. Independent, a city-centre [[nightclub]]/music venue, satisfies underground music lovers.\n\nThe Manor Quay' the students' union nightclub on St. Peter's Riverside at the [[University of Sunderland]], has also hosted the [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Max\u00efmo Park]], [[911 (UK band)|911]], [[the Levellers (band)|the Levellers]] and [[Girls Aloud]]. In 2009, the club was taken into private ownership under the name Campus and hosted [[N-Dubz]], [[Ocean Colour Scene]], [[Little Boots]], [[Gary Numan]] and [[Showaddywaddy]] but has since been returned to the university.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The former students' union Wearmouth Hall hosted [[Voice of the Beehive]], [[Manic Street Preachers]], The Primitives and Radiohead before closing in 1992.\n\nSince 2009, Sunderland: Live in the City has played host to a series of free and ticketed live music events throughout venues in the city centre. Sunderland also hosts the yearly Split Music Festival at Ashbrooke Cricket Club which was first celebrated in October 2009 {{citation needed|date=January 2014}} and will return in 2010 with Max\u00efmo Park and The Futureheads headlining.{{Update inline|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 2013 local band Frankie and The Heartstrings opened a temporary pop up record store in the city, Pop Recs Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24437766 |title=Frankie and the Heartstrings: Record shop boys|publisher=BBC News |date=9 October 2013 |first=Ian |last=Youngs |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Initially only intended to remain open for a fortnight, the store remains open and has hosted live performances from acts including [[The Cribs]], [[The Vaccines]] and [[The Charlatans (English band)|The Charlatans]].\n\n===Theatre===\n[[File:Sunderland Empire.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Sunderland Empire]]\nThe [[Sunderland Empire Theatre]] opened in 1907 on [[High Street West]] in the city centre. It is the largest theatre in between [[Edinburgh]] and [[London]]{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}, and completed a comprehensive refurbishment in 2004. Operated by international entertainment group [[Live Nation]], the Empire is the only theatre between [[Glasgow]] and [[Leeds]] with sufficient capacity to accommodate large [[West End theatre|West End]] productions.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Sunderland Empire Theatre |work=Sunderland City Council |url=http://www.visitsunderland.com/culture/empire.html |access-date=18 January 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061222233211/http://www.visitsunderland.com/culture/empire.html |archive-date=22 December 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It is infamous for playing host to the final performance of British comic actor [[Sid James]] who died of a heart attack whilst on stage in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/retro1980s/1989-Ghostly-tale.4331124.jp|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120918044323/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/retro1980s/1989-Ghostly-tale.4331124.jp|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 September 2012|title=1989: Ghostly tale|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Royalty Theatre on [[A183 road (England)|Chester Road]] is the home to the amateur Royalty Theatre Group who also put on a number of low-budget productions throughout the year. Film producer [[David Parfitt]] belonged to this company before achieving worldwide fame and is now a patron of the theatre.<ref>[http://gostridge.net/page.php?pageid=14] {{dead link|date=August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sunniside, Sunderland|Sunniside]] area plays host to a number of smaller theatrical workshops and production houses, as well as the ''Theatre Restaurant'', which combines a dining experience with a rolling programme of musical theatre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/local/all-news/restaurant-puts-entertainment-on-menu-1-1136283 |title=Restaurant puts entertainment on menu |newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]] |date=17 August 2007 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Twin towns and sister cities===\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the United Kingdom}}\nSunderland is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[Harbin]], China<ref name=\"Harbin-Sunderland link\">{{cite web|url=http://en.ichtf.com/news_2008.php?id=47248|title=Harbin is linking up with Sunderland|access-date=8 August 2013|work=Harbin News Web|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301222614/http://en.ichtf.com/news_2008.php?id=47248|archive-date=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sunderland Echo\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/China-opens-a-window-on.5276489.jp |title=China opens a window on Sunderland&nbsp;\u2013 Local |publisher=Sunderland Echo |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=16 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521180257/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/China-opens-a-window-on.5276489.jp |archive-date=21 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[Saint-Nazaire]], France<ref name=\"Archant twinning 3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705094933/http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|title=British towns twinned with French towns ''[via WaybackMachine.com]''|accessdate=20 July 2013|archivedate=5 July 2013|work=Archant Community Media Ltd}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington, D.C.]], United States<ref name=DCsite>{{cite web|url=http://os.dc.gov/service/dc-sister-cities|title=DC Sister Cities - os|website=os.dc.gov|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Essen]], Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2804 |title=Sunderland City Council: Further Information on Essen |publisher=Sunderland.gov.uk |date= |access-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422095518/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2804 |archive-date=22 April 2016  }}</ref>\n\nSunderland is the only city that is not a capital of country twinned with Washington, D.C., as it includes the town of [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], the ancestral home of George Washington's family.<ref name=DCsite/>\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Stadium of light from distance.jpg|thumb|right|View of the Stadium of Light from the opposite side of the River Wear.]]\nThe only professional sporting team in Sunderland is the [[Association football|football]] team, [[Sunderland A.F.C.]], which was formed in 1879 and was elected to the [[Football League]] in 1890.<ref>Sunderland : the Complete Record / Rob Mason. Breedon Books, 2005. pp 16-17</ref> The club, which currently plays in [[EFL League One]] following consecutive relegations from the [[FA Premier League]] and the [[EFL Championship]], is based at the 49,000 seat capacity [[Stadium of Light]], which was opened in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAFC Previous Grounds / History / Previous Grounds |url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=3911|work=SAFC website |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> Sunderland A.F.C also has the north-east's top women's football team, [[Sunderland A.F.C. Women]], They currently play in the 3rd tier of English women's football \u2013 [[FA Women's National League North]]. Despite their financial struggles. Sunderland were league champions six times within the [[The Football League|Football League's]] first half century, but have not achieved this accolade since 1936. Their other notable successes include [[FA Cup]] glory in 1937 and 1973 and winning the [[Football League First Division|Division One]] title with a (then) [[Football in England|English league]] record of 105 points in 1999.\n\nSunderland AFC's longest stadium occupancy so far was of [[Roker Park]] for 99 years beginning in 1898, with relocation taking place due to the stadium's confined location and the need to build an all-seater stadium. The initial relocation plan, announced in the early 1990s, had been for a stadium to be situated alongside the Nissan factory, but these were abandoned in favour of the Stadium of Light at [[Monkwearmouth]] on the site of a [[colliery]] on the banks of the River Wear that had closed at the end of 1993.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sunderland Cricket Club|url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=3911|work=SAFC website |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> The city also has two non-league sides, [[Sunderland Ryhope Community Association F.C.]] of the [[Northern League Division Two]] and Sunderland West End FC of the [[Wearside League]], who play at the Ford Quarry Complex.\n\nSunderland's amateur [[Rugby football|Rugby]] and [[Cricket]] clubs are both based in [[Ashbrooke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SAFC Previous Grounds|url=http://vega.sund.ac.uk/ashbrooke/cricket.cfm|work=vega.sund.ac.uk website|date=2 January 2008|access-date=3 April 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20060507000445/http://vega.sund.ac.uk/ashbrooke/cricket.cfm|archive-date=7 May 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A Very Warm Welcome to Sunderland RFC. The Home of Sunderland Rugby Union|url=http://www.sunderlandrufc.com|work=sunderlandrufc.com website|date=2 January 2008|access-date=3 April 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310072625/http://www.sunderlandrufc.com/|archive-date=10 March 2008}}</ref> The Ashbrooke ground was opened on 30 May 1887.\n\nThe Crowtree Leisure Centre has also played host to a number of important boxing matches and snooker championships including the 2003 Snooker World Trickshot and Premier League Final. In September 2005, [[BBC]] TV cameras captured international boxing bouts featuring local boxers [[David Dolan]], Stuart Kennedy and [[Tony Jeffries]]. The latter became Sunderland's first Olympic medallist when he won a [[bronze medal]] in the light heavyweight boxing category for [[Great Britain and Northern Ireland]] at the [[2008 Beijing Olympic Games]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\n[[File:Sunderland Aquatic Centre - geograph.org.uk - 1665091.jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland Aquatic Centre, located next to the Stadium of Light, holds the only Olympic-sized swimming pool in North-East England]]\nOn 18 April 2008, the Sunderland Aquatic Centre was opened. Constructed at a cost of \u00a320 million, it is the only Olympic sized 50&nbsp;m pool between [[Leeds]] and [[Edinburgh]] and has six diving boards, which stand at 1&nbsp;m, 3&nbsp;m and 5&nbsp;m.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/Olympic-splashout-spectacular.3991372.jp|title=Sunderland Echo Olympic splash-out spectacular|work=Sunderland Echo}}</ref>\n\nAthletics is also a popular sport in the city, with Sunderland Harriers Athletics Club based at Silksworth Sports Complex. 800&nbsp;m runner Gavin Massingham represented the club at the AAA Championships in 2005. On 25 June 2006, the first Great Women's Run took place along Sunderland's coastline. Among the field which lined up to start the race were Olympic silver medallists [[Sonia O'Sullivan]] of the [[Republic of Ireland]] and [[Gete Wami]] of [[Ethiopia]], who eventually won the race. The race quickly became an annual fixture in the city's sporting schedule, with races in 2007 and 2008. In 2009, the race will be relaunched as the [[Great North 10K]] Run, allowing male competitors to take part for the first time, on 12 July.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great North 10K moves|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/wear/hi/front_page/newsid_9393000/9393838.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{Main|List of people from Sunderland}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North East England}}\n* [[Boxing Day Dip|Sunderland's Boxing Day dip]]\n* [[The North Dock Tufa]]\n* [[List of important dates in the history of Sunderland]]\n* [[The New Monkey]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Category:Sunderland|Sunderland}}\n*{{Commons category-inline|Sunderland}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Sunderland}}\n{{Navboxes |list1=\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre = Sunderland\n| North = [[South Tyneside]]\n| Northeast = [[North Sea]]\n| East = [[North Sea]]\n| Southeast = [[North Sea]]\n| South = [[Seaham]], [[Easington, County Durham|Easington]]\n| Southwest = [[Durham, England|Durham]], [[Chester-le-street]].\n| West = [[Gateshead]], [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]]\n| Northwest = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n}}\n{{City of Sunderland}}\n{{Tyne and wear}}\n{{Coastal settlements\n|place = Tyne and Wear\n|settlement = Wearmouth, Sunderland\n|anticlockwise = [[Roker]]\n|clockwise = [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]]\n}}\n{{T&W places}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n}}\n\n[[Category:Sunderland| ]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in North East England]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Towns in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:City of Sunderland]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the city in England}}{{Merge from|Sunderland Blitz|date=March 2020|discuss=Talk:Sunderland#Merge_proposal_of_Sunderland_Blitz}}{{More citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Sunderland\n|country = England\n|region= North East England\n|static_image_name=SunderlandMontage.jpg\n|static_image_width=280\n|static_image_caption=Clockwise, from top: Echo 24 and the [[Wearmouth Bridge]], Roker Lighthouse, the [[National Glass Centre]], [[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]], Fulwell Mill and [[Penshaw Monument]]\n|population = 174,286\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref name=\"BUA\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1119884905|title=Sunderland Built-up area|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n|population_demonym=[[Mackem]]\n|os_grid_reference= NZ395575\n|coordinates = {{coord|54.9061|-1.38113|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position=  left\n|post_town= SUNDERLAND\n|postcode_area= SR\n|postcode_district = SR1\u2013SR6\n|dial_code= 0191\n|constituency_westminster= [[Houghton and Sunderland South (UK Parliament constituency)|Houghton and Sunderland South]]\n|constituency_westminster1=[[Sunderland Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland Central]]\n|constituency_westminster2=[[Washington and Sunderland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Washington and Sunderland West]]\n|london_distance= 240&nbsp;mi&nbsp;(387&nbsp;km)&nbsp;[[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n|metropolitan_borough= [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]]\n|metropolitan_county = [[Tyne and Wear]]\n}}\n'''Sunderland''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Sunderland.ogg|\u02c8|s|\u028c|n|d|\u0259r|l|\u0259|n|d}}) is a city at the centre of the [[City of Sunderland]] [[metropolitan borough]], in [[Tyne and Wear]], England, 12 miles northeast of [[Durham, England|Durham]] and 10 miles southeast of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], at the mouth of the [[River Wear]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/roker.htm|title=Roker (Whitburn South) Beach|accessdate=18 August 2017 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/seaburn-beach.htm|title=Seaburn Beach (Whitburn North)|accessdate=18 August 2017 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebeachguide.co.uk/north-east-england/tyne-and-wear/hendon-south-sunderland.htm|title=Hendon South Beach (Sunderland)|accessdate=2 January 2018 |publisher=UK Beach Guide|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in [[County Durham]], there were three original settlements by the mouth of the River Wear on the site of modern-day Sunderland. On the north side of the river, [[Monkwearmouth]] was settled in 674 when [[Ecgfrith of Northumbria|King Ecgfrith of Northumbria]] granted land to [[Benedict Biscop]] to found [[Monkwearmouth\u2013Jarrow Abbey|Monkwearmouth Monastery]]. In 685, Ecgfrith further granted Biscop the land adjacent to the monastery on the south side of the river. As the river separated this land from the monastic community, it was henceforth referred to as the \"sunder-land\", and would grow as a fishing settlement before being granted a charter in 1179.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://englandsnortheast.co.uk/Sunderland.html|title=Old Sunderland History|website=englandsnortheast.co.uk|access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref> West of the medieval village of Sunderland on the south bank, [[Bishopwearmouth]] was founded in 930.\n\nSunderland grew as a port, trading [[coal]] and [[salt]]. Ships began to be built on the river in the 14th century. By the 19th century, the port of Sunderland had absorbed Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth, owing to the growing economic importance of the shipbuilding docks. Following the decline of the city's traditional industries in the late 20th century, the area grew into a commercial centre for the automotive industry, science and technology and the service sector.\n\n[[Bede]], sometimes called the father of English history, began his monastic career at Monkwearmouth monastery in Sunderland, before moving to the newly founded Jarrow monastery in 685 (these monasteries together formed the dual [[Monkwearmouth-Jarrow Abbey]]). It therefore seems likely that he was born in or near Sunderland. Indeed, Bede later wrote that he was \"\u00e1cenned on ''sundorlande'' \u00fe\u00e6s ylcan mynstres\" (born in a ''separate land'' of this same monastery); here, \"sundorlande\" translates literally as \"separate land\" but could refer to the village of Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bosworthtoller.com/058721 |title=Sundor-land (supplementary) |last=Bosworth |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Bosworth |editor-last=Toller |editor-first=Thomas Northcote |editor-link=Thomas Northcote Toller |editor2-last=Christ |editor2-first=Sean |editor3-last=Tich\u00fd |editor3-first=Ond\u0159ej |publisher=Faculty of Arts, [[Charles University in Prague]] |date=March 21, 2010 |website=[[An Anglo-Saxon Dictionary]] Online.  |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bosworthtoller.com/029360 |title=Sundor-land |last=Bosworth |first=Joseph |author-link=Joseph Bosworth |editor-last=Toller |editor-first=Thomas Northcote |editor-link=Thomas Northcote Toller |editor2-last=Christ |editor2-first=Sean |editor3-last=Tich\u00fd |editor3-first=Ond\u0159ej |publisher=Faculty of Arts, [[Charles University in Prague]] |date=March 21, 2010 |website=[[An Anglo-Saxon Dictionary]] Online.  |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, it is possible that Sunderland was later named in honour of Bede's connections to the area, by people familiar with this statement of his.\n\nA person from Sunderland is sometimes known as a [[Mackem]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2005/06/21/wordhunt_feature.shtml|title=The Mackem Wordhunt|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=BBC|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/bulletin_board/18/messages/814.html |title=The word Mackem origins|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=Phrases.org website|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandsnortheast.co.uk/SunderlandMackems.html|title=Sunderland Mackem Origin|accessdate=19 August 2017 |publisher=englandsnortheast.co.uk|year=2016}}</ref> However, as this term originated as recently as the early 1980s, its use and acceptance by Sunderland residents, particularly among the older generations, is not universal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wp.sunderland.ac.uk/seagullcity/mackem/|title=Mackem|accessdate=19 August 2017 |publisher=Seagull City|year=2017}}</ref> At one time, Sunderland-built ships were called \"Jamies\", in contrast with those from Tyneside, which were known as \"Geordies\", although in the case of \"Jamie\" it is not known whether this was ever extended to people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/sunderland-mackems/|title=Sunderland : 'Mackems'|publisher=England's North East|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Northumbria.rise.600.700.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The areas that are now Sunderland were once part of the Kingdom of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]].]]\n\n===Early history===\n{{Main|Monkwearmouth\u2013Jarrow Abbey}}\nThe earliest inhabitants of the Sunderland area were [[Stone Age]] [[hunter-gatherer]]s and artifacts from this era have been discovered, including [[microliths]] found during excavations at [[St Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Sunderland |edition=2nd |year=2001 |isbn=0-9525122-6-2 |author=Glen Lyndon Dodds |page=5}}</ref> During the final phase of the Stone Age, the [[Neolithic period]] (c. 4000 \u2013 c. 2000 BC), [[Hastings Hill]], on the western outskirts of Sunderland, was a focal point of activity and a place of burial and ritual significance. Evidence includes the former presence of a [[cursus]] monument.<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Sunderland |edition=2nd |year=2001 |isbn=0-9525122-6-2 |author=Glen Lyndon Dodds |page=6}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed the [[Brigantes]] inhabited the area around the [[River Wear]] in the pre- and post-[[Roman Empire|Roman]] era. There is a long-standing local legend that there was a Roman settlement on the south bank of the River Wear on what is the site of the former Vaux Brewery, although no archaeological investigation has taken place.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3200659.stm|title=Brewery may hold Roman answers|accessdate=22 July 2009 |publisher=BBC News|date=2 September 2003}}</ref>\n\n====Early Middle Ages: Anglo-Saxon Northumbria====\n[[File:st peters sunderland.jpg|thumb|left|250px|St Peter's Church in Monkwearmouth. Only the porch and part of the west wall are what remain of the original monastery built in 674.]]\nRecorded settlements at the mouth of the Wear date to 674, when an [[Anglo-Saxon]] nobleman, [[Benedict Biscop]], granted land by King [[Ecgfrith of Northumbria]], founded the Wearmouth\u2013Jarrow (''St. Peter's'') [[monastery]] on the north bank of the river \u2013 an area that became known as Monkwearmouth. Biscop's monastery was the first built of stone in [[Northumbria]]. He employed glaziers from [[France]] and in doing so he re-established [[glass making]] in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/CustomPages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31748|title=Museum and Winter Gardens \u2013 Look At Glass|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo|year=2005 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080513072206/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/CustomPages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31748 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 May 2008}}</ref>\nIn 686 the community was taken over by [[Ceolfrid]], and Wearmouth\u2013Jarrow became a major centre of learning and knowledge in [[Anglo-Saxon England]] with a library of around 300 volumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weardaleway.wanadoo.co.uk/history1.html|title=Sunderland History|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Weardaleway website|year=2005|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131032803/http://www.weardaleway.wanadoo.co.uk/history1.html|archive-date=31 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Codex Amiatinus]], described by White as the 'finest book in the world',<ref>[[Henry Julian White|H. J. White]], ''The Codex Amiatinus and its Birthplace'', in: Studia Biblica et Ecclesiasctica (Oxford 1890), Vol. II, p. 273.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09227b.htm |title=Libraries |work=Catholic Encyclopedia |accessdate=23 January 2007}}</ref> was created at the monastery and was likely worked on by [[Bede]], who was born at Wearmouth in 673.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedesworld.co.uk/academic-bede.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030604082808/http://bedesworld.co.uk/academic-bede.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 June 2003|title=Academic \u2013 The Venerable Bede|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Bede's World museum|year=2008}}</ref> This is one of the oldest monasteries still standing in England.  While at the monastery, Bede completed the ''[[Historia ecclesiastica gentis Anglorum]]'' ''(The Ecclesiastical History of the English People)'' in 731, a feat which earned him the title ''The father of English history.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/exhibns/month/jan2001.html|title=Book of the Month, Bede Wrings on the Calendar|accessdate=3 April 2008 |publisher=University of Glasgow|year=2001}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 8th century, the [[Vikings]] raided the coast, and by the middle of the 9th century, the monastery had been abandoned. Lands on the south side of the river were granted to the [[Bishop of Durham]] by [[Athelstan|Athelstan of England]] in 930; these became known as Bishopwearmouth and included settlements such as [[Ryhope]] which fall within the modern boundary of Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/implementation/conservation/conservationwalks/bishopwearmouth/bishop.origins.asp |title=Origins of Bishopwearmouth |accessdate=23 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201702/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/implementation/conservation/conservationwalks/bishopwearmouth/bishop.origins.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wearsideonline.com/ryhope_village.html|title=Ryhope Village|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Wearsideonline website|year=2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316021942/http://www.wearsideonline.com/ryhope_village.html|archive-date=16 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Medieval developments after the Norman conquest====\nIn 1100, Bishopwearmouth parish included a [[fishing]] village at the southern mouth of the river (now the East End) known as 'Soender-land' (which evolved into 'Sunderland').<ref>{{cite news |title=What's in a name? |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=1512&ArticleID=1962253 |work=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=17 January 2007  }}{{dead link|date=October 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> This settlement was granted a [[charter]] in 1179 by [[Hugh Pudsey]], then the [[Bishop of Durham]] (who had quasi-[[monarchical]] power within the [[County Palatine of Durham|County Palatine]]);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/page42.htm|title=The North East England History Pages|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=David Simpson|work=The Millennium History of North East England|year=1991}}</ref> the charter gave its merchants the same rights as those of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]], but it nevertheless took time for Sunderland to develop as a [[port]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Newcastle Coal |url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/NewcastleCoal.html |website=England's North East |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> Fishing was the main commercial activity at the time: mainly [[herring]] in the 13th century, then [[salmon]] in the 14th and 15th centuries.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\">{{cite book |last1=Pevsner |first1=Nikolaus |last2=Williamson |first2=Elizabeth |title=The Buildings of England: County Durham |date=1983 |publisher=Penguin |location=London |edition=2nd}}</ref> From 1346 [[shipbuilding|ships were being built]] at Wearmouth, by a merchant named Thomas Menville,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissunderland.com/history/a_shipbuilding_tradition.asp |title=Sunderland Ship Building |access-date=3 April 2008 |work=This is Sunderland website |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814171112/http://www.thisissunderland.com/history/a_shipbuilding_tradition.asp |archive-date=14 August 2007 }}</ref> and by 1396 a small amount of coal was being exported.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" />\n\nRapid growth of the port was initially prompted by the salt trade.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Salt exports from Sunderland are recorded from as early as the 13th century, but In 1589, [[Salt pan (evaporation)|salt pans]] were laid at Bishopwearmouth Panns (the modern-day name of the area the pans occupied is Pann's Bank, on the river bank between the city centre and the East End).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.localhistories.org/sunderland.html|title=A Brief History of Sunderland|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Tim Lambert|year=2008}}</ref> Large vats of [[seawater]] were heated using coal; as the water evaporated the salt remained. As coal was required to heat the salt pans, a [[coal mining]] community began to emerge. Only poor quality coal was used in salt panning; better quality coal was traded via the port, which subsequently began to grow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/coal/1100_1500/index.html |title=North East History, Early Coal Mining |access-date=3 April 2008 |work=The Northern Echo |year=2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927173408/http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/coal/1100_1500/index.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===17th century===\nBoth salt and coal continued to be exported through the 17th century, but the coal trade grew significantly (2-3,000 tons of coal were exported from Sunderland in the year 1600; by 1680 this had increased to 180,000 tons).<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Because of the difficulty for colliers trying to navigate the shallow waters of the Wear, coal mined further inland was loaded onto keels (large, flat-bottomed boats) and taken downriver to the waiting colliers. The keels were manned by a close-knit group of workers known as '[[keelmen]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasthistory.co.uk/the_north_east/history/didyouknow/12.html|title=Did you know?|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=North East History website|year=2003}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn 1634 a charter was granted by Bishop [[Thomas Morton (bishop)|Thomas Morton]], which [[Municipal corporation|incorporated]] the inhabitants of the '[[Ancient borough|antient borough]]' of Sunderland as the 'Mayor, Aldermen and Commonality' of the Borough and granted the privilege of a market and an annual fair. While, as a consequence, a [[mayor]] and twelve [[aldermen]] were appointed, and a common council established, their establishment does not seem to have survived the ensuing [[English Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" />\n\nBefore the 1st English civil war the North, with the exclusion of [[Kingston upon Hull]], declared for the King. In 1644 the North was captured by parliament.<ref name=civilwar>{{cite web | last = History.com Staff | title = English civil wars | website = history.com | publisher = A+E Networks | year = 2009 | url = http://www.history.com/topics/british-history/english-civil-wars | accessdate = 29 July 2015 }}</ref> The villages that later become Sunderland, were taken in March 1644.<ref name=\"civWar1644\">{{cite book | last = Dodds | first = Derek | title = Northumbia\u2026 (Battlefield Britain) | publisher = Leo Cooper Ltd (20 Oct 2005) | date = 20 October 2005 | location = England | page = 139 | url = https://www.amazon.co.uk/Northumbria-War-Conflict-Northumberland-Battlefield/dp/1844151492/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1433176389&sr=1-1&keywords=9781844151493| isbn = 1844151492}}</ref> One artifact of the English civil war near this area was the long trench; a tactic of later warfare.<ref name=\"civWar1644\"/> In the village of [[Offerton, Tyne and Wear|Offerton]] roughly three miles inland from the area, skirmishes occurred.<ref>{{cite news |title=''A History of Sunderland'' (second edition, 2001), Glen Lyndon Dodds, pp. 46\u201348}}</ref><ref name=tren>{{cite web | title = Offerton, site of Civil War skirmish - Details| website = twsitelines.info| publisher = | year = | url = http://www.twsitelines.info/SMR/25| accessdate = 19 August 2016 }}</ref> Parliament also blockaded the [[River Tyne]], crippling the Newcastle coal trade which allowed the coal trade of the area to flourish for a short period.\n\nIn 1669, after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]], King [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] granted [[letters patent]] to one Edward Andrew, [[Esq.]] to 'build a pier and erect a lighthouse or lighthouses and cleanse the harbour of Sunderland', and authorised the levying of a [[tonnage]] [[Duty (economics)|duty]] on shipping in order to raise the necessary funds;<ref name=\"Sykes1833\">{{cite book |last1=Sykes |first1=John |title=Local Records: Or, Historical Register of Remarkable Events, which Have Occurred in Northumberland and Durham, Newcastle Upon Tyne, and Berwick Upon Tweed (vol. 1) |url=https://archive.org/details/localrecordsorh02sykegoog |date=1833 |publisher=J. Sykes |location=Newcaste |page=[https://archive.org/details/localrecordsorh02sykegoog/page/n435 114]}}</ref> however it took time before these improvements were realized.\n\nThere is evidence of a growing number of shipbuilders or boatbuilders being active on the River Wear in the late 17th century: among others, the banking family Goodchilds opened a building yard in 1672 (it eventually closed when the bank went out of business in 1821); and in 1691 one Thomas Burn aged 17 is recorded as having taken over the running of a yard from his mother.<ref name=\"JAMarr\">{{cite web |last1=Marr |first1=J. A. |title=A History of Shipbuilding on the Wear |url=http://www.searlecanada.org/sunderland/sunderland160.html |website=The Sunderland Site |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===18th century===\n[[File:10 Church Street (13920301659).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Rare surviving early 18th-century merchant's house (later used as a warehouse) in Church Street, Sunderland.]]\n\n====River works====\nThe River Wear Commission was formed in 1717 in response to the growing prosperity of Sunderland as a port.<ref name=\"PoSHistory\">{{cite web |title=Port History |url=https://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/port-history |website=Port of Sunderland |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> Under the Board of Commissioners (a committee of local land owners, ship owners, colliery owners and merchants) a succession of civil engineers adapted the natural riverscape to meet the needs of maritime trade and shipbuilding. Their first major harbour work was the construction in stone of the South Pier (later known as the Old South Pier), begun in 1723 with the aim of diverting the river channel away from [[sandbanks]];<ref name=\"Jones2014\">{{cite book|last1=Jones|first1=Robin|title=Lighthouses of the North East Coast|date=2014|publisher=Halsgrove|location=Wellington, Somerset}}</ref> the building of the South Pier continued until 1759. By 1748 the river was being manually dredged.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\" /> A northern counterpart to the South Pier was not yet in place; instead, a temporary breakwater was formed at around this time, consisting of a row of piles driven into the seabed interspersed with old keelboats. From 1786 work began on a more permanent North Pier (which was later known as the Old North Pier): it was formed from a wooden frame, filled with stones and faced with masonry, and eventually extended {{convert|1,500|ft|abbr=on}} into the sea. The work was initially overseen by Robert Stout (the Wear Commissioners' Engineer from 1781 to 1795). In 1794 a lighthouse was built at the seaward end, by which time around half the pier had been enclosed in masonry;<ref name=\"Jones2014\" /> it was completed in 1802.\n\nBy the start of the 18th century the banks of the Wear were described as being studded with small shipyards, as far as the tide flowed.<ref name=\"JAMarr\" /> After 1717, measures having been taken to increase the depth of the river, Sunderland's shipbuilding trade grew substantially (in parallel with its coal exports).<ref name=\"Davis1962,2012\">{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Ralph |title=The Rise of the English Shipping Industry in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=62 |edition=2nd}}</ref> A number of warships were built, alongside many commercial sailing ships. By the middle of the century the town was probably the premier shipbuilding centre in Britain.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Encyclopaedia Britannica: Micropaedia |date=1983}}</ref> By 1788 Sunderland was Britain's fourth largest port (by measure of tonnage) after London, Newcastle and Liverpool; among these it was the leading coal exporter (though it did not rival Newcastle in terms of home coal trade).<ref name=\"Davis1962,2012\" /> Still further growth was driven across the region, towards the end of the century, by London's insatiable demand for coal during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]].<ref name=\"JAMarr\" />\n\nSunderland's third-biggest export, after coal and salt, was glass.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> The town's first modern glassworks were established in the 1690s and the industry grew through the 17th century.<ref name=\"BBCGlassmaking\">{{cite web |title=Glassmaking on Wearside |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2008/02/04/glassmaking_wearside_04022008_feature.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> Its flourishing was aided by trading ships bringing good-quality sand (as [[ballast]]) from [[the Baltic]] and elsewhere which, together with locally available limestone (and coal to fire the furnaces) was a key ingredient in the [[glassmaking]] process. Other industries that developed alongside the river included [[lime burning]] and [[pottery making]] (the town's first commercial pottery manufactory, the Garrison Pottery, had opened in old Sunderland in 1750).<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\n[[File:The Ropery, Sunderland (geograph 3880645).jpg|thumb|right|Grimshaw and Webster's Patent Ropery of 1797: the world's oldest factory for machine-made rope.]]\nThe world's first steam [[dredger]] was built in Sunderland in 1796-7 and put to work on the river the following year.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\">{{cite journal |last1=Skempton |first1=A. W. |title=A History of the Steam Dredger, 1797\u20131830 |journal=Transactions of the Newcomen Society |date=1974 |volume=47 |issue=1 |pages=97\u2013116}}</ref> Designed by Stout's successor as Engineer, Jonathan Pickernell jr (in post from 1795 to 1804), it consisted of a set of 'bag and spoon' dredgers driven by a tailor-made 4-horsepower [[Boulton & Watt]] beam engine. It was designed to dredge to a maximum depth of {{convert|10|ft|abbr=on}} below the waterline and remained in operation until 1804, when its constituent parts were sold as separate lots.<ref name=\"Skempton1974\" /> Onshore, numerous small industries supported the business of the burgeoning port. In 1797 the world's first patent ropery (producing machine-made [[rope]], rather than using a [[ropewalk]]) was built in Sunderland, using a steam-powered hemp-spinning machine which had been devised by a local schoolmaster, Richard Fothergill, in 1793;<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> the ropery building still stands, in the Deptford area of the city.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Websters Ropery (Grade II listing) |num=1207121 |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Urban developments====\n[[File:HolyTrinitySunderland-apse.jpg|thumb|left|Holy Trinity church, built in 1719]]\nIn 1719, the parish of Sunderland was carved from the densely populated east end of Bishopwearmouth by the establishment of a new parish church, [[Holy Trinity Church, Sunderland]] (today also known as Sunderland Old Parish Church). Later, in 1769, St John's Church was built as a [[chapel of ease]] within Holy Trinity parish; built by a local coal fitter, John Thornhill, it stood in Prospect Row to the north-east of the parish church. (St John's was demolished in 1972.)<ref>{{cite web |title=Photo: blue plaque |url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3327052 |website=Geograph |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> By 1720 the port area was completely built up, with large houses and gardens facing the Town Moor and the sea, and labourers' dwellings vying with manufactories alongside the river.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> The three original settlements of Wearmouth (Bishopwearmouth, Monkwearmouth and Sunderland) had begun to combine, driven by the success of the port of Sunderland and salt panning and shipbuilding along the banks of the river. Around this time, Sunderland was known as 'Sunderland-near-the-Sea'.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shegog |first=Eric |url=http://www2.citysun.ac.uk/minster/history.htm |title=Sunderland Minster |publisher=City of Sunderland College |access-date=9 December 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627223638/http://www2.citysun.ac.uk/minster/history.htm |archive-date=27 June 2008  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plan of Sunderland, Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth, 1817.jpg|thumb|right|Early 19th century map showing the 18th-century barracks, battery and piers to the east, with the bridge and nearby 'Pann Field' to the west.]]\nBy 1770 Sunderland had spread westwards along its High Street to join up with Bishopwearmouth.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> In 1796 Bishopwearmouth in turn gained a physical link with Monkwearmouth following the construction of a bridge, the [[Wearmouth Bridge]], which was the world's second iron bridge (after the famous span at [[Ironbridge]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hodstw.org.uk/sunderland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918193101/https://www.hodstw.org.uk/sunderland |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 September 2015 |title=Short History of Sunderland |publisher=www.hodstw.org.uk |date= |access-date=3 June 2016 }}</ref> It was built at the instigation of [[Rowland Burdon (died 1838)|Rowland Burdon]], the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[County Durham (UK Parliament constituency)|County Durham]], and described by [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] as being 'a triumph of the new metallurgy and engineering ingenuity [...] of superb elegance'.<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" /> Spanning the river in a single sweep of {{convert|236|ft}}, it was over twice the length of the earlier bridge at Ironbridge but only three-quarters the weight. At the time of building, it was the biggest single-span bridge in the world;<ref>{{cite web |work=Wearside Onliine |title=Sunderland Wearmouth Bridge |url=http://www.wearsideonline.com/Sunderland_Wearmouth_Bridge.html |access-date=24 September 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127114349/http://www.wearsideonline.com/sunderland_wearmouth_bridge.html |archive-date=27 November 2011  }}</ref> and because Sunderland had developed on a plateau above the river, it never suffered from the problem of interrupting the passage of high-masted vessels.\n\n====Defences====\nDuring the [[War of Jenkins' Ear]] a pair of [[Gun battery|gun batteries]] were built (in 1742 and 1745) on the shoreline to the south of the South Pier, to defend the river from attack (a further battery was built on the cliff top in Roker, ten years later).<ref name=\"LimeLand\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland Under Attack |url=http://www.limestonelandscapes.info/media/12325/Sunderland-Under-Attack/pdf/SunderlandUnderAttack.pdf |website=Limestone Landscapes |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> One of the pair was washed away by the sea in 1780, but the other was expanded during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and became known as the Black Cat Battery.<ref name=\"VCHDefPort\">{{cite web |title=Defending the Port |url=https://www.victoriacountyhistory.ac.uk/explore/items/defending-port |website=Victoria County History |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> In 1794 [[Sunderland Barracks]] were built, behind the battery, close to what was then the tip of the headland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandsnortheast.co.uk/Sunderland.html|title=Sunderland : 'Old Sunderland'|publisher=Wearside History|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:Sunderland Harbour, 19th century (Entrance to Sunderland Harbour) by Stuart Henry Bell.jpg|thumb|right|View from the South Pier in the first half of the 19th century.]]\nIn 1802 a new, {{convert|72|ft|abbr=on}} high octagonal stone lighthouse was built on the end of the newly finished North Pier, designed by the chief Engineer Jonathan Pickernell. At the same time he built a lighthouse on the South Pier, which showed a red light (or by day a red flag) when the tide was high enough for ships to pass into the river.<ref name=\"Jones2014\" /> From 1820 Pickernell's lighthouse was lit by gas from its own gasometer.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" /> In 1840 work began to extend the North Pier to {{convert|1,770|ft|abbr=on}} and the following year its lighthouse was moved in one piece, on a wooden cradle, to its new seaward end, remaining lit each night throughout the process.<ref name=\"Jones2014\" />\n\n====Local government====\n[[File:The Exchange Building (14103741331).jpg|thumb|left|The Exchange Building (1812-14) in High Street East.]]\nIn 1809 an [[Act of Parliament]] was passed creating an Improvement Commission, for 'paving, lighting, cleansing, watching and otherwise improving the town of Sunderland';<ref name=\"Burnett1830\">{{cite book |last1=Burnett |first1=James |title=The history of the town and port of Sunderland, and the parishes of Bishopwearmouth and Monkwearmouth |date=1830 |publisher=J. S. Burnett |location=Sunderland |page=44}}</ref> this provided the beginnings of a structure of [[local government]] for the township as a whole.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\">{{cite book |last1=Johnson |first1=Michael |last2=Potts |first2=Graham |title=The Architecture of Sunderland 1700-1914 |date=2013 |publisher=The History Press |location=Stroud, Gloucs.}}</ref> Commissioners were appointed, with the power to levy contributions towards the works detailed in the Act, and in 1812-14 the Exchange Building was built, funded by public subscription, to serve as a combined Town Hall, Watch House, Market Hall, Magistrate's Court, Post Office and News Room. It became a regular gathering place for merchants conducting business, and the public rooms on the first floor were available for public functions when not being used for meetings of the Commissioners. By 1830 the Commissioners had made a number of improvements, ranging from the establishment a police force to installing gas lighting across much of the town.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" />\n\nIn other aspects, however, [[Local government]] was still divided between the three parishes (Holy Trinity Church, Sunderland, [[Sunderland Minster|St. Michael's, Bishopwearmouth]], and [[St Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth|St. Peter's, Monkwearmouth]]) and when [[cholera]] broke out in 1831, the \"select vestrymen\", as the church councilmen were called, were unable to cope with the [[epidemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/longview/longview_20030415.shtml|title=BBC Diary of an Epidemic|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=BBC website|year=2003}}</ref> Sunderland, a main trading port at the time, was the first British town to be struck with the 'Indian cholera' epidemic.<ref>''Diary of an Epidemic (Cholera)'', [[BBC Radio 4]], [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/longview/longview_20030415.shtml]</ref> The first victim, William Sproat, died on 23 October 1831. Sunderland was put into quarantine, and the port was blockaded, but in December of that year the disease spread to [[Gateshead]] and from there, it rapidly made its way across the country, killing an estimated 32,000 people; among those to die was Sunderland's Naval hero [[Jack Crawford (sailor)|Jack Crawford]]. (The novel ''The Dress Lodger'' by American author [[Sheri Holman]] is set in Sunderland during the epidemic.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Jack%20Crawford.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011202836/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Jack%20Crawford.pdf|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 October 2007|title=Who was Jack Crawford?|access-date=3 April 2008 |publisher=Sunderland Council |year=2005|format=PDF }}</ref>\n\nDemands for [[democracy]] and organised town government saw the three parishes incorporated as the Borough of Sunderland in 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2003/3/10/100809.html|title=Burning Questions|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=The Northern Echo|year=2003}}</ref> Later, the Sunderland Borough Act of 1851 abolished the Improvement Commission and vested its powers in the new Corporation.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" />\n\n====Coal, staiths, railways and docks====\n[[File:Sunderland dock (opening 1850).jpg|thumb|right|The opening of Hudson Dock on 20 June 1850; on the left the staiths of the York, Newcastle & Berwick Railway.]]\nIn the early nineteenth century 'the three great proprietors of collieries upon the Wear [were] [[Lord Durham]], the [[Marquis of Londonderry]] and the [[Hetton-le-Hole|Hetton]] Company'.<ref name=\"Burnett1830\" /> In 1822 the [[Hetton colliery railway]] was opened, linking the company's collieries with [[staith]]s ('Hetton Staiths') on the riverside at Bishopwearmouth, where [[coal drops]] delivered the coal directly into waiting ships. Engineered by [[George Stephenson]], it was the first railway in the world to be operated without animal power, and at the time (albeit briefly) was the longest railway in the world.<ref name=\"ETHetColRly\">{{cite web |title=Hetton Colliery Railway |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1464 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref> At the same time Lord Durham began establishing rail links to an adjacent set of staiths ('Lambton Staiths'). Lord Londonderry, on the other hand, continued conveying his coal downriver on keels; but he was working on establishing his own separate port down the coast at [[Seaham Harbour]].\n\n[[File:North Dock, Sunderland (19873625392).jpg|thumb|left|North Dock in 1957; the steam-powered wood yard to the right remained operational till 1990.<ref>{{cite web |title=Armstrong, Addison & Co, Timber Merchants, Sunderland |url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/7046356b-9144-4a29-a0e7-fbaf8170d2c4 |website=The National Archives |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>]]\nAlthough the volume of coal exports were increasing, there was a growing concern that without the establishment of a purpose-built dock Sunderland would start losing trade to Newcastle and [[Hartlepool]].<ref name=\"ETNthDock\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland North Dock, site of |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1133 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The colliery rail links were on the south side of the river, but Sir [[Sir Hedworth Williamson, 7th Baronet|Hedworth Williamson]], who owned much of the land on the north bank, seized the initiative. He formed the Wearmouth Dock Company in 1832, obtained a Royal Charter for establishing a dock at Monkwearmouth riverside, and engaged no less a figure than [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]] to provide designs (not only for docks but also for a double-deck [[suspension bridge]] to provide a rail link to the opposite side of the river). Building of the dock went ahead (albeit the smallest of Brunel's proposals) but not of the bridge; the resulting North Dock, opened in 1837, soon proved too small at {{convert|6|acre}}, and it suffered through lack of a direct rail link to the colliery lines south of the Wear (instead, it would be linked, by way of the [[Brandling Junction Railway]] from 1839, to collieries in the Gateshead area).<ref name=\"ETNthDock\" />\n\nAlso in Monkwearmouth, further upstream, work began in 1826 on sinking a pit in the hope of reaching the seams of coal (even though, at this location, they were deep underground). Seven years later, coal was struck at 180 fathoms;<ref name=\"DMM\">{{cite web |title=Wearmouth Colliery |url=http://www.dmm.org.uk/colliery/w001.htm |website=Durham Mining Museum |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> digging deeper, the Bensham seam was found the following year at 267 fathoms and in 1835 [[Wearmouth Colliery]], which was then the deepest mine in the world, began producing coal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wearmouth Colliery |url=https://www.aditnow.co.uk/documents/Wearmouth-Coal-Mine/Wearmouth-Colliery.pdf |website=AditNow: the site for mine explorers and mining historians |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> When the superior Hutton seam was reached, at a still greater depth in 1846, the mine (which had begun as a speculative enterprise by Messrs Pemberton and Thompson) began to be profitable.\n\n[[File:Sunderland Docks Office (13920362930).jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland Dock Company offices (1850 by John Murray) and the [[Gladstone Bridge (Sunderland)|Gladstone Swing Bridge]] of 1874.]]\nMeanwhile, south of the river, the [[Durham & Sunderland Railway]] Co. built a railway line across the Town Moor and established a passenger terminus there in 1836. In 1847 the line was bought by [[George Hudson]]'s [[York and Newcastle Railway]]. Hudson, nicknamed 'The Railway King', was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sunderland (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland]] and was already involved in a scheme to build a dock in the area. In 1846 he had formed the [[Sunderland Docks|Sunderland Dock Company]], which received parliamentary approval for the construction of a dock between the South Pier and Hendon Bay.<ref name=\"SundEcho16.3.17\">{{cite web |title=On the waterfront: First sea link with the docks |url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/on-the-waterfront-first-sea-link-with-the-docks-357798 |website=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The engineer overseeing the project was John Murray; the foundation stone for the entrance basin was laid in February 1848, and by the end of the year excavation of the new dock was largely complete, the spoil being used in the associated [[land reclamation]] works. Lined with limestone and entered from the river by way of a [[half tide dock|half tide basin]], the dock (later named Hudson Dock) was formally opened by Hudson on 20 June 1850.<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland South Docks |url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=1134 |website=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> Most of the dockside to the west was occupied with coal staiths linked to the railway line, but there was also a warehouse and granary built at the northern end by [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]] in 1856 (this, along with a second warehouse dating from the 1860s, was demolished in 1992).<ref>{{cite web |title=Nos 1 & 2 Warehouses, North Hudson Docks, Sunderland, Tyne & Wear |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/services-skills/education/educational-images/nos-1-2-warehouses-north-hudson-docks-sunderland-tyne-wear-3055 |website=Historic England |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:An Aerial view of Sunderland (9105585273).jpg|thumb|left|River Wear (top) in 1969, with Hudson Dock, Hendon Dock and associated rail links to the south.]]\nIn 1850-56 a half-tidal sea-entrance was constructed at the south-east corner of the dock, protected by a pair of breakwaters, to allow larger ships to enter the dock direct from the [[North Sea]]. At the same time (1853\u201355) Hudson Dock itself was extended southwards and deepened, and, alongside the entrance basin to the north, the first of a pair of public [[graving docks]] was built.<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\" /> In 1854 the Londonderry, Seaham & Sunderland Railway opened, linking the Londonderry and South Hetton collieries to a separate set of staiths at Hudson Dock South. It also provided a passenger service from Sunderland to Seaham Harbour.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colliery Railways: Londonderry Seaham & Sunderland 1854/55 |url=https://durhamrecordsonline.com/library/colliery-railways-londonderry-seaham-sunderland-185455/ |website=Durham Records Online |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1859 the docks were purchased by the River Wear Commissioners. Under Thomas Meik as engineer the docks were further extended with the construction of Hendon Dock to the south (1864\u201367). (Hendon Dock was entered via Hudson Dock South, but in 1870 it too was provided with a half-tidal sea-entrance providing direct access from the North Sea.) Under Meik's successor, Henry Hay Wake, Hudson Dock was further enlarged and the entrances were improved:<ref name=\"ETSthDocks\" /> in 1875 lock gates were installed (along with a [[swing bridge]]) at the river entrance, to allow entry at all states of the tide; they were powered by [[hydraulic machinery]], installed by [[Sir William Armstrong]] in the adjacent dock office building.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Swing-bridge, lock and walls of north end of Dock |num=1207097 |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> Similarly, a new [[sea lock]] was constructed at the south-east entrance in 1877\u201380.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Swing-bridge at east side with ashlar walls |num=1279892 |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The breakwater (known as the 'Northeast Pier') which protected the sea entrance to the docks was provided with a lighthouse ({{convert|29|ft|abbr=on}} high and of lattice construction, since demolished) which [[Chance Brothers]] equipped with a [[Fifth order Fresnel lens|fifth-order optic]] and clockwork [[Occulting Light|occulting mechanism]] in 1888;<ref name=\"Chance1919\">{{cite book |last1=Chance |first1=James Frederick |title=A History of the Firm of Chance Brothers & Co. |date=2018 |publisher=Society of Glass Manufacturers |location=Sheffield |page=182}}</ref> it displayed a [[sector light]]: white indicating the fairway and red indicating submerged hazards.<ref>{{cite book |title=British Islands Pilot, vol. VII |publisher=Government Printing Office |location=Washington DC |page=299}}</ref>\n\nBy 1889 two million tons of coal per year was passing through the dock.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tyne and Wear HER(2874): Sunderland, South Dock (Hudson Dock) - Details |url=https://twsitelines.info/SMR/2874 |website=SiteLines |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> The eastern wharves, opposite the coal staiths, were mainly occupied by saw mills and timber yards, with large open spaces given over to the storage of [[pit prop]]s for use in the mines;<ref>[[Commons:File:Insurance Plan of Sunderland; sheet 13-1 (BL 148858).tiff|Map, 1894]]</ref> while to the south of Hendon Dock, the Wear Fuel Works distilled [[coal tar]] to produce pitch, oil and other products.<ref>[[Commons:File:Insurance Plan of Sunderland; sheet 14-1 (BL 148860).tiff|Map detail, 1894]]</ref>\n\nAfter completion of the dock works, H. H. Wake embarked on the construction of [[Roker Pier]] (part of a scheme to protect the river approach by creating an outer harbour). Protection of a different kind was provided by the Wave Basin Battery, armed with four [[RML 80 pounder 5 ton gun]]s, constructed just inside the Old South Pier in 1874.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Wave Basin Battery adjacent to old South Pier |num=1207135 |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIncreasing industrialisation had prompted affluent residents to move away from the old port area, with several settling in the suburban terraces of the Fawcett Estate and [[Mowbray Park]]. The area around Fawcett Street itself increasingly functioned as the civic and commercial town centre. In 1848 George Hudson's [[York, Newcastle and Berwick Railway]] built a passenger terminus, [[Monkwearmouth Station Museum|Monkwearmouth Station]], just north of Wearmouth Bridge; and south of the river another passenger terminus, in Fawcett Street, in 1853. Later, [[Thomas Elliot Harrison]] (chief engineer to the [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]) made plans to carry the railway across the river; the [[Wearmouth Railway Bridge]] (reputedly 'the largest Hog-Back iron girder bridge in the world') opened in 1879.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> In 1886-90 a new Town Hall was built in Fawcett Street, just to the east of the railway station, designed by [[Brightwen Binyon]].<ref name=\"Pevsner1983\" />\n\n====\"The greatest shipbuilding port in the world\"====\n[[File:William Pile's Shipyard, North Sands, Sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|[[William Pile (shipbuilder)|William Pile]]'s Shipyard at North Sands, {{circa|1830}}; described as the greatest ship designer of his age, he built more than 100 ships in wood and almost as many in iron.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\">{{cite web |title=Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 2 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/6957/11-Shipbuilding-on-the-Wear-Part-2/pdf/Shipbuilding_on_the_Wear_Part_2.pdf |website=Sunderland Council |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>]]\nSunderland's shipbuilding industry continued to grow through most of the 19th century, becoming the town's dominant industry and a defining part of its identity.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> By 1815 it was 'the leading shipbuilding port for wooden trading vessels' with 600 ships constructed that year across 31 different yards.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\">{{cite web |title=Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 1 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/6958/10-Shipbuilding-on-the-Wear-Part-1/pdf/10_Shipbuilding_Part_1.pdf |website=Sunderland Council |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> By 1840 the town had 76 shipyards and between 1820 and 1850 the number of ships being built on the Wear increased fivefold. From 1846 to 1854 almost a third of the UK's ships were built in Sunderland, and in 1850 the ''Sunderland Herald'' proclaimed the town to be the greatest shipbuilding port in the world.<ref name=\"Clarke1997\">{{cite book |last1=Clarke |first1=Joseph Finbar |title=Building Ships on the North-East Coast |date=1997 |publisher=Bewick Press |page=93}}</ref>\n\nDuring the century the size of ships being built increased and technologies evolved: in 1852 the first iron ship was launched on Wearside, built by marine engineer [[George Clark & NEM|George Clark]] in partnership with shipbuilder John Barkes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunderland, Hudson Dock, George Clark Engine Works - Details |url=https://twsitelines.info/SMR/16317 |website=SiteLines |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref> Thirty years later Sunderland's ships were being built in steel<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> (the last wooden ship having been launched in 1880).<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" /> As the century progressed, the shipyards on the Wear decreased in number on the one hand, but increased in size on the other, so as to accommodate the increasing scale and complexity of ships being built.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" />\n\nShipyards founded in the 19th century, and still operational in the 20th, included:<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\" />\n* Sir James Laing & Sons (established by Philip Laing at Deptford in 1818, renamed Sir James Laing & sons in 1898)\n* [[Austin & Pickersgill|S. P. Austin]] (established in 1826 at Monkwearmouth, moving across the river to a site alongside Wearmouth Bridge in 1866)\n* [[Bartram & Sons]] (established at [[North Hylton|Hylton]] in 1837, moved to South Dock in 1871)\n* [[William Doxford & Sons]] (established at Cox Green in 1840, moved to [[Pallion]] in 1857)\n* [[Austin & Pickersgill|William Pickersgill]]'s (established at [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] in 1845)\n* [[J. L. Thompson & Sons]] (yard established at North Sands by Robert Thompson in 1846, taken over by his son Joseph in 1860, another son (also Robert) having established his own yard at Southwick in 1854)\n* [[John Crown & Sons]] (yard established at Monkwearmouth by Luke Crown (or Crone) by 1807, taken over by his grandson Jackie in 1854)\n* [[Short Brothers of Sunderland|Short Brothers]] (established by George Short in 1850, moved to Pallion in 1866)\n* [[John Priestman|Sir J Priestman]] (established at Southwick in 1882)\n\nAlongside the shipyards, marine engineering works were established from the 1820s onwards, initially providing engines for [[paddle steamers]]; in 1845 a ship named ''Experiment'' was the first of many to be converted to [[screw steamer|steam screw propulsion]].<ref name=\"JAMarr\" /> Demand for steam-powered vessels increased during the [[Crimean War]]; nonetheless, sailing ships continued to be built, including fast [[fully-rigged]] [[composite ship|composite]]-built [[Clipper|clippers]], including the [[City of Adelaide (1864)|''City of Adelaide'']] in 1864 and [[Torrens (clipper ship)|''Torrens'']] (the last such vessel ever built), in 1875.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS2\" />\n\n====Other industries====\n[[File:Commemorative plates Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens (8096466202).jpg|thumb|left|Commemorative plate, with pink '[[lustreware|splash lustre]]', depicting Wearmouth Bridge of 1796.]]\nBy the middle of the century glassmaking was at its height on Wearside. [[Hartley Wood and Co|James Hartley & Co.]], established in Sunderland in 1836, grew to be the largest glassworks in the country and (having patented an innovative production technique for [[rolled plate glass]]) produced much of the glass used in the construction of [[the Crystal Palace]] in 1851.<ref name=\"SundIndust\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland Industries |url=https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/sunderland-industries/ |website=England's North East |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> A third of all UK-manufactured plate glass was produced at Hartley's by this time.<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" /> Other manufacturers included the Cornhill Flint Glassworks (established at Southwick in 1865), which went on to specialise in [[pressed glass]], as did the Wear Flint Glassworks (which had originally been established in 1697).<ref name=\"BBCGlassmaking\" /> In addition to the plate glass and pressed glass manufacturers there were 16 bottle works on the Wear in the 1850s, with the capacity to produce between 60 and 70,000 bottles a day.<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\nLocal potteries also flourished in the mid-19th century, again making use of raw materials (white clay and stone) being brought into Sunderland as ballast on ships. Sunderland pottery was exported across Europe, with [[Sunderland Lustreware]] proving particularly popular in the home market; however the industry sharply declined later in the century due to foreign competition, and the largest remaining manufacturer (Southwick Pottery) closed in 1897.<ref name=\"SundIndust\" />\n\n====Victoria Hall Disaster====\n{{Main|Victoria Hall disaster}}\n[[File:Victoria Hall Memorial.png|upright|thumbnail|right|The memorial to the Victims of the Victoria Hall Disaster in Mowbray Park]]\nVictoria Hall was a large [[concert hall]] on Toward Road facing [[Mowbray Park]]. The hall was the scene of a [[Tragedy (event)|tragedy]] on 16 June 1883 when 183 children died.<ref name=\"vic\">{{cite web |title=Sunderland's Victoria Hall Stampede |url=http://www.north-country.co.uk/victoria.htm |work=North Country Web |access-date=27 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108182434/http://www.north-country.co.uk/victoria.htm |archive-date=8 January 2007  }}</ref> During a [[variety show]], children rushed towards a staircase for treats.<ref>{{cite web |title=Victims of the Victoria Hall Calamity |url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/DUR/Sunderland/VictoriaHall.html |work=Genuki |accessdate=27 January 2007}}</ref> At the bottom of the staircase, the door had been opened inward and bolted in such a way as to leave only a gap wide enough for one child to pass at a time.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Victoria Hall Disaster 1883 |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Victorian%20Hall%20Disaster.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711002529/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/libraries/Leaflets/Victorian%20Hall%20Disaster.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 July 2007 |work=City of Sunderland Library |access-date=27 January 2007|format=PDF }}</ref> The children surged down the stairs and those at the front were [[Human crush|trapped and crushed]] by the weight of the crowd behind them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/GIVE-THEM-A-FITTING-MEMORIAL.589296.jp|title=Give them a fitting memorial|newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]]|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Carol Roberton|year=2000}}</ref>\n\nThe [[asphyxiation]] of 183 children aged between three and 14 is the worst disaster of its kind in British history.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Victoria Hall Disaster of 1883 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A882173 |work=BBC h2g2 |accessdate=26 May 2007}}</ref> The memorial, a grieving mother holding a dead child, is located in Mowbray Park inside a protective canopy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Toy Tragedy Children Honoured|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1925815.stm|work=BBC News|date=12 May 2002 |accessdate=27 January 2007}}</ref> Newspaper reports triggered a mood of national outrage and an inquiry recommended that public venues be fitted with a minimum number of outward opening [[emergency exit]]s, which led to the invention of 'push bar' emergency doors. This law remains in force. Victoria Hall remained in use until 1941 when it was destroyed by a [[Nazi Germany|German]] bomb.<ref>{{cite book|first=Bryan |last=Talbot |authorlink=Bryan Talbot |title=Alice in Sunderland: An Entertainment |year=2007 |publisher=Jonathon Cape |location=London|isbn=0-224-08076-8|pages=58\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===20th and 21st centuries===\n[[File:Deptford, Sunderland 14.9.1917.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland in 1917]]\nThe public transport network was enhanced in 1900 - 1919 with an [[Sunderland Corporation Tramways|electric tram system]]. The trams were gradually replaced by buses during the 1940s before being completely axed in 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeastfilmarchive.com/videos/12751/going-places-story-sunderland-transport|title=Yorkshire Film Archive -|website=Northeastfilmarchive.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> In 1909 the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] was built, linking [[Deptford, Sunderland|Deptford]] and [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SINE Project: Structure details for Queen Alexandra Bridge |work=University of Newcastle upon Tyne |url=http://sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=1242 |access-date=12 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125023527/http://sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=1242 |archive-date=25 January 2009  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Women working in the shipyard (10817948524).jpg|thumb|right|King George V visiting women workers at Sir James Laing & Sons shipyard, 15 June 1917.]]\nThe First World War led to a notable increase in shipbuilding but also resulted in the town being targeted by a [[Zeppelin]] raid in 1916.  The Monkwearmouth area was struck on 1 April 1916 and 22 lives were lost.  Many citizens also served in the armed forces during this period, over 25,000 men from a population of 151,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson |first=Tony |url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/news/north-east-news/monkwearmouth-station-museum-sunderland-hosts-7184023 |title=Monkwearmouth Station Museum in Sunderland hosts First World War poster exhibition |publisher=The Journal |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the First World War, and on through the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Great Depression]] of the 1930s, shipbuilding dramatically declined: the number of shipyards on the Wear went from fifteen in 1921 to six in 1937.<ref name=\"ShipbuildingFS1\" /> The small yards of J. Blumer & Son (at North Dock) and the Sunderland Shipbuilding Co. Ltd. (at Hudson Dock) both closed in the 1920s, and other yards were closed down by [[National Shipbuilders Securities]] in the 1930s (including Osbourne, Graham & Co., way upriver at North Hylton, Robert Thompson & Sons at Southwick, and the 'overflow' yards operated by [[Swan, Hunter & Wigham Richardson]] and [[William Gray & Company|William Gray & Co.]]).<ref>[http://www.searlecanada.org/sunderland/sunderland037.html Map, with dates]</ref>\n\n[[File:Wearmouth Bridge to the Sea 2nd March 1967.jpg|thumbnail|left|Sunderland viewed from above in 1967]]\nWith the outbreak of [[World War II]] in 1939, Sunderland was a key target of the [[Germany|German]] [[Luftwaffe]], who claimed the lives of 267 people<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/ten-interesting-facts-about-sunderland-1342150|title=Ten interesting facts about Sunderland|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=1 January 2012|publisher=|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> in the town, caused damage or destruction to 4,000 homes, and devastated local industry. After the war, more housing was developed. The town's boundaries expanded in 1967 when neighbouring [[Ryhope]], [[Silksworth]], [[Herrington]], [[South Hylton]] and [[Castletown, Tyne and Wear|Castletown]] were incorporated into Sunderland.\n\nDuring the second half of the 20th century shipbuilding and coalmining declined; shipbuilding ended in 1988 and coalmining in 1993. At the worst of the unemployment crisis up to 20% of the local workforce were unemployed in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U4JWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NEENAAAAIBAJ&pg=1235,602714&dq=britain+million+unemployment&hl=en|title=The Leader-Post - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:NMUK.JPG|thumb|right|400px|Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK Ltd in Sunderland. Factory complex, including wind turbines, taken from Penshaw Monument]]\nAs the former heavy industries declined, new industries were developed (including electronic, chemical, paper and motor manufacture) and the service sector expanded during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/A-good-little-runner-.1616180.jp|title=A Good Little Runner|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Kevin Clark|year=2006|work=Sunderland Echo}}</ref> In 1986 Japanese car manufacturer [[Nissan]] opened its [[Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK]] factory in Washington, which has since gone on to become the UK's largest car factory.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/car-manufacturers/nissan/9753733/The-history-of-Nissans-Sunderland-factory.html |title=The history of Nissan's Sunderland factory |work=The Daily telegraph |location=London |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1990, the banks of the Wear were regenerated with the creation of housing, retail parks and business centres on former shipbuilding sites. Alongside the creation of the [[National Glass Centre]] the [[University of Sunderland]] has built a new campus on the [[St Peter's, Sunderland|St. Peter's site]]. The clearance of the [[Vaux Breweries]] site on the north west fringe of the city centre created a further opportunity for development in the city centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Centre-will-be-a-glass.817088.jp|title=Centre will be a glass act again|accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Laura White|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|title=Sir Tom gets own campus!|accessdate=3 April 2008|work=Sunderland Echo|year=2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201083138/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Sir-Tom-gets-own-campus.598289.jp|archive-date=1 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/HAVE-YOUR-SAY-ON-VAUX.589897.jp|title=Have your say on Vaux site|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2003}}</ref>\n\nSunderland received city status in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.localhistories.org/sunderland.html|title=A History of Sunderland|work=localhistories.org}}</ref> Like many cities, Sunderland comprises a number of areas with their own distinct histories, [[Fulwell, Sunderland|Fulwell]], Monkwearmouth, [[Roker]], and [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] on the northern side of the Wear, and Bishopwearmouth and Hendon to the south. On 24 March 2004, the city adopted St. Benedict Biscop as its [[patron saint]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Saint-that-nice--our.918420.jp|title=Saint that nice \u2013 our own patron|accessdate=3 April 2008 |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2005}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1937wembleylapofhonour.jpg|thumb|left|FA cup winners, Wembley 1937.]]\nThe 20th century saw [[Sunderland A.F.C.]] established as the Wearside area's greatest claim to sporting fame. Founded in 1879 as Sunderland and District Teachers A.F.C. by [[schoolmaster]] [[James Allan (footballer, born 1857)|James Allan]], Sunderland joined [[The Football League]] for the [[1890\u201391 in English football|1890\u201391 season]]. By 1936 the club had been league champions on five occasions. They won their first [[FA Cup]] in [[1937 FA Cup Final|1937]], but their only post-[[World War II]] major honour came in 1973 when they won a [[1973 FA Cup Final|second FA Cup]]. They have had a checkered history and dropped into the old third division for a season and been relegated thrice from the [[Premier League]], twice with the lowest points ever,<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/HonoursDetail/0,,10281~1690850,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704093811/http://www.safc.com/page/HonoursDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1690850%2C00.html|date=4 July 2011}}</ref> earning the club a reputation as a [[yo-yo club]]. After 99 years at the historic [[Roker Park]] stadium,<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0,,10281~1697691,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901082800/http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1697691%2C00.html|date=1 September 2010}}</ref> the club moved to the 42,000-seat [[Stadium of Light]] on the banks of the River Wear in 1997. At the time, it was the largest stadium built by an English football club since the 1920s, and has since been expanded to hold nearly 50,000 seated spectators.<ref>[http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0,,10281~1697689,00.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901082756/http://www.safc.com/page/PreviousGroundsDetail/0%2C%2C10281~1697689%2C00.html|date=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMany fine old buildings remain despite the bombing that occurred during World War II.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rare images recall wartime blitz |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/4434123.stm |accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=12 April 2005}}</ref> Religious buildings include Holy Trinity Church, built in 1719 for an independent Sunderland, St. Michael's Church, built as Bishopwearmouth Parish Church and now known as Sunderland Minster and St. Peter's Church, Monkwearmouth, part of which dates from AD 674, and was the original monastery. St. Andrew's Roker, known as the \"Cathedral of the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]]\", contains work by [[William Morris]], [[Ernest Gimson]] and [[Eric Gill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/Roker39s-39cathedral-of-arts-and.1392538.jp|title=Roker's 'cathedral of arts and crafts' |accessdate=3 April 2008 |author=Sarah Stoner |work=Sunderland Echo |year=2006}}</ref> [[St Mary's Church, Sunderland|St Mary's Catholic Church]] is the earliest surviving Gothic revival church in the city.<ref>[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-391394-church-of-st-mary-and-attached-railings-#.VmxkFxorKqA Church of St Mary and Attached Railings, Sunderland] from British listed buildings, retrieved 12 December 2015</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Borough of Sunderland COA.png|upright|thumb|The [[Sunderland coat of arms|coat of arms of the former County Borough of Sunderland]].]]\n[[File:Sunderlandciviccentre2.jpg|thumb|left|Sunderland Civic Centre (right background) with Mowbray Park to the left. This road was the route of the old [[A19 road|A19]] until the 1970s {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}.]]\nSunderland was created a [[municipal borough]] of [[County Durham]] in 1835. Under the [[Local Government Act 1888]], it was given the status of a County Borough, independent from [[county council]] control. In 1974, under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the county borough was abolished and its area combined with that of other districts to form the Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland in Tyne and Wear. In 1986, [[Tyne and Wear County Council]] was abolished, and Sunderland became a [[unitary authority]], once again independent from county council control. The metropolitan borough was granted [[city status in the United Kingdom|city status]] after winning a competition in 1992 to celebrate the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen's]] 40th year on the throne. The population of the city taken at the 2011 Census was 275,506.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1946157068|title=Sunderland Local Authority|fewer-links=y|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough it is a [[unitary authority]], many public services in the [[City of Sunderland]] are provided in cooperation with neighbouring local authorities. For instance, the [[Northumbria Police]] covers the five (now independent) boroughs of Tyne and Wear, plus the neighbouring county of [[Northumberland]]. The [[Tyne and Wear Fire and Rescue Service]] covers the five boroughs only.\n\nSince 2014, the [[City of Sunderland]] has been a member of the [[North East Combined Authority]], which is an alliance of the five former boroughs of [[Tyne and Wear]] and the neighbouring counties of [[Northumberland]] and [[County Durham]]. However, Sunderland is still a unitary authority; [[combined authority|combined authorities]] are voluntary alliances, in which local authorities agree to pool certain responsibilities and receive delegated functions from central government. For instance, the [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]], better known by its brand name Nexus, is now an executive body of the [[North East Combined Authority]].\n\n[[File:Durham - John Speed Map.jpg|thumb|alt=Historic map of County Durham.|Historic map of County Durham. Sunderland was part of [[County Durham]] until the local government changes in 1974. The [[River Wear]] is seen here passing through the city of [[Durham, England|Durham]], before reaching the North Sea in Sunderland.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Timeline\n! Years      !! Title                !! Parent or alliance\n|-\n| 674 - 866 || Monkwearmouth (or Wearmouth) || [[Kingdom of Northumbria]]<ref>Monkwearmouth was settled shortly after the unification of the kingdoms of [[Bernicia]] and [[Deira]] into [[Northumbria]] in AD 654.</ref><ref>In AD 866, [[Great Heathen Army|Vikings]] invaded southern Northumbria (formerly [[Deira]]), creating the kingdom of [[Jorvik]] (York). During this period, [[Jorvik]] made numerous incursions into [[Bernicia]] (the part of Northumbria north of the [[Tees]]), and largely subjugated the [[Angles|Anglian]] kingdom.</ref>\n|-\n| 883 - 930 || Monkwearmouth (or Wearmouth) || Liberty of [[Saint Cuthbert]]'s Land<ref>Saint Cuthbert's Land, between the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] and the [[Tees]], became a distinct political entity in AD 883. [[Wessex]] united with [[Northumbria]] and defeated [[Jorvik]] in AD 927, creating the [[Kingdom of England]].</ref>\n|-\n| 930 - 995 || Monkwearmouth and Bishopwearmouth || Liberty of [[Saint Cuthbert]]'s Land\n|-\n| 995 - 1179 || Monkwearmouth and Bishopwearmouth || [[Liberty of Durham]]<ref>[[Durham, England|Durham]] was founded in AD 995.</ref>\n|-\n| 1179 - 1293 || Sunderland || [[Liberty of Durham]]\n|-\n| 1293 - 1835 || Sunderland || [[County Palatine of Durham]]\n|-\n| 1835 - 1888 || Municipal Borough of Sunderland    || [[County Durham]]<ref>Durham ceased to be a [[county palatine]] in 1836.</ref>\n|-\n| 1888 - 1974 || County Borough of Sunderland       || [[County Durham]]\n|-\n| 1974 - 1992 || Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland || [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|-\n| 1992 - 2014 || City of Sunderland                 || [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|-\n| 2014\u2013present || City of Sunderland              || [[North East Combined Authority]] (an alliance)\n|}\n\nSunderland has the motto of ''Nil Desperandum Auspice Deo'' or ''Under God's guidance we may never despair''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/pages/Press/pritem.asp?Id=10190|title=STILL TIME TO SEE SUNDERLAND SHINE|access-date=3 April 2008|publisher=Sunderland Council|year=2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124205855/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/pages/Press/pritem.asp?Id=10190|archive-date=24 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{wide image|Sunderland panoramic riverside.jpg|900px|Sunderland riverside at sunset}}\n{{See also|List of places in Sunderland}}\n[[File:Wearmouth Bridge, Sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|The Wearmouth Bridge (right) and railway bridge (left). This road was the route of the old A19, now it is the A1018.]]\nMuch of the city is located on a low range of hills running parallel to the coast. On average, it is around 80 metres [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. Sunderland is divided by the River Wear which passes through the middle of the city in a deeply incised valley, part of which is known as the Hylton gorge. The three road bridges connecting the north and south portions of the city are the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] at Pallion, the [[Wearmouth Bridge]] just to the north of the city centre and most recently the [[Northern Spire Bridge]] between Castletown and Pallion. To the west of the city, the [[Hylton Viaduct]] carries the [[A19 road|A19]] dual-carriageway over the Wear (see map below).\n\nMost of the suburbs of Sunderland are situated towards the west of the city centre with 70% of its population living on the south side of the river and 30% on the north side. The city extends to the seafront at Hendon and Ryhope in the south and [[Seaburn]] in the north.\n\n===Suburbs===\nSome, mainly local authority-built, Sunderland suburbs have most streets beginning with the same letter:\n* '''A''': [[Farringdon, Sunderland|Farringdon]]\n* '''B''': [[Town End Farm]] and [[Barnes, Sunderland|Barnes]]\n* '''C''': [[Hylton Castle (suburb)|Hylton Castle]]\n* '''D''': Dykelands Road area of [[Seaburn]]\n* '''E''': [[Carley Hill]]\n* '''F''': [[Ford Estate]]\n* '''G''': [[Grindon, Sunderland|Grindon]]\n* '''H''': [[Hylton Lane]] / [[Havelock, Tyne and Wear|Havelock]] / Humbledon\n* '''J''': [[John Street, Sunderland]]\n* '''K''': [[Downhill, Sunderland|Downhill]]\n* '''M''': [[Moorside, Sunderland|Moorside]] and [[Millfield, Tyne and Wear]]\n* '''P''': [[Pennywell]] and [[Plains Farm]] and [[Pallion]]\n* '''R''': [[Redhouse, Sunderland|Red House]]\n* '''S''': [[Springwell, Sunderland|Springwell]], [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]]\n* '''T''': [[Thorney Close]]\n* '''W''': [[Witherwack]]\n\nIn Marley Pots, the streets are all associated with trees, e.g. Maplewood, Elmwood etc.\nIn Millfield, the streets are all associated with plants, e.g. Chester, Fern, Rose, Hyacinth etc.\n\n===Definitions of Sunderland===\nThere are two definitions for Sunderland. The smaller Urban Subdivision follows the boundaries of what is considered the city itself, however, the USD alone has not been given city status. The larger metropolitan borough contains other settlements with a separate identity such as [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], but has been given official city status, with all individual settlements being the responsibility of Sunderland city council.\n\n===Green belt===\n{{main|North East Green Belt}}\nThe town is bounded by the Tyne & Wear Green Belt,<ref name=\"sunderland-belt\">{{cite web|title=GREEN BELT REVIEW STAGE 1 \u2013 CORE STRATEGY GROWTH OPTIONS STAGE, MARCH 2016 |url=https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/18571/SD43-Sunderland-Green-Belt-Review-Stage-1-Core-Strategy-Growth-Options-Stge-March-2016-/pdf/SD43_Sunderland_Green_Belt_Review_Stage_1_-_Core_Strategy_Growth_Options_Stage_March_2016.pdf|website=www.sunderland.gov.uk}}</ref> with its portion in much of its surrounding rural area of the borough. It is a part of the local [[development plan]], of which its stated aims<ref name=\"sunderland-belt\"/> are as follows:\n\n''A Green Belt will be maintained which will:-''\n\n''(i) Check the unrestricted sprawl of the built up area of Sunderland;''<br/>\n''(ii) Assist in safeguarding the city\u2019s countryside from further encroachment;''<br/>\n''(iii) Assist in the regeneration of the urban area of the city;''<br/>\n''(iv) Preserve the setting and special character of Springwell Village;''<br/>\n''(iv) Prevent the merging of Sunderland with Tyneside, Washington, Houghton-le-Spring and Seaham, and the merging of Shiney Row with Washington, Chester-le-Street and Bournmoor.''\n\nIn the Sunderland borough boundary, as well as the aforementioned areas, landscape features and facilities such as much of the River Don and Wear basins, the George Washington Hotel Golf and Spa complex, Sharpley Golf Course, Herrington Country Park, Houghton Quarry and Penshaw Hill are within the green belt area.\n\n==Climate==\nSunderland has a temperate [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfb'').  Its location in the [[rain shadow]] of the [[Pennines]], as well as other mountain ranges to the west, such as those of the [[Lake District]] and southwestern Scotland, make Sunderland one of the least rainy cities of Northern England. The climate is heavily moderated by the adjacent [[North Sea]], giving it cool summers, and winters that are mild considering its latitude. The closest weather station is in [[Tynemouth]], about {{convert|8|mi|km}} north of Sunderland. As a result, Sunderland's coastline is likely slightly milder given the more southerly position. Another relatively nearby weather station in [[Durham, England#Climate|Durham]] has warmer summer days and colder winter nights courtesy of its inland position.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Tynemouth, 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n| Jan high C = 7.2\n| Feb high C = 7.3\n| Mar high C = 9.0\n| Apr high C = 10.3\n| May high C = 12.7\n| Jun high C = 15.6\n| Jul high C = 18.1\n| Aug high C = 18.1\n| Sep high C = 16.1\n| Oct high C = 13.2\n| Nov high C = 9.7\n| Dec high C = 7.4\n|year high C = 12.1\n| Jan low C = 2.2\n| Feb low C = 2.2\n| Mar low C = 3.3\n| Apr low C = 4.8\n| May low C = 7.2\n| Jun low C = 10.0\n| Jul low C = 12.3\n| Aug low C = 12.3\n| Sep low C = 10.4\n| Oct low C = 7.7\n| Nov low C = 4.9\n| Dec low C = 2.5\n|year low C = 6.7\n| Jan precipitation mm = 45.5\n| Feb precipitation mm = 37.8\n| Mar precipitation mm = 43.9\n| Apr precipitation mm = 45.4\n| May precipitation mm = 43.2\n| Jun precipitation mm = 51.9\n| Jul precipitation mm = 47.6\n| Aug precipitation mm = 59.6\n| Sep precipitation mm = 53.0\n| Oct precipitation mm = 53.6\n| Nov precipitation mm = 62.8\n| Dec precipitation mm = 52.9\n|year precipitation mm = 597.2\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan precipitation days = 9.8\n| Feb precipitation days = 7.6\n| Mar precipitation days = 8.7\n| Apr precipitation days = 8.2\n| May precipitation days = 8.3\n| Jun precipitation days = 8.7\n| Jul precipitation days = 8.6\n| Aug precipitation days = 9.2\n| Sep precipitation days = 8.1\n| Oct precipitation days = 10.7\n| Nov precipitation days = 11.6\n| Dec precipitation days = 10.1\n|year precipitation days = 109.5\n| Jan sun = 61.1\n| Feb sun = 81.6\n| Mar sun = 117.7\n| Apr sun = 149.9\n| May sun = 191.7\n| Jun sun = 183.0\n| Jul sun = 185.7\n| Aug sun = 174.9\n| Sep sun = 141.1\n| Oct sun = 106.2\n| Nov sun = 70.4\n| Dec sun = 51.9\n|year sun = 1515.0\n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/gcz02e3x2| title = Sunderland climate information | accessdate =23 December 2017|publisher = [[Met Office]]}}</ref>\n|date=August 2015\n}}\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"toc\" border=\"1\" style=\"float:right; border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:10pt;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''Population of Sunderland urban area<br /> by ward'''<ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Census \u2013 Fact Cards for wards in the City of Sunderland|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/wardmap.asp|work=Sunderland city Council|accessdate=26 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201455/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/wardmap.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n||'''Ward'''||align=right|'''Population'''\n|-\n||Castle||align=right|11,292\n|-\n||Fulwell||align=right|12,906\n|-\n||Redhill||align=right|11,867\n|-\n||St Peter's||align=right|11,760\n|-\n||Southwick||align=right|11,634\n|-\n||'''Northside total:'''||align=right|'''59,459'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;\n|-\n||Barnes||align=right|12,030\n|-\n||Doxford||align=right|11,318\n|-\n||Hendon||align=right|11,551\n|-\n||Millfield||align=right|10,277\n|-\n||Pallion||align=right|10,385\n|-\n||Ryhope||align=right|11,217\n|-\n||St Anne's||align=right|11,409\n|-\n||St Chad's||align=right|10,922\n|-\n||St Michael's||align=right|11,626\n|-\n||Sandhill||align=right|11,319\n|-\n||Silksworth||align=right|11,245\n|-\n||'''Southside total:'''||align=right|'''123,299'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;\n|-\n||'''City total:'''||align=right|'''182,758'''\n|}\n\nAt 3,874 [[hectares]], Sunderland is the 45th largest {{citation needed|date=March 2015}} urban area in England by measure of area, with a population density of 45.88 people per hectare.\n\nAccording to statistics<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunderland 2001 Census Statistics|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/dfc-sunderland.pdf|accessdate=18 January 2007|format=PDF |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711002534/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/theCity/Key-Statistics-Environment/Census/dfc-sunderland.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 11 July 2007}}</ref> based on the 2001 census, 60% of homes in the Sunderland [[metropolitan area]] are [[Owner Occupied|owner occupied]], with an average household size of 2.4 people. Three percent of the homes have no permanent residents.\n\nThe most ethnically diverse ward of the city was the (now defunct)<ref>The Thornholme ward no longer existed in the [[United Kingdom Census 2011]]</ref> Thornholme area which had a population of 10,214 in 2001. This ward, which included Eden Vale, Thornhill, as well as parts of Hendon, Ashbrooke and the city centre, has long been the focus of Wearside's Bangladeshi community. In Thornholme, 89.4% are white (86.3% White British), 7.8% are Asian and 1.3% are mixed-race.<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941170&c=thornholme&d=14&e=15&g=370084&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462122135203&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47 |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Nowadays the [[Barnes, Sunderland|Barnes ward]], which contains part of former Thornholme ward, has the highest percentage (5.4%) of Bangladeshi residents in the city, with people of this ethnicity being the ward's only significant ethnic minority. The 2001 census also recorded a substantial concentration of Greek nationals, living mainly in Central and Thornholme wards. The least ethnically diverse wards are in the north of the city. The area of [[Castletown, Sunderland|Castletown]] is made up of 99.3% white, 0.4% Asian and 0.2% mixed-race.\n\nThe Sunderland USD had a population of 174,286 in 2011 compared with 275,506 for the wider city. Both of these figures are a decrease compared with 2001 figures that showed the Sunderland USD had a population of 182,758 compared with 280,807 for the wider city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/asv2htm.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930205650/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/asv2htm.aspx |archive-date=30 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Millfield, Tyne and Wear|Millfield ward]], which contains the western half of the city centre, was the most ethnically diverse ward in Sunderland. Millfield is a multiracial area with large Indian and Bangladeshi communities, being the centre of Wearside's Bangladeshi community along with neighbouring Barnes. The ward's ethnicity was, in 2011, 76.4% White (73.5% White British), 17.6% Asian and 2.5% Black.<ref>{{cite web|title = Millfield - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/millfield-e05001161#sthash.k4D5ViU8.uuCzDyBH.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref> Other wards with high ethnic minority populations include [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]], Barnes, St Michael's and St Peter's. In 2011, the least ethnically diverse ward was the Northside suburb Redhill which was 99.0% White (98.3% White British), 0.3% Asian and 0.1% Black.<ref>{{cite web|author=Good Stuff IT Services |url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/redhill-e05001163#sthash.Dnm2WCse.dpbs |title=Redhill - UK Census Data 2011 |publisher=Ukcensusdata.com |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> This ward has so few ethnic minorities that it can even be compared to rural wards in Cumbria and it also proves there is a lot of contrast between areas when it comes to ethnicity.\n\nHere is a table comparing Sunderland and the wider City of Sunderland Metropolitan Borough as well as [[North East England]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!2011 Census Ethnic Groups\n!White British\n!Asian\n!Black\n|-\n|Sunderland (Urban Subdivision)\n|93.4%\n|3.6%\n|0.6%\n|-\n|[[Metropolitan Borough of Sunderland]]\n|94.8%\n|2.6%\n|0.5%\n|-\n|[[North East England]]\n|93.6%\n|2.8%\n|0.5%\n|-\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title = Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.uKxpOFke.ELqplSD3.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119884905|title=Custom report - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/north-east-e12000001#sthash.ykCPT4B2.dpbs|title=North East - UK Census Data 2011|first=Good Stuff IT|last=Services|website=UK Census Data}}</ref>\n\nThe Sunderland Urban Subdivision is made up of all the wards listed on the table on the right hand side. In the Sunderland Urban Subdivision, 6.6% of the population were from an ethnic minority group (non white British) compared with 5.2% in the surrounding borough. Sunderland is less ethnically diverse than [[Gateshead]] and [[South Shields]], mainly because of many outlying suburbs to the south, north and west of the city such as St Chad's, [[Southwick, Sunderland|Southwick]] and [[Fulwell, Sunderland|Fulwell]] which have very high White British populations. The [[Sunderland Central]] Parliament constituency largely omits these areas. However, in 2001, the Sunderland USD was 96.6% White British, so the ethnic minority population is increasing.\n\n===Religion===\nThe area is part of the [[Church of England|Anglican]] [[Diocese of Durham]]. It has been in the [[Roman Catholic]] [[Diocese of Hexham and Newcastle]]<ref name=rcdhn2017>{{cite web | url = http://www.rcdhn.org.uk/churches07/churchtowns.php | title = RCDHN | website = rcdhn.org.uk| publisher = rcdhn.org.uk | access-date = 29 January 2017 | quote = }}</ref> since the [[Catholic Church hierarchy|Catholic hierarchy]] was restored in 1850. The 2011 census recorded that 70.2% of the population identified as Christian, 1.32% as Muslim, 0.29% as Sikh, 0.22% as Hindu, 0.19% as Buddhist, 0.02% as Jewish, and 21.90% as having no religion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.8BxUZ8zv.dpbs|title=Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|last=Services|first=Good Stuff IT|website=UK Census Data|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nJewish heritage in the city, once part of a thriving community, can be dated back to around 1750, when a number of Jewish merchants from across the UK and Europe settled in Sunderland,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seligman.org.il/sunderland_jews.html|title=Sunderland Jews|website=www.seligman.org.il|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> eventually forming a congregation in 1768. A [[rabbi]] from [[Holland]] was established in the city in 1790. After a rapid growth in numbers during the latter half of the nineteenth century, the Jewish community in Sunderland reached its height in the mid 1930s, when around 2,000 Jews were recorded to be living in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seligman.org.il/sunderland_jews.html|title=Sunderland Jews|last=Seligman|first=Jon|website=www.seligman.org.il|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref> The community has been in slow decline since the mid-20th century. Many Sunderland Jews left for stronger Jewish communities in Britain or to Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.999sunderland.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912072202/http://www.999sunderland.com/ |archive-date=12 September 2007  }}</ref> The Jewish primary school, the Menorah School, closed in July 1983. The [[synagogue]] on Ryhope Road, opened in 1928, closed at the end of March 2006.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/wear/hi/people_and_places/religion_and_ethics/newsid_8197000/8197862.stm|title=BBC - Wear - Jewish community gradually fades|date=12 August 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> (See also [[Jews and Judaism in North East England]]) The Jewish population of the Sunderland Metropolitan Borough is continually diminishing, as the Jewish population fell from 114 people in 2001, to 76 people in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title = Sunderland - UK Census Data 2011|url = http://www.ukcensusdata.com/sunderland-e08000024#sthash.uKxpOFke.IyxsRnyA.dpbs|website = UK Census Data|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, following the grant of City status to Sunderland, the erstwhile [[parish church]] of Bishopwearmouth (St Michael's) was redesignated as [[Sunderland Minster]] with a city-wide role. It was believed to have been the first creation of a [[Minster (church)|minster church]] in England since the [[Reformation in England|Reformation]].<ref name=\"JohnsonPotts2013\" />\n\n====Alexander Boddy and the Early Development of Pentecostalism in Britain====\nThe Reverend [[Alexander Boddy]] (who lived 1854-1930) was appointed vicar of All Saints Church (Church of England) in the [[Monkwearmouth]] area of Sunderland in 1884.  During his ministry at Monkwearmouth, Boddy was influenced by the [[1904-1905 Welsh revival]] and also by the British-born Norwegian preacher [[Thomas Ball Barratt]] (T.B. Barratt). In the early years of the 20th century All Saints, Monkwearmouth became an important centre for the development of the Pentecostal Movement in Britain.\n\n==Economy==\n{{Further|List of companies in the City of Sunderland}}\n\n===Regeneration===\nSince the mid-1980s Sunderland has undergone massive regeneration {{citation needed|date=July 2015}}, particularly around the central business district and the river corridor, following the industrial decline of the 1970s and early 1980s.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Sunderland's economic situation began to improve following the collapse of the local shipbuilding industry. Japanese car manufacturer [[Nissan]] opened the [[Nissan Motor Manufacturing UK]] factory in 1986, and the first [[Nissan Bluebird]] car was produced later that year.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> The factory and its supplier companies remain the largest employers in the region, with current cars produced there including the [[Nissan Qashqai]], the [[Nissan Juke]] and the electric [[Nissan Leaf|Nissan LEAF]]. As of 2012 over 500,000 cars are produced annually, and it is the UK's largest car factory.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAlso in the late 1980s, new [[Service industry|service industries]] moved into sites such as the [[Doxford International Business Park]] in the south west of the city, attracting national and international companies. Sunderland was named in the shortlist of the top seven \"intelligent cities\" in the world for the use of [[information technology]], in 2004 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Pages/press/pritem.asp?Id=1021 |title=TOP OF THE WORLD |publisher=Sunderland City Council |date=20 January 2005 |accessdate=9 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070312062944/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Pages/press/pritem.asp?Id=1021 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 12 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe former shipyards along the Wear were transformed with a mixture of residential, commercial and leisure facilities including St. Peter's Campus of the University of Sunderland, University accommodation along the Fish Quay on the South side of the river, the North Haven housing and marina development, the [[National Glass Centre]], the [[Stadium of Light]] and Hylton Riverside Retail Park. Also in 2007, the Echo 24 luxury apartments opened on Pann's Bank overlooking the river. In 2008 the [[Sunderland Aquatic Centre]] opened adjacent to the Stadium of Light, containing the only [[Olympic-size swimming pool]] between [[Leeds]] and [[Edinburgh]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\nIn 2000, [[the Bridges]] [[shopping mall|shopping centre]] was extended towards Crowtree Road and the former Central [[Bus station|Bus Station]], attracting national [[chain store]]s. This was followed by adjacent redevelopments on Park Lane.\n\nSunderland Corporation's massive post-war housing estate developments at [[Farringdon, Sunderland|Farringdon]], [[Pennywell]] and [[Grindon, Sunderland|Grindon]] have all passed into the ownership of [[Gentoo Group|Gentoo]] (previously 'Sunderland Housing Group'), a private company and a [[Registered Social Landlord]].\n\n[[Sunderland A.F.C.]] has been a major symbol of the area and a contributor to the local economy since the late [[19th century]]. The club was one of the most successful and best supported clubs in the English game during this era, with its home at [[Roker Park]] holding more than 70,000 spectators at its peak. However, the [[FA Cup]] triumph of 1973 would prove to be the club's only postwar major trophy to date, and after its relegation in 1958 the club frequently bounced between the top two divisions of English football, and in 1987 and again in 2018 suffered relegation to the third tier of English football. The club played at Roker Park for 99 years until the completion of the new [[Stadium of Light]] at [[Monkwearmouth]] on the banks of the [[River Wear]] in 1997. The new stadium seated more than 42,000 on its completion, and has since been expanded to hold some 49,000 spectators. Sunderland's relatively high attendances have been a major boost to the local economy - averaging at more than 30,000 even during the club's current spell in the third tier of English football.\n\nIn 2004, redevelopment work began in the Sunniside area in the east-end of the city centre, including a [[multiplex cinema]], a [[multi-storey car park]], restaurants, a [[casino]] and [[tenpin bowling]]. Originally the River Quarter, the site was renamed Limelight in 2005, and renamed in 2008, when it became Sunniside Leisure. Sunniside Gardens were landscaped, and a number of new cafes, bars and restaurants were opened. Up-market residential apartments were developed, including the Echo 24 building.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/sunniside/ |title=Sunniside |publisher=[[Sunderland arc]]|date=6 January 2009 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226232909/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/sunniside/ |archive-date=26 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSunderland City Council's Unitary Development Plan (UDP) outlines ambitious regeneration plans for a number of sites around the city.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/public/editable/themes/environment/planningandenvironment/planningpolicy/udp/udp/udphome-page.asp |title=Sunderland Unitary Development Plan |date=6 January 2009 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330043523/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/Public/Editable/Themes/Environment/PlanningandEnvironment/PlanningPolicy/UDP/UDP/udphome-page.asp |archive-date=30 March 2009  }}</ref>\nThe plans are supported by [[Sunderland Arc]], an urban regeneration company funded by the City council, [[One NorthEast]] and the [[Homes and Communities Agency]].\n\n;Vaux and Farringdon Row\nSince the closure of the [[Vaux Breweries|Vaux brewery]] in 1999, a {{convert|26|acre|ha|adj=on|abbr=off}} [[brownfield land|brownfield site]] has lain dormant in the centre of Sunderland. The land is subject to dispute between supermarket chain [[Tesco]], who bought the site in 2001, and Sunderland arc, who submitted plans for its redevelopment in 2002.<ref name=\"Vaux Site FAQ\">{{cite news |url=http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/faqs.aspx |title=Vaux Site FAQ |date=4 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226201305/http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/faqs.aspx |archive-date=26 February 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During formal negotiations, Tesco stated they would be willing to sell the land to arc, if an alternative city centre site could be found. Possibilities include Holmeside Triangle, and the Sunderland Retail Park in Roker. Arc hope to begin development in 2010.<ref name=\"Vaux Site FAQ\"/>\nArc's plans for the site were approved by the Secretary of State in 2007, and include extensive office space, [[hotel]]s, leisure and retail units, residential apartments and a new \u00a350&nbsp;m [[Crown and Magistrates court]]. The central public arcade will be located under an expansive glass canopy. It is hoped an \"[[evening economy]]\" can be encouraged which will complement the city's nightlife.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/this-is-the-opportunity.aspx |title=Vaux Site Opportunity |date=4 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226201316/http://www.vauxsite.co.uk/this-is-the-opportunity.aspx |archive-date=26 February 2009  }}</ref> In 2013 in the area opposite the Vaux site, Sunderland City Council announced the [[Keel Square]] project, a new public space designed to commemorate Sunderand's maritime heritage, which was completed in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/business/images-of-sunderland-s-new-11-8million-square-1-6149182|title=Images of Sunderland\u2019s new \u00a311.8million square|date=16 October 2013|accessdate=9 August 2014 |publisher=Sunderland Echo}}</ref> Construction commenced in 2014.\n;Stadium Village\nRedevelopment of the Monkwearmouth Colliery site, which sits on the north bank of the river Wear opposite the Vaux site, began in the mid-1990s with the creation of the [[Stadium of Light]]. In 2008, it was joined by the [[Sunderland Aquatic Centre]].\nThe Sheepfolds industrial estate occupies a large area of land between the Stadium and the [[Wearmouth Bridge]].\n[[Sunderland Arc]] were in the process of purchasing land in the Sheepfolds, with a view to relocate the businesses and redevelop the site. The emphasis of development plans included further sporting facilities, in order to create a ''Sports Village''. Other plans included a hotel, residential accommodation, and a [[footbridge]] linking the site with the Vaux development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/stadiumVillage/sheepfolds/index.aspx |title=Stadium Park Development |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025004930/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/stadiumVillage/sheepfolds/index.aspx |archive-date=25 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n;Grove and Transport Corridor\nThe Sunderland Strategic Transport Corridor (SSTC) is a proposed transport link from the A19, through the city centre, to the port. A major phase of the plan was the creation of a new bridge, the [[Northern Spire Bridge]], which links the [[A1231 road|A1231]] Wessington Way on the north of the river with the Grove site in Pallion, on the south of the river.\nIn 2008, Sunderland City Council offered the residents of Sunderland the opportunity to vote on the design of the bridge. The choices were a {{Convert|180|m|ft|-1|adj=on}} iconic [[cable-stayed bridge]], which would result in a temporary increase in [[council tax]], or a simple [[road bridge|box structure]] which would be within the council's budget.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/newbridge/ |title=New Bridge |date=10 March 2008 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118050641/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/newbridge/ |archive-date=18 November 2009  }}</ref>\nThe results of the consultation were inconclusive, with residents keen to have an iconic bridge, but reluctant to have a subsequent increase in tax to fund it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/Next-step-in-road-to.4747133.jp |title=Next step in road to iconic Wear bridge|date=1 December 2008 |accessdate=10 March 2009}}</ref>\nRegardless of the ultimate design of the new bridge, the landing point will be the former Grove Cranes site in [[Pallion]]. Plans for this site focus around the creation of a new residential area, with homes, community buildings, commercial and retail space.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/groves/ |title=Gorve Site |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226232800/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/groves/ |archive-date=26 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n;The Port\nThe Port of Sunderland, owned by the city council, has been earmarked for medium-term redevelopment with a focus on mixed-use industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/portofsunderland/ |title=Port of Sunderland |date=1 January 2006 |access-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227122242/http://www.sunderlandarc.co.uk/portofsunderland/ |archive-date=27 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Ship building and coal mining===\n[[File:Shipbuilding during the First World War Q20119.jpg|thumbnail|left|A group of boys who worked on the construction of a Standard ship at a yard in Sunderland during the First World War.]]\n[[File:Radiant II is launched into the River Wear (14508024713).jpg|thumb|right|A ship (''Radiant II'') launched into the River Wear by [[Austin & Pickersgill]], 29 March 1961.]]\nOnce hailed as the \"Largest Shipbuilding Town in the World\",<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Shipbuilding in the North East|work=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/ship-building/background.shtml|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> ships were built on the Wear from at least 1346<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2008/01/16/shipbuilding_has_been_20_years_feature.shtml|title=History of shipbuilding on Wearside|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> onwards and by the mid-18th century Sunderland was one of the chief shipbuilding towns in the country. [[Sunderland Docks]] was the home of operations for the [[shipbuilding]] industry on [[Wearside]]. The Port of Sunderland was significantly expanded in the 1850s with the construction of Hudson Dock to designs by River Wear Commissioner's Engineer John Murray, with consultancy by [[Robert Stephenson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SINE Project: Structure details for South Dock: Hudson Dock|work=University of Newcastle upon Tyne|url=http://www.sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=505|access-date=22 November 2006|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060616184050/http://www.sine.ncl.ac.uk/view_structure_information.asp?struct_id=505|archive-date=16 June 2006}}</ref> One famous vessel was the [[Torrens (clipper ship)|''Torrens'']], the clipper in which [[Joseph Conrad]] sailed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/opinion/the-clipper-ship-torrens-1-1147795|title=The clipper ship Torrens|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> and on which he began his first novel. She was one of the most famous ships of her time and can claim to be the finest ship ever launched from a Sunderland yard. {{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:An Aerial view of Sunderland (9105585273).jpg|left|thumb|221x221px|[[Sunderland Docks]] in 1969.]]\nBetween 1939 and 1945 the Wear yards launched 245 merchant ships totalling 1.5 million tons, a quarter of the merchant tonnage produced in the UK at this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/ship-building/background.shtml|title=BBC - Nation on Film - Shipbuilding - Background|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> Competition from overseas caused a downturn in demand for Sunderland built ships toward the end of the 20th century. The last shipyard in Sunderland closed on 7 December 1988.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sunderland Public Library Service|title=LOCAL STUDIES CENTRE FACT SHEET NUMBER 10:Shipbuilding on the Wear: Part 1|url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=6958&p=0|access-date=27 August 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902021657/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=6958&p=0|archive-date=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nSunderland, part of the Durham coalfield, has a coal-mining heritage that dates back centuries. At its peak in 1923, 170,000 miners were employed in County Durham alone,<ref>{{cite web|title=Rise and Fall of Coal Mining|work=North East England History|url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/CoalMiningandRailways.htm|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> as labourers from all over Britain, including many from [[Scotland]] and [[Ireland]], entered the region. As demand for coal slipped following [[World War II]], mines began to close across the region, causing mass unemployment. The last [[coal mine]] closed in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/lifestyle/retro/exhibition-digs-into-sunderland-s-mining-history-1-7374451|title=Exhibition digs into Sunderland\u2019s mining history|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911013557/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/lifestyle/retro/exhibition-digs-into-sunderland-s-mining-history-1-7374451|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The site of the last coal mine, [[Wearmouth Colliery]], is now occupied by the [[Stadium of Light]], and a miner's [[Davy lamp]] monument stands outside of the ground to honour the site's mining heritage. Documentation relating to the region's coalmining heritage are stored at the [[North East England Mining Archive and Resource Centre]] (NEEMARC).\n\n===Other industry===\n[[File:Sunderland Liebherr Riverside.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Liebherr]] crane factory is the last remaining heavy industry on the River Wear in Sunderland.]]\n\nAs with the coal-mining and shipbuilding, overseas competition has forced the closure of all of Sunderland's glass-making factories. [[Corning Glass Works]], in Sunderland for 120 years, closed on 31 March 2007<ref>{{cite web\n|title=End of an era as glass firm sets closure date\n|work=[[The Northern Echo]]\n|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/business/news/display.var.1124976.0.end_of_era_as_glass_firm_sets_closure_date.php\n|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> and in January 2007, the [[Pyrex]] manufacturing site also closed,<ref>{{cite news|title=Energy costs close glass factory|work=[[BBC News]]|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/6271617.stm|date=17 January 2007|accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> bringing to an end commercial glass-making in the city. However, there has been a modest rejuvenation with the opening of the [[National Glass Centre]] which, amongst other things, provides international glass makers with working facilities and a shop to showcase their work, predominantly in the artistic rather than functional field.\n\n[[Vaux Breweries]] was established in the town centre in the 1880s and for 110 years was a major employer. Following a series of consolidations in the British [[Brewing industry]], however, the brewery was finally closed in July 1999.<ref>{{cite web|last=Journal |first=The |url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/culture/restaurants-bars/painful-anniversary-vaux-brewery-sunderland-4480444 |title=Painful Anniversary for Vaux Brewery, Sunderland - journallive Administrator |publisher=The Journal |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>  Vaux in Sunderland and [[Wards Brewing Company|Wards]] in [[Sheffield]] had been part of the Vaux Group, but with the closure of both breweries it was re-branded The Swallow Group, concentrating on the hotel side of the business. This was subject to a successful take-over by [[Whitbread|Whitbread PLC]] in the autumn of 2000. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}} It is now a brownfield site and this is a derelict site in an urban area.\n\nIn 1855, [[John Candlish]] opened a bottleworks, producing glass bottles, with 6 sites at nearby [[Seaham]] and at Diamond Hall, Sunderland.\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Sunderland}}\n[[File:St peters campus.jpg|thumb|St Peter's Riverside Campus at Monkwearmouth]]\n\nSunderland Polytechnic was founded in 1969, becoming the [[University of Sunderland]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=University history |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university|work=Sunderland University |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> The institution currently has over 17,000 students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Facts, Figures, Accolades, the University's vision |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts |work=Sunderland University |date=2 January 2008 |access-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318005834/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/ |archive-date=18 March 2008 }}</ref> The university is split into two campuses; the City Campus (site of the original Polytechnic) is just to the west of the city centre, as is the main university library and the main administrative buildings. The 'Award-Winning' St Peter's Riverside Campus is located on the north banks of the river Wear, next to the National Glass Centre and houses the School of Business, Law and Psychology, as well as Computing and Technology and The Media Centre.<ref>{{cite news |title=The University |url=\nhttp://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/campuses/|work=Sunderland University, Our Campuses |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Sunderland was named the top university in England for providing the best student experience by ''[[The Times Higher Education Supplement]]'' (THES) in 2006. Since 2001 Sunderland has been named the best new university in England by ''[[The Guardian]]'' and Government performance indicators showed Sunderland as the best new university in England for the quality, range and quantity of its research.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awards and Accolades 2007/8 |url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/accolades |work=Sunderland University website |date=2 January 2008 |access-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080427134351/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/university/facts/accolades/ |archive-date=27 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sunderland College]] is a [[further education]] establishment with five campuses located at the Bede centre on [[A690|Durham Road]], [[Shiney Row]], Hylton, Doxford International Business Park and 'Phoenix House' in the city centre. It has over 14,000 students, and based on exam results is one of the most successful colleges.<ref>{{cite web |title=City of Sunderland College |url=http://www.citysun.ac.uk/opencms/opencms/website/home/pressoffice/factsandstatistics/index.html |accessdate=18 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061207074028/http://www.citysun.ac.uk/opencms/opencms/website/home/pressoffice/factsandstatistics/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 7 December 2006}}</ref> St Peter's Sixth Form College, next to St Peter's Church and the University, opened in September 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Work begins on \u00a36&nbsp;m campus college |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/7168780.stm |work=BBC News |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 January 2008}}</ref> The college is a partnership between the three Sunderland North schools and City of Sunderland College.<ref>{{cite web |title=St Peter's Sixth Form College |url=http://www.stpeterssixthformcollege.ac.uk/ |access-date=3 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080127163823/http://www.stpeterssixthformcollege.ac.uk/ |archive-date=27 January 2008  }}</ref>\n\nThere are eighteen [[secondary school]]s in the Sunderland area, predominantly comprehensives. According to exam results, the most successful was [[St Robert of Newminster Catholic School]], a coeducational secondary school and sixth form in Washington.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/education/school_tables/secondary/12/html/eng_maths_394.stm?compare=|title=Secondary school league tables in Sunderland|last=|first=|date=23 April 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> However, comprehensive schools also thrive, notably the Roman Catholic single-sex schools [[St Anthony's Girls' Catholic Academy|St. Anthony's]] (for girls) and [[St Aidan's Catholic School|St. Aidan's]] (for boys). Both continue to attain high exam results. There are seventy-six [[primary school]]s in Sunderland. According to the 'Value Added' measure, the most successful is Mill Hill Primary School, in [[Doxford Park]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Primary Schools in Sunderland League Table |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/06/school_tables/primary_schools/html/va_394.stm |accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nSunderland voted for [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on European Union membership]] by 61% of the vote; an unexpectedly high margin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/how-world-reacted-sunderland-voted-17654528|title=How the world reacted when Sunderland voted to leave the European Union|last=Lindsay|first=Kali|date=2020-01-31|website=nechronicle|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Freytas-Tamura|first=Kimiko de|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/28/world/europe/european-union-brexit-sunderland-britain-cameron.html|title=Pro-\u2018Brexit\u2019 City of Sunderland Glad to Poke Establishment in the Eye|date=2016-06-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New Statesman]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/07/how-sunderland-became-poster-child-brexit|title=How Sunderland became a poster child for Brexit|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> and [[The Daily Telegraph]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wallace|first=Tim|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/12/06/special-report-sunderland-aiming-poster-city-brexit/|title=Special report: Sunderland aiming to be the \u2018poster city for Brexit\u2019|date=2019-12-06|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> have described Sunderland as the [[Poster child|poster city]] for Brexit.\n\nFor decades, Sunderland has been an electoral stronghold of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nSunderland is currently represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] by three Labour Members of Parliament; [[Bridget Phillipson]], [[Julie Elliott]] and [[Sharon Hodgson]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n![[Houghton and Sunderland South (UK Parliament constituency)|Houghton and Sunderland South]]\n![[Sunderland Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sunderland Central]]\n![[Washington and Sunderland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Washington and Sunderland West]]\n|-\n|[[Bridget Phillipson]]\n|[[Julie Elliott]]\n|[[Sharon Hodgson]]\n|-\n|[[File:Official portrait of Bridget Phillipson MP crop 2.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Julieface.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Official portrait of Mrs Sharon Hodgson MP crop 2.jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|}\n\n==Transport==\n{{Main|Transport in Tyne and Wear}}\n\n===Metro===\n[[File:Sunderland_Metro_Map.png|thumb|780px|Sunderland-oriented Metro map. Dashed lines indicate omitted stations.]]\n[[File:Pallion station 02.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pallion Metro station]] on the Tyne and Wear Metro is a small suburban station in Sunderland.]]\nIn May 2002 the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] was extended to Sunderland in an official ceremony attended by The Queen, twenty-two years after it originally opened in Newcastle upon Tyne. The Green line now stretches deeper into [[South Tyneside]] and into Sunderland, incorporating [[Seaburn]], [[Millfield]], [[Pallion]], as well as [[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland's mainline railway station]] and stations at the [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane Transport Interchange]] and both campuses of the [[University of Sunderland]] before terminating at [[South Hylton]]. The trains run every 12\u201315 minutes (depending on time of day) and call at all stations. All-zones Metro tickets cost \u00a35.20 for a daily and \u00a322.40 for a weekly, as of October 2019.<ref>https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro-day-ticket</ref><ref>https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro-season-ticket</ref>\n\nIn March 2014 Metro owner Nexus proposed an extension of the network by the creation of an \"on-street\" tram link which would connect the city centre to [[South Shields]] to the north and Doxford Park to the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/business/new-south-tyneside-metro-and-tram-link-up-plans-revealed-1-6525102 |title=New South Tyneside Metro and tram link-up plans revealed |publisher=Shields Gazette |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\nSunderland is served by [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]], which is a 55-minute Metro ride from Sunderland city centre; there is a Metro train connecting with the airport every 12\u201315 minutes in both directions until about 11pm, Monday-Sunday.\n\n===Rail===\n===National Rail===\n[[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland station]] has 5 direct trains to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] on weekdays (5 on Saturday / 4 on Sunday), taking about 3 hours 30 minutes. [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] is a 30-minute [[Tyne & Wear Metro]] ride (see above) from Sunderland city centre, and has connecting services to London every half hour that take approximately 2 hours 45 minutes and also regular services to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]], [[Glasgow Central railway station|Glasgow]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]], [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]], [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]], [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham]] and beyond.\n\n[[File:Sunderland station Metro platforms.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland railway and Metro station]].]]\n[[File:GRAND CENTRAL 2 Launch Day.JPG|thumbnail|right|[[Grand Central (train operating company)|Grand Central]] operate five daily services from [[Sunderland railway station|Sunderland]] to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross']]]]\nSunderland station opened in 1879<ref name=\"disused-stations.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/s/sunderland_central/ |title=Sunderland Central Station |publisher=Disused Stations |date= |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> but was completely redesigned to facilitate football teams and officials from countries who were drawn to play at [[Roker Park]] during England's hosting of the [[1966 World Cup]]. It is situated on an underground level.<ref name=\"disused-stations.org.uk\"/> It was renovated in 2005, backed by the artistic team which designed the stations along the Wearside extension of the [[Tyne & Wear Metro]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title= New look arriving|work=Sunderland Echo|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/New-look-will-be-arriving.1010574.jp|date=27 April 2005|accessdate=3 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= New rail service launch delayed|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6168002.stm|date=21 November 2006|accessdate=22 November 2006}}</ref> It is situated on the [[Durham Coast Line]] served by direct [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] services to Newcastle, [[Hartlepool railway station|Hartlepool]], [[Stockton railway station (County Durham)|Stockton]] and [[Middlesbrough railway station|Middlesbrough]], as well as further afield to [[Hexham railway station|Hexham]], [[Carlisle railway station|Carlisle]] and the Gateshead [[MetroCentre railway station|MetroCentre]]. These services run hourly in each direction, cut from half-hourly on 12 December 2005 (but towards Newcastle there is also the option of taking the Metro - see the Metro subsection above).\n\nFrom 1998 to 2004, Northern Spirit and subsequently [[Arriva Trains Northern]] ran bihourly direct trains from Sunderland to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] via [[Durham railway station|Durham]], [[Darlington railway station|Darlington]], [[York railway station|York]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] and [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester]]. The services were withdrawn due to a change of franchise which saw the [[First TransPennine Express]] route gain a franchise in its own right, distinct from the Regional Railways network which Arriva had inherited. Services now terminate at Newcastle, and a separate service also travels to Middlesbrough, but both only stretch as far as [[Manchester Airport railway station|Manchester Airport]].\n\nIn 2006, [[Grand Central (train operating company)|Grand Central]] announced plans to operate a direct service between Sunderland and [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] via [[York railway station|York]], a service which had been stripped from Wearside twenty years earlier. A scaled-down service of one train each day began in December 2007, twelve months after the initial launch date, due to delays caused by restoring rolling stock and a protracted court case against [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] (which Grand Central won). The service increased to three departures daily each way on 1 March 2008, connecting a line which can run from Edinburgh to London. The service has proved so popular that daily fourth and fifth direct trains are now in operation.\n\nWhen [[Virgin Trains East Coast]] were announced as the winners of the [[InterCity East Coast]] franchise in November 2014 their plans included a daily service from Sunderland to London Kings Cross that commenced in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stagecoach.com/media/news-releases/2014/2014-11-27.aspx |title=Stagecoach-Virgin company awarded InterCity East Coast rail franchise - Stagecoach Group |publisher=Stagecoach.com |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Main roads in sunderland.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of the main roads through Sunderland.]]\nThe fastest, largest and busiest road is the [[A19 road|A19]], which is a [[dual carriageway]] running north-to-south along the western edge of the urban area, crossing the River Wear at Hylton, and providing access north to the [[Tyne Tunnel]], joining up with the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] to Edinburgh, and south through [[Teesside]], joining up with the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1M]] via the [[A168 road|A168]] at [[Thirsk]], providing an entirely [[grade separated]] connection between Sunderland and the [[M1 motorway]]. The A19 originally ran through Sunderland city centre until the bypass was built in the 1970s; this route is now the A1018.\n\nThere are four main roads which support the city centre. The [[A690 road|A690]] ''Durham Road'' terminates in the city centre, and runs to [[Crook, County Durham]] via the city of Durham.\n\nThe [[A1231 road|A1231]] (Sunderland Highway) begins in the city centre, crosses the [[Queen Alexandra Bridge]] and runs west through [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]] to the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]]. Most of this road is [[national speed limit]] [[dual carriageway]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nThe [[A1018 road|A1018]] and [[A183 road (England)|A183]] roads both start in the centre of South Shields and enter Sunderland from the north, before merging to cross the Wearmouth Bridge. The A1018 follows a direct route from Shields to Sunderland, the A183 follows the coast. After crossing the bridge, the A1018 follows a relatively straight path to the south of Sunderland where it merges with the A19. The A183 becomes ''Chester Road'' and heads west out of the city to the A1 at [[Chester-le-Street]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn Autumn 2007 the ''Southern Radial Route'' was opened. This is a bypass of the A1018 through Grangetown and Ryhope \u2013 a stretch that commonly suffered from [[traffic congestion|congestion]], especially during [[rush hour]]. The bypass starts just south of Ryhope, and runs parallel to the cliff tops into Hendon, largely avoiding residential areas.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nSunderland strategic transport corridor project, is an ongoing investment to the city's road infrastructure. The scheme will improve transport links around the city ensuring continuous dual carriageway between the A19 road and the port of Sunderland. The scheme also includes the building of a new wear bridge between Pallion on the south embankment and Castletown to the north.\n\n===Bus===\n[[File:Buses in Park Lane Interchange - geograph.org.uk - 1748466.jpg|thumbnail|right|[[Go North East]] buses in [[Park Lane Interchange]]]]\nA multimillion-pound [[transport interchange]] at [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]] was opened on 2 May 1999 by the then ''[[Brookside]]'' actor [[Michael Starke (actor)|Michael Starke]]. With 750,000 passengers per year it is the busiest bus and coach station in Britain after [[Victoria Coach Station]] in [[Central London]], and has won several awards for innovative design.<ref name=\"didyouknow\">{{cite news|title=Did you know? Sunderland facts|work=Sunderland Echo News|url=http://www.wear1.co.uk/didyouknow.html|date=21 November 2006|accessdate=22 November 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070802181549/http://www.wear1.co.uk/didyouknow.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 August 2007}}</ref> The majority of bus services in Sunderland are provided by [[Stagecoach North East|Stagecoach in Sunderland]] and [[Go North East]], with a handful of services provided by [[Arriva North East]]. Besides these, there are also inter state and inter city route buses mainly operated by [[National Express Coaches|National Express]] and [[Megabus (Europe)|Megabus]] . A new Metro station was built underneath the bus concourse to provide a direct interchange as part of the extension to South Hylton in 2002.\n\n===Cycle===\nThere are a number of cycle routes that run through and around Sunderland. The [[National Cycle Network]] National Route 1 runs from Ryhope in the south, through the centre of the city, and then along the coast towards South Shields.\nBritain's most popular long-distance [[Segregated cycle facilities|cycle route]] \u2013 The 'C2C' [[Sea to Sea Cycle Route]] \u2013 traditionally starts (or ends) when the cyclist dips their wheel in the sea on Roker beach. The '[[W2W]]' 'Wear-to-[[Walney]]' route, and the 'Two-Rivers' (Tyne and Wear) route also terminate in Sunderland.\n\n===The Port===\n[[File:Sunderland harbour.jpg|thumb|Sunderland harbour viewed from the north dock]]\nThe Port of Sunderland is the second largest municipally owned port in the U.K.<ref name=\"pos1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk | title=Port of Sunderland | publisher=Port of Sunderland | accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The port offers a total of 17 quays<ref name=\"pos-quays\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/port_map.php | title=Port of Sunderland - Port Map | publisher=Port of Sunderland | access-date=6 July 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814055615/http://portofsunderland.org.uk/port_map.php | archive-date=14 August 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> handling cargoes including forest products, non-ferrous metals, steel, aggregates and refined oil products, limestone, chemicals and maritime cranes.<ref name=\"pos1\"/> It also handles offshore supply vessels and has ship repair and [[drydock]]ing facilities.\n\nThe river berths are deepwater and [[tide|tidal]], while the South Docks are entered via a lock with an 18.9 m beam restriction.<ref name=\"pos-southdock\">{{cite web | url=http://www.portofsunderland.org.uk/south_docks.php | title=Port of Sunderland - South Docks | publisher=Port of Sunderland | access-date=6 July 2014 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814055945/http://portofsunderland.org.uk/south_docks.php | archive-date=14 August 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Dialect and accent===\n{{Main|Mackem}}\nThe dialect of Sunderland is known as [[Mackem]], and contains a large amount of vocabulary and distinctive words and pronunciations not used in other parts of the United Kingdom. The Mackem dialect has much of its origins in the language spoken by the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] population. Although the accent has so much in common with the more popular [[Geordie]], the dialect spoken in Sunderland is quite distinctive from the dialect spoken in Newcastle.\n\nA few Sunderland dialect words:\n*Nee - No\n*Bosh - Problem\n*Marra - Mate\n*Ha'way - Come on ( Not to be confused with Geordie's Howay)\n*Knack - Hurt\n*Git - Very (Used to emphasize something so 'very good' becomes 'git good')\n*Claes - Clothes\n\n===Attractions===\nNotable attractions for visitors to Sunderland include the 14th century [[Hylton Castle]] and the beaches of Roker and Seaburn.\nThe [[National Glass Centre]] opened in 1998, reflecting Sunderland's distinguished history of glass-making. Despite sustained support from the [[Arts Council]] the centre has struggled to meet visitor targets since it opened.<ref>{{cite news |title=Another new head for Glass Centre |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3861253.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=2 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n[[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]], on Borough Road, was the first municipally funded museum in the country outside London.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It houses a comprehensive collection of the locally produced [[Sunderland Lustreware]] pottery. The City Library Arts Centre, on Fawcett Street, housed the Northern Gallery for Contemporary Art until the library was closed in January 2017.  The library service was relocated to the Museum and Winter Gardens and the Gallery for Contemporary Art transferred to Sunderland University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/our-region/sunderland/closure-date-set-for-sunderland-s-city-library-1-8190155|title=Closure date set for Sunderland\u2019s City Library|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe city possesses a number of public parks. Several of these are historic, including [[Mowbray Park]], [[Roker Park (park)|Roker Park]] and [[Barnes Park]]. In the early 2000s, [[Herrington Country Park]] was opened opposite [[Penshaw Monument]]. The city's parks have secured several awards for its commitment to preserving natural facilities, receiving the [[Britain in Bloom]] collective in 1993, 1997 and 2000.\n\n===Events===\n[[File:Red Arrows Sunderland Airshow 2009 (2).jpg|thumb|right|The Red Arrows display team perform at the 2009 Sunderland International Airshow]]\nEach year on the last weekend in July, the city hosts the [[Sunderland International Airshow]]. It takes place primarily along the sea front at Roker and Seaburn.\n\nSunderland also hosts the free International Festival of Kites, Music and Dance, which attracts kite-makers from around the world to Northumbria Playing Fields, Washington.\n\nEvery year the city hosts a large [[Remembrance Day]] memorial service, the largest in the UK outside [[London]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=North honours fallen war heroes |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6141372.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=17 January 2007 | date=12 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nSunderland's inaugural film festival took place in December 2003 at the ''Bonded Warehouse'' on Sunderland riverside, in spite of the lack of any cinema facilities in the city at that time, featuring the films of local and aspiring directors as well as reshowings of acclaimed works, such as [[Alan Bleasdale]]'s [[The Monocled Mutineer]], accompanied by analysis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/features/featurepages/0,,1099724,00.html|title=The show must go on  | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Simon | last=Hattenstone | date=5 December 2003 | accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref> By the time of the second festival commencing on 21 January 2005, a new cinema multiplex had opened in Sunderland to provide a venue which allowed the festival to showcase over twenty films.\n\nSunderland celebrates an annual Restaurant week, where city centre restaurants provide some of the best plates at low costs.<ref>https://sunderlandvibe.com/sunderland-restaurant-week-2020-what-to-expect/</ref>\n\n===Literature and art===\n[[File:Sunderlandstreets2.jpg|thumb|Sunniside district in the city centre.]]\n[[Lewis Carroll]] was a frequent visitor to the area. He wrote most of ''[[Jabberwocky]]'' at [[Whitburn, South Tyneside|Whitburn]] as well as \"[[The Walrus and the Carpenter]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Walrus and the Carpenter |url=http://www.northeastengland.talktalk.net/Sunderland%20and%20East%20Durham.htm|work=Sunderland and East Durham History |accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref> Some parts of the area are also widely believed to be the inspiration for his Alice in Wonderland stories, such as Hylton Castle and Backhouse Park.<ref>''Alice in Sunderland'', Bryan Talbot, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-59307-673-3}}</ref> There is a statue to Carroll in Whitburn library. Lewis Carroll was also a visitor to the Rectory of Holy Trinity Church, Southwick; then a township independent of Sunderland. Carroll's connection with Sunderland, and the area's history, is documented in [[Bryan Talbot]]'s 2007 graphic novel ''[[Alice in Sunderland]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ross |last=Robertson |title=News focus: Alice in Pictureland |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2181289&SectionID=1512 |work=Sunderland Echo |date=27 March 2007 |accessdate=29 March 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070402012743/http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2181289&SectionID=1512 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 April 2007}}</ref> More recently, Sunderland-born [[Terry Deary]], writer of the series of ''[[Horrible Histories]]'' books, has achieved fame and success, and many others such as thriller writer [[Sheila Quigley]], are following his lead.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grandmother has write stuff|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/3004139.stm |work=BBC News |date=6 May 2003 |accessdate=28 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Salford-born painter [[L. S. Lowry]] was a frequent visitor, staying in the Seaburn Hotel in Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters of Art |url=http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/mk4custompages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31751|work=Sunderland Echo |accessdate=18 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231083815/http://www.sunderlandtoday.co.uk/mk4custompages/CustomPage.aspx?PageID=31751 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 31 December 2006}}</ref> Many of his paintings of seascapes and shipbuilding are based on Wearside scenes. The [[Northern Gallery for Contemporary Art]] on Fawcett Street and [[Sunderland Museum and Winter Gardens]] showcase exhibitions and installations from up-and-coming and established artists alike, with the latter holding an extensive collection of Lowry. The National Glass Centre on Liberty Way also exhibits a number of glass sculptures.\n\n===Media, film and television===\nSunderland has two local newspapers: the daily evening tabloid ''The [[Sunderland Echo]]'', founded in 1873, and the ''Sunderland Star'' \u2013 a [[Free daily newspaper|free newspaper]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Newspaper Report for the publication: Sunderland Star |work=The Newspaper Society |url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1012 |access-date=6 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714180613/http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1012 |archive-date=14 July 2007  }}</ref>\n\nIt also has its own commercial station, [[Sun FM]], formerly an independent station but now owned by [[Nation Broadcasting]] who acquired the station from the [[UKRD Group]], a student-led community radio station, [[Spark Sunderland|Spark]], and a hospital radio station \u2013 [[Radio Sunderland for Hospitals]], and can receive other north-eastern independent radio stations [[Metro Radio]], [[Greatest Hits North East]], [[Capital North East]] and [[Smooth Radio North East]].\nThe current regional BBC radio station is [[BBC Radio Newcastle]]. The regional DAB multiplex for the Sunderland area is operated by Bauer DIGITAL RADIO LTD. \u2013 owned by Bauer Digital Radio plc.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The city is covered by [[BBC North East and Cumbria]] and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Tyne Tees Television|Tyne Tees]] franchise, which has a regional office in the University's Media Centre.<ref>{{cite web |title=Julia Barthram |work=ITV Tyne Tees |url=http://www.tynetees.tv/Julia_Barthram.htm |access-date=6 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308122635/http://www.tynetees.tv/Julia_Barthram.htm |archive-date=8 March 2007  }}</ref>\n\nSunderland's first film company was established in 2008; and is known as \"Tanner Films Ltd\" and is based in the [[Sunniside, Sunderland|Sunniside]] area of the city. The companies first film, \"King of the North\" starring [[Angus MacFadyen]] and set in the [[Hetton-le-Hole]] area of the city; is currently under production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/6million-film-deal-for-North.5295605.jp|title=$6million film deal for North East murder film|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Bands and musicians from Yorkshire and North East England}}\nSunderland musicians that have gone on to reach international fame include [[David A. Stewart|Dave Stewart]] of the [[Eurythmics]] and all four members of [[Kenickie]], whose vocalist [[Lauren Laverne]] later became known as a TV presenter. In recent years, the [[underground music]] scene in Sunderland has helped promote the likes of [[Frankie & the Heartstrings]], [[The Futureheads]], [[The Golden Virgins]] and [[Field Music]].\n\nOther Mackem musicians include punk rockers [[The Toy Dolls]] (\"Nellie the Elephant\", December 1984), oi! punk band [[Red Alert (band)|Red Alert]], punk band [[Leatherface]], the lead singer of dance outfit [[Olive (band)|Olive]], [[Ruth Ann Boyle]] (\"You're Not Alone\", May 1997) and [[A Tribe of Toffs]] (\"[[John Kettley is a Weatherman]]\", December 1988).\n\nIn May 2005, Sunderland played host to [[BBC Radio 1]]'s [[Big Weekend]] concert at [[Herrington|Herrington Country Park]], attended by 30,000 visitors and which featured [[Foo Fighters]], [[Kasabian]], [[KT Tunstall]], [[Chemical Brothers]] and [[The Black Eyed Peas]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Radio 1's Big Weekend: Penshaw Monument, Herrington Park, Sunderland |work=BBC Radio 1 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend05 |accessdate=26 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Local boys shine at Sunderland's Big Weekend |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wear/content/articles/2005/05/10/stage_two_sunday_review_feature.shtml |accessdate=26 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Sunderland [[Stadium of Light]], home to [[Sunderland AFC]], is recognised internationally as a major stadium concert venue. Headlining acts have included [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], [[Take That]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Coldplay]], [[Bruce Springsteen|Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[Rihanna]], [[One Direction]], [[Foo Fighters]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce]]. The Empire Theatre sometimes plays host to music acts. Independent, a city-centre [[nightclub]]/music venue, satisfies underground music lovers.\n\nThe Manor Quay' the students' union nightclub on St. Peter's Riverside at the [[University of Sunderland]], has also hosted the [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Max\u00efmo Park]], [[911 (UK band)|911]], [[the Levellers (band)|the Levellers]] and [[Girls Aloud]]. In 2009, the club was taken into private ownership under the name Campus and hosted [[N-Dubz]], [[Ocean Colour Scene]], [[Little Boots]], [[Gary Numan]] and [[Showaddywaddy]] but has since been returned to the university.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The former students' union Wearmouth Hall hosted [[Voice of the Beehive]], [[Manic Street Preachers]], The Primitives and Radiohead before closing in 1992.\n\nSince 2009, Sunderland: Live in the City has played host to a series of free and ticketed live music events throughout venues in the city centre. Sunderland also hosts the yearly Split Music Festival at Ashbrooke Cricket Club which was first celebrated in October 2009 {{citation needed|date=January 2014}} and will return in 2010 with Max\u00efmo Park and The Futureheads headlining.{{Update inline|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 2013 local band Frankie and The Heartstrings opened a temporary pop up record store in the city, Pop Recs Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24437766 |title=Frankie and the Heartstrings: Record shop boys|publisher=BBC News |date=9 October 2013 |first=Ian |last=Youngs |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Initially only intended to remain open for a fortnight, the store remains open and has hosted live performances from acts including [[The Cribs]], [[The Vaccines]] and [[The Charlatans (English band)|The Charlatans]].\n\n===Theatre===\n[[File:Sunderland Empire.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Sunderland Empire]]\nThe [[Sunderland Empire Theatre]] opened in 1907 on [[High Street West]] in the city centre. It is the largest theatre in between [[Edinburgh]] and [[London]]{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}, and completed a comprehensive refurbishment in 2004. Operated by international entertainment group [[Live Nation]], the Empire is the only theatre between [[Glasgow]] and [[Leeds]] with sufficient capacity to accommodate large [[West End theatre|West End]] productions.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Sunderland Empire Theatre |work=Sunderland City Council |url=http://www.visitsunderland.com/culture/empire.html |access-date=18 January 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061222233211/http://www.visitsunderland.com/culture/empire.html |archive-date=22 December 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It is infamous for playing host to the final performance of British comic actor [[Sid James]] who died of a heart attack whilst on stage in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/retro1980s/1989-Ghostly-tale.4331124.jp|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120918044323/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/retro1980s/1989-Ghostly-tale.4331124.jp|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 September 2012|title=1989: Ghostly tale|website=Sunderlandecho.com|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Royalty Theatre on [[A183 road (England)|Chester Road]] is the home to the amateur Royalty Theatre Group who also put on a number of low-budget productions throughout the year. Film producer [[David Parfitt]] belonged to this company before achieving worldwide fame and is now a patron of the theatre.<ref>[http://gostridge.net/page.php?pageid=14] {{dead link|date=August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sunniside, Sunderland|Sunniside]] area plays host to a number of smaller theatrical workshops and production houses, as well as the ''Theatre Restaurant'', which combines a dining experience with a rolling programme of musical theatre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/local/all-news/restaurant-puts-entertainment-on-menu-1-1136283 |title=Restaurant puts entertainment on menu |newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]] |date=17 August 2007 |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Twin towns and sister cities===\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the United Kingdom}}\nSunderland is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[Harbin]], China<ref name=\"Harbin-Sunderland link\">{{cite web|url=http://en.ichtf.com/news_2008.php?id=47248|title=Harbin is linking up with Sunderland|access-date=8 August 2013|work=Harbin News Web|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301222614/http://en.ichtf.com/news_2008.php?id=47248|archive-date=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sunderland Echo\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/China-opens-a-window-on.5276489.jp |title=China opens a window on Sunderland&nbsp;\u2013 Local |publisher=Sunderland Echo |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=16 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521180257/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/China-opens-a-window-on.5276489.jp |archive-date=21 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[Saint-Nazaire]], France<ref name=\"Archant twinning 3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705094933/http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|title=British towns twinned with French towns ''[via WaybackMachine.com]''|accessdate=20 July 2013|archivedate=5 July 2013|work=Archant Community Media Ltd}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington, D.C.]], United States<ref name=DCsite>{{cite web|url=http://os.dc.gov/service/dc-sister-cities|title=DC Sister Cities - os|website=os.dc.gov|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Essen]], Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2804 |title=Sunderland City Council: Further Information on Essen |publisher=Sunderland.gov.uk |date= |access-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422095518/http://www.sunderland.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2804 |archive-date=22 April 2016  }}</ref>\n\nSunderland is the only city that is not a capital of country twinned with Washington, D.C., as it includes the town of [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], the ancestral home of George Washington's family.<ref name=DCsite/>\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Stadium of light from distance.jpg|thumb|right|View of the Stadium of Light from the opposite side of the River Wear.]]\nThe only professional sporting team in Sunderland is the [[Association football|football]] team, [[Sunderland A.F.C.]], which was formed in 1879 and was elected to the [[Football League]] in 1890.<ref>Sunderland : the Complete Record / Rob Mason. Breedon Books, 2005. pp 16-17</ref> The club, which currently plays in [[EFL League One]] following consecutive relegations from the [[FA Premier League]] and the [[EFL Championship]], is based at the 49,000 seat capacity [[Stadium of Light]], which was opened in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAFC Previous Grounds / History / Previous Grounds |url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=3911|work=SAFC website |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> Sunderland A.F.C also has the north-east's top women's football team, [[Sunderland A.F.C. Women]], They currently play in the 3rd tier of English women's football \u2013 [[FA Women's National League North]]. Despite their financial struggles. Sunderland were league champions six times within the [[The Football League|Football League's]] first half century, but have not achieved this accolade since 1936. Their other notable successes include [[FA Cup]] glory in 1937 and 1973 and winning the [[Football League First Division|Division One]] title with a (then) [[Football in England|English league]] record of 105 points in 1999.\n\nSunderland AFC's longest stadium occupancy so far was of [[Roker Park]] for 99 years beginning in 1898, with relocation taking place due to the stadium's confined location and the need to build an all-seater stadium. The initial relocation plan, announced in the early 1990s, had been for a stadium to be situated alongside the Nissan factory, but these were abandoned in favour of the Stadium of Light at [[Monkwearmouth]] on the site of a [[colliery]] on the banks of the River Wear that had closed at the end of 1993.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sunderland Cricket Club|url=http://www.safc.com/history/?page_id=3911|work=SAFC website |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> The city also has two non-league sides, [[Sunderland Ryhope Community Association F.C.]] of the [[Northern League Division Two]] and Sunderland West End FC of the [[Wearside League]], who play at the Ford Quarry Complex.\n\nSunderland's amateur [[Rugby football|Rugby]] and [[Cricket]] clubs are both based in [[Ashbrooke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SAFC Previous Grounds|url=http://vega.sund.ac.uk/ashbrooke/cricket.cfm|work=vega.sund.ac.uk website|date=2 January 2008|access-date=3 April 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20060507000445/http://vega.sund.ac.uk/ashbrooke/cricket.cfm|archive-date=7 May 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A Very Warm Welcome to Sunderland RFC. The Home of Sunderland Rugby Union|url=http://www.sunderlandrufc.com|work=sunderlandrufc.com website|date=2 January 2008|access-date=3 April 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310072625/http://www.sunderlandrufc.com/|archive-date=10 March 2008}}</ref> The Ashbrooke ground was opened on 30 May 1887.\n\nThe Crowtree Leisure Centre has also played host to a number of important boxing matches and snooker championships including the 2003 Snooker World Trickshot and Premier League Final. In September 2005, [[BBC]] TV cameras captured international boxing bouts featuring local boxers [[David Dolan]], Stuart Kennedy and [[Tony Jeffries]]. The latter became Sunderland's first Olympic medallist when he won a [[bronze medal]] in the light heavyweight boxing category for [[Great Britain and Northern Ireland]] at the [[2008 Beijing Olympic Games]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\n[[File:Sunderland Aquatic Centre - geograph.org.uk - 1665091.jpg|thumb|right|Sunderland Aquatic Centre, located next to the Stadium of Light, holds the only Olympic-sized swimming pool in North-East England]]\nOn 18 April 2008, the Sunderland Aquatic Centre was opened. Constructed at a cost of \u00a320 million, it is the only Olympic sized 50&nbsp;m pool between [[Leeds]] and [[Edinburgh]] and has six diving boards, which stand at 1&nbsp;m, 3&nbsp;m and 5&nbsp;m.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/daily/Olympic-splashout-spectacular.3991372.jp|title=Sunderland Echo Olympic splash-out spectacular|work=Sunderland Echo}}</ref>\n\nAthletics is also a popular sport in the city, with Sunderland Harriers Athletics Club based at Silksworth Sports Complex. 800&nbsp;m runner Gavin Massingham represented the club at the AAA Championships in 2005. On 25 June 2006, the first Great Women's Run took place along Sunderland's coastline. Among the field which lined up to start the race were Olympic silver medallists [[Sonia O'Sullivan]] of the [[Republic of Ireland]] and [[Gete Wami]] of [[Ethiopia]], who eventually won the race. The race quickly became an annual fixture in the city's sporting schedule, with races in 2007 and 2008. In 2009, the race will be relaunched as the [[Great North 10K]] Run, allowing male competitors to take part for the first time, on 12 July.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great North 10K moves|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/wear/hi/front_page/newsid_9393000/9393838.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{Main|List of people from Sunderland}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North East England}}\n* [[Boxing Day Dip|Sunderland's Boxing Day dip]]\n* [[The North Dock Tufa]]\n* [[List of important dates in the history of Sunderland]]\n* [[The New Monkey]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Category:Sunderland|Sunderland}}\n*{{Commons category-inline|Sunderland}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Sunderland}}\n{{Navboxes |list1=\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre = Sunderland\n| North = [[South Tyneside]]\n| Northeast = [[North Sea]]\n| East = [[North Sea]]\n| Southeast = [[North Sea]]\n| South = [[Seaham]], [[Easington, County Durham|Easington]]\n| Southwest = [[Durham, England|Durham]], [[Chester-le-street]].\n| West = [[Gateshead]], [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]]\n| Northwest = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n}}\n{{City of Sunderland}}\n{{Tyne and wear}}\n{{Coastal settlements\n|place = Tyne and Wear\n|settlement = Wearmouth, Sunderland\n|anticlockwise = [[Roker]]\n|clockwise = [[Hendon, Sunderland|Hendon]]\n}}\n{{T&W places}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n}}\n\n[[Category:Sunderland| ]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in North East England]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Towns in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:City of Sunderland]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTee (disambiguation)(link changed toRiver Tees; link chan