{"title_page": "Sardar Patel Stadium", "text_new": "{{distinguish-otheruses2|Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Stadium, Ahmedabad|Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Stadium}}\n{{short description|Cricket stadium in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| name                = Sardar Patel Stadium\n| logo_image          = \n| logo_caption        = \n| caption             = Motera Cricket Stadium \n| nickname            = Motera Stadium\n| fullname            = Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Stadium\n| former_names        = Sardar Patel Gujarat Stadium\n| location            = [[Motera]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]]\n| coordinates         = \n| broke_ground        = 1983 (former structure)\n2017 (expansion) \n| built               = 12 November 1983 (former structure)<br>24 February 2020 (post expansion) \n| opened              = 12 November 1983 (former structure)<br>24 February 2020 (post expansion)\n| renovated           = 24 February 2020 \n| expanded            = 24 February 2020\n| closed              = 2015 (former structure)\n| demolished          = 2015 (former structure)\n| owner               = [[Gujarat Cricket Association]]\n| operator            = \n| surface             = Australian Grass (Oval)\n| scoreboard          = \n| construction_cost   = {{INRConvert|800|c}}  (reconstruction, 2017\u20132020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/world-s-largest-cricket-stadium-gearing-up-to-host-trump-modi-in-gujarat-120021201119_1.html|title=Motera Stadium gearing up to host Trump}}</ref>\n| suites              = 76\n| architect           = [[Populous (company)|Populous]] (reconstruction)<br>[[Shashi Prabhu]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spa-aec.com/spaweb/allprojects.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823063136/http://www.spa-aec.com/spaweb/allprojects.html |archivedate=23 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (former structure)\n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = [[Larsen & Toubro]]\n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 110,000 (2020\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/sports/cricket/revamped-motera-stadium-to-have-record-one-lakh-seating-capacity-gca_1794982.html|title=Revamped Motera stadium to have record one lakh seating capacity: GCA|work=Zee News}}</ref><br>54,000 (2006\u20132015)<ref name='htold' /><ref name=Cricinfo>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/ground/57851.html Sardar Patel Stadium, Motera, Ahmedabad, India]. ESPN</ref><br>49,000 (1982-2006)\n| record_attendance   = 51,000 (India v Australia, World Cup 2011, 24 March 2011)(Sports)<br>125,000(temporary seating, \"Namaste Trump\" event, 24 February 2020)\n| executive_suites    =\n| dimensions          = 162 yards x 170 yards<ref name=\"Motera Stadium PM Modi's Vision\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/new-motera-stadium-is-prime-minister-narendra-modis-vision-says-amit-shah/articleshow/70918902.cms|title=New Motera Stadium is PM Modi's Vision|work=Times Of India}}</ref>\n| acreage             = 63\n| tenants             = [[Indian Cricket Team]] (1983\u2013present)<br>[[Gujarat cricket team]] (1983\u2013present)<br>[[Rajasthan Royals]] (2010 & 2014)\n| embedded            = {{infobox cricket ground\n| embed            = yes\n| country          = India\n| location         = [[Motera]]\n| establishment    = \n| seating_capacity = 110,000\n| owner            = \n| operator         = Gujarat Cricket Association\n| tenants          = \n| architect        = \n| end1             = Adani Pavilion End\n| end2             = GMDC End\n| international    = true\n| firstodidate     = 5 October\n| firstodiyear     = 1984\n| firstodihome     = India\n| firstodiaway     = Australia\n| lastodidate      = 6 November\n| lastodiyear      = 2014\n| lastodihome      = India\n| lastodiaway      = Sri Lanka\n| firsttestdate    = 12\u201316 November\n| firsttestyear    = 1983\n| firsttesthome    = India\n| firsttestaway    = West Indies\n| lasttestdate     = 15\u201319 November\n| lasttestyear     = 2012\n| lasttesthome     = India\n| lasttestaway     = England\n| onlyt20idate     = 28 December\n| onlyt20iyear     = 2012\n| onlyt20ihome     = India\n| onlyt20iaway     = Pakistan\n\n| firstwodidate  = 12 March\n| firstwodiyear  = 2012\n| firstwodihome  = India\n| firstwodiaway  = Australia\n| lastwodidate  = 12 April\n| lastwodiyear  = 2013\n| lastwodihome  = India\n| lastwodiaway  = Bangladesh\n| firstwt20idate   = 22 January\n| firstwt20iyear   = 2011\n| firstwt20ihome   = India\n| firstwt20iaway   = West Indies\n| lastwt20idate   = 24 January\n| lastwt20iyear   = 2011\n| lastwt20ihome   = India\n| lastwt20iaway   = West Indies\n| year1            = 1983\u2013present\n| club1            = [[Gujarat cricket team]]\n| date             = 25 October 2019\n| source           = [http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57851.html ESPNcricinfo]\n| image            = \n| caption           = New Motera stadium from riverside}}}}\nThe '''Sardar Patel Stadium,''' commonly known as '''Motera Stadium''', is a [[cricket]] [[List of Test cricket grounds|stadium]] in [[Ahmedabad]], [[India]]. As of 2020, it is the [[List of cricket grounds by capacity|largest cricket stadium in the world]] and the [[List of stadiums by capacity|second-largest stadium overall]], with a seating capacity of 110,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhaskar.com/news/GUJ-AHM-OMC-sardar-patel-stadium-at-motera-demolished-in-ahmedabad-5297477-PHO.html|title=Motera Stadium demolished}}</ref> Owned by the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]], it is a regular venue for [[Test cricket|Test]], [[One Day International|ODI]], and [[Twenty20 International|T20I]] matches.\n\nThe stadium was constructed in 1983 and underwent its first renovation ahead of the [[ICC Champions Trophy]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/cover-story/motera-stadium-gujarats-grand-stand/articleshow/74050920.cms|title=Motera Stadium: Gujarat's Grand Stand|website=Ahmedabad Mirror}}</ref> It became the regular venue for international matches in the city. In 2015 the stadium was closed and demolished, and a complete reconstruction was done by 2020, with an estimated cost of {{INRConvert|800|c|lk=on}}, increasing the capacity to 110,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/donald-trump-likely-to-inaugurate-motera-cricket-stadium-worlds-largest-cricket-facility-in-ahmedabad/motera-cricket-stadium/slideshow/74131161.cms|title=Donald Trump likely to inaugurate, Motera Cricket Stadium, world's largest cricket facility in Ahmedabad |website=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The stadium hosted the opening of the '[[Namaste Trump]]' meeting of [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Donald Trump]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on 24 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/motera-stadium-10-things-to-know-about-namaste-trump-venue/articleshow/74277404.cms|title=Motera Stadium: 10 things to know about 'Namaste Trump' venue |last=|date=24 February 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nApart from cricket, the ground has played host to several programs arranged by the [[Government of Gujarat]]. It has also hosted matches during the [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]], [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]], and [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011]] World Cups. The pitch previously used to favour [[Bowling (cricket)|bowlers]] but has recently been host to competitive games. As of 2020, the stadium has hosted 12 [[Test cricket|Tests]], 23 [[One Day International|ODIs]], and 1 [[Twenty20 International|T20Is]] matches.<ref name=\"stadiumrecord\">{{cite web |title=Stadium statistics (on ESPN Cricinfo) |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/india/engine/records/team/match_results.html?class=2;id=840;type=ground}}</ref>[[File:The Trumps and Modi in Motera Stadium.jpg|thumb|US President Donald Trump along with Indian Prime Minister Modi at the Sardar Patel Stadium]]\n\n==History==\n\n===1982\u20132006 (Early Years)===\nFormerly known as the Gujarat Stadium, the ground was renamed in tribute to [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]],<ref>{{cite news|title=14 Things You Did Not Know about Sardar Patel, the Man Who United India|url=http://topyaps.com/sardar-patel-the-ironman|accessdate=16 May 2014|newspaper=Topyaps|date=1 November 2014|author=Ashwani Sharma}}</ref> India's first [[Home Minister]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of India|Deputy Prime Minister]]. Before the Motera Stadium came into existence, international cricket matches in the city were played at [[Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation]]'s [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Stadium, Ahmedabad|stadium of the same name]] (Sardar Patel Stadium) in the Navrangpura area. In 1982, the Government of Gujarat donated a {{convert|100|acre|m2|adj=on}} stretch of land on the banks of the [[Sabarmati River]] for the construction of a new stadium. The construction of the Sardar Patel Stadium was carried out in a span of nine months.<ref name='htold'>{{cite news|title=Why Sardar Patel Stadium in Motera, Ahmedabad will make cricket history|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/why-sardar-patel-stadium-in-motera-ahmedabad-will-make-cricket-history/story-7b59h4SZG5yHl7BGkg9agK.html|accessdate=10 Dec 2016|newspaper=HindustanTimes|date=10 December 2016|author=HT Correspondent}}</ref> Since then, all International cricket fixtures for the city are hosted here. Later in the 1984-85 Australia-India series, Sardar Patel Stadium hosted its first [[One Day International|ODI]], in which [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] defeated [[Indian cricket team|India]].\n\n[[Sunil Gavaskar]] became the first cricketer to score 10,000 runs in Test cricket on this ground \u2013 a feat he achieved against Pakistan in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|title=India Today article on Sunil Gavaskar's 10,000 runs|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1987-Gavaskar+is+the+first+to+score+10,000+test+runs:+A+10+tonne+toast/1/76385.html}}</ref> Seven years later, [[Kapil Dev]] claimed his 432nd Test wicket on this ground to become the highest wicket-taker in the world, breaking [[Richard Hadlee|Sir Richard Hadlee's]] previous record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ashaval.com/motera-stadium-0221119/|title=Motera Stadium: Inaugration, Renovationm and Seating Capacity |last=Paliwal|first=Priyansha|date=2020-02-08|website=Ashaval.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> Prior to achieving this, Kapil Dev took a nine-wicket haul against West Indies at the Motera ground in 1983. In 1996, the ground hosted a low-scoring Test match against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], where the visitors faltered while chasing 170 to win, ending up at 105 all out. [[Javagal Srinath]] took six wickets in the fourth innings of the match. However, South Africa had their revenge when they bowled India out for 76 runs in the first session of the Test match in 2008 and went on to win the game by an innings and 90 runs.\n\n===2006-2015 (Rise to Prominence)===\nThe stadium had become of the focal venues of [[ICC Champions Trophy]] in 2006,  with hosting five of the 15 games played. In order to host such an organization, the stadium had gone into a comprehensive renovation that includes three new pitches and a new outfield. Moreover, floodlights and covered stands were introduced at the stadium as a part of the renovation program.\n\nThe Motera Stadium has hosted games whenever India has hosted the [[Cricket World Cup]], including the first match of the 1996 World Cup between [[England cricket team|England]] and [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]]. However, while it hosted only one game each in the 1987 and 1996 editions, the stadium was given three games in the 2011 World Cup, including the quarter-final between [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] and [[India cricket team|India]]. Sachin Tendulkar became the first-ever cricketer to score 18,000 runs in One Day International cricket, during that match. As of 19 August 2017, it has hosted 12 Tests, 23 ODIs and 1 T20I.\n\n===2015-2020 (Reconstruction)===\n[[File:President_Trump_and_the_First_Lady_in_India_(49579268442).jpg|thumb|US President [[Donald Trump]] and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] at the Sardar Patel Stadium, 24 February 2020.]]\nIn October 2015, the stadium was demolished to allow for reconstruction. Though some media cite it as 'renovation', the original venue was completely demolished. Hence, effectively it is an entirely new stadium in place. The total cost of reconstruction was estimated to be [[Indian Rupee|\u20b9]]700 crores.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} However, the final cost has been reported at [[Indian Rupee|\u20b9]]800 crores. The redevelopment, originally planned to be completed in 2019, was accomplished finally by February 2020.\n\n====Conception====\nReportedly, the idea to make the new stadium was proposed by [[Narendra Modi]], then the president of the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] and the Chief Minister of Gujarat. Shortly before Modi moved to Delhi as the [[Prime Minister of India]], there were discussions about minor upgrades to the stadium and development of the structure at the pavilion end. When informed about the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]], Modi asked the officials to build a new larger stadium instead of minor renovation work.<ref name=\"Gujarat soon to have the largest stadium\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/sports/2019/09/16/Gujarat-will-soon-have-world-largest-cricket-stadium-All-you-need-to-know.html|title=Motera stadium: All you need to know}}</ref> The stadium has often been touted as one of his dream projects.\n\n====Bids====\nAfter starting the demolition work at the end of 2015, the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] issued a tender notice on January 1, 2016 in [[The Times of India]] and [[The Indian Express]]. Nine bidders showed interest and purchased the tender documents, out of which three actually submitted Technical and Financial bids on time. The three bidders were the [[Shapoorji Pallonji Group]], Nagarjuna Construction Company, and [[Larsen & Toubro]]. A Tender Commercial Committee (TCC) of nine experts was formed for the evaluation of tenders. Additionally, STUP Consultants was appointed as the Project Management Consultant to evaluate proposals and technical details of each bid working with the TCC.<ref name=\"Motera Stadium - GCA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gujaratcricketassociation.com/page/motera-stadium|title=GCA \u2013 Motera Stadium}}</ref>\n\nEach of the three bidders presented their designs, models, and technical details of their concepts & designs. Because of the sheer size and complexity of the project, the bidders were evaluated on multiple parameters like efficiency, resources, the time frame of completion, ease of implementation, etc. The bidders were ranked and weighted on all of the parameters.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Bids Submitted for Motera Reconstruction\n! Bidder\n! Bid\n! Evaluation\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Larsen & Toubro]]\n| {{INRConvert|677.19|c}}\n| Lowest-1 (L1)\n| Winning bid. Financially lowest and technically ranked first.\n|-\n| [[Shapoorji Pallonji Group|Shapoorji Pallonji & Co. Ltd.]]\n| {{INRConvert|847.88|c}}\n| Lowest-2 (L2)\n|\n|-\n| Nagarjuna Construction Co. Ltd.\n|{{INRConvert|1065|c}}\n| Highest (L3)\n|\n|}\n\nIn the end, [[Larsen & Toubro|L&T]] was finalized as the Principal Contractor to build and design the Motera Stadium.\n\n====Work====\nL&T took over the construction work of the stadium in December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=L&T to build largest cricket stadium in the world|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/LT-to-build-worlds-biggest-cricket-stadium-at-Motera/articleshow/55884457.cms}}</ref> On 16 January 2017, foundation stone laying was held by Gujarat Cricket Association, and work formally started on the ground. The stadium was planned to get ready in 2 years, and the reconstruction project estimated to cost around \u20b9 7 billion.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/India-starts-building-world%E2%80%99s-biggest-stadium/article17079837.ece India starts building world's largest cricket stadium]. Retrieved on 23 January 2017</ref> Finishing touches are being given to the stadium as of February 2020, and it is expected to host an [[England national cricket team|England]]-[[India national cricket team|India]] day-night test match by 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/112303/new-motera-stadium-to-host-england-in-dn-test|title=Motera to host England in a Day-Night test}}</ref>\n\nMumbai based Commercial Kitchen Consultants \"Span Asia\" were hired to work with [[Populous (company)|Populous]] and [[Larsen and Toubro|L&T]] on all the F&B Related areas such as the Concession Counters, Main Stadium Kitchens, Player Kitchens, VIP/VVIP Boxes, Corporate Boxes, Press & Media Boxes, Pantries, GCA Club and Related areas.\n\n==Stadium Design==\nThe Stadium is spread across 63 acres of land, with three entry points as opposed to just one in the old Stadium, with a metro line at one of the entry points. Additionally, it contains 76 corporate boxes, each having capacity of 25,<ref name=\"business-standard.com\">https://www.business-standard.com/article/sports/motera-stadium-all-you-need-to-know-about-world-s-largest-cricket-venue-120022200600_1.html</ref> a 55-room clubhouse, an Olympic sized swimming pool,<ref name=\"business-standard.com\"/><ref>https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2020/02/24/1988930/0/en/WORLD-S-LARGEST-CRICKET-STADIUM-OPENS-IN-AHMEDABAD.html</ref> and four dressing rooms. A unique feature of the Stadium is the LED lights on the roof instead of the usual floodlights at cricket grounds. This will be the first of its kind design in India. The LED lights are installed on an anti-bacterial, fireproof canopy with PTFE membrane that covers 30 metres of the total 55 metres breadth of sitting area. The roof has been designed by the company [[Walter P Moore]], been specifically designed to be lightweight and separate from the seating bowls in order to allow for movement in times of seismic activity, making it fairly earthquake resistant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walterpmoore.com/projects/motera-cricket-stadium-roof-design|title=Motera Stadium roof design}}</ref> The structure eliminates the need for pillars, giving spectators an unobstructed view of the entire field from any place in the Stadium.\n \nOutside of the main ground, the Stadium will be able to accommodate several other features, including an olympic sized swimming pool, indoor cricket academy, badminton and tennis courts, squash arena, table tennis area, 3D projector theatre and a clubhouse with three practice grounds and 50 rooms.<ref name=\"World's largest stadium to host POTUS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/kem-chho-trump-world-largest-cricket-stadium-all-set-to-host-potus/story/396505.html|title=Motera Stadium ready to host POTUS|work=Business Today}}</ref> The parking lot can accommodate 3,000 cars and 10,000 two-wheelers. The Motera Stadium also has a huge ramp designed to facilitate the movement of around 60,000 people simultaneously. The stadium design has been done in a way where patrons will fill the lower levels of the ground for smaller events, which will help maintain the crowd atmosphere despite the colossal Stadium not being full.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/motera-cricket-stadium-in-ahmedabad-with-seating-capacity-of-over-a-lakh-to-be-largest-in-the-world-359982.html|title=Motera Stadium in Ahmedabad to be the largest in the world|work=India Times}}</ref>\n\nIt has also been planned that the Motera Stadium will get a \"Sky-walk\", allowing the crowd to directly enter the Stadium within 300 metres from disembarking at the metro station. This will eliminate the need to get on the roads, easing congestion. However, the sky-walk will only get completed after September 2020, and is a part of the Motera Metro Station project rather than the Stadium's project.<ref name=\"Motera to get skywalk by 2020\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/motera-stadium-to-get-skywalk-by-september-2020/articleshow/70744418.cms|title=Motera Stadium to get Skywalk by 2020|work=Times Of India}}</ref>\n\n==Major events==\n===Namaste Trump===\n{{further|Namaste Trump}}\nThe Motera Stadium hosted US President [[Donald Trump]] on 24 February 2020, along with Indian Prime minister [[Narendra Modi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/videos/politics/ahmedabads-motera-stadium-to-host-us-president-donald-trump-5304111.htm|title=Ahmedabad's Motera Stadium to host US President Donald Trump|website=cnbctv18.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The event, titled \"Namaste Trump\", is a response to the \"Howdy Modi\" event held in [[Houston]], [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-17/it-ll-be-namaste-trump-in-india-after-howdy-modi-in-texas|title=It will be Namaste Trump in India after Howdy Modi in US}}</ref>\n\n==Records==\n[[File:Sardar Patel Gujarat Stadium Ahmedabad.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Sardar Patel Stadium (before reconstruction)]]\n\n===Test match records===\n\n* '''Highest innings total''': [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] 760/7d \u2013 India v Sri Lanka, 2nd innings, 16 Nov 2009\n* '''Lowest innings total''': [[Indian cricket team|India]] 76 \u2013 India v South Africa, 1 inning, 3 Apr 2008\n* '''Highest individual score''': [[Mahela Jayawardene]] 275 (Balls: 435 4x27 6x1) \u2013 Sri Lanka v India, 16 Nov 2009\n* '''Best bowling''':<br>(in an innings) [[Kapil Dev]]  9/83 \u2013 India v West Indies, 12 Nov 1983<br>(in a match) [[Venkatapathy Raju]] 11/125 \u2013 India v Sri Lanka, 8 Feb 1994\n* '''Most runs''': [[Rahul Dravid]] (India) 771 Runs (Mat:7 Inn:14 HS:222 Ave:59.30 SR:49.10 100x3 50x1), [[Sachin Tendulkar]] \u2013 642 runs, [[VVS Laxman]] \u2013 574 runs\n* '''Most wickets''': [[Anil Kumble]] (India) 36 Wickets (Mat:7 Runs:964 BBI:7/115 BBM:10/233 Ave:26.77 Econ:2.29 SR:70.1 5W/I:3 10W/M:1), [[Harbhajan Singh]]- 29 wickets, [[Kapil Dev]] \u2013 14 wickets\n\n===One Day International match records===\n\n* '''Highest total''': [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]] 365/2 \u2013 India v South Africa, 1st innings, 27 Feb 2010\n* '''Lowest total''': [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] 85 \u2013 Zimbabwe v [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], 1st innings, 8 Oct 2006\n* '''Highest individual score''': [[Sourav Ganguly]] 144 (Balls:152 4x8 6x6) \u2013 India v Zimbabwe, 5 Dec 2000\n* '''Best bowling''': [[Mitchell Johnson (cricketer)|Mitchell Johnson]] 4/19 (9.2 overs) \u2013 Australia v Zimbabwe, 21 Feb 2011\n* '''Most runs''':  [[Chris Gayle]] \u2013 316 runs, [[Sachin Tendulkar]] \u2013 215 runs\n* '''Most wickets''': [[Kapil Dev]] (India) 10 Wickets (Mat:6 Runs:156 Best:3/26 Ave:15.60 Econ:3.04), [[Lasith Malinga]] \u2013 7 wickets, [[Chris Gayle]]- 6 wickets\n\n==Landmarks witnessed==\n{{wide image|Motera.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of Motera Stadium seen from Club Pavilion \u2013 India playing a test match against New Zealand in November 2010 (former structure)}}\n\nMotera has witnessed some great feats of Indian cricket history:[[File:Sachin Tendulkar waiting.jpg|thumb|Sachin scored 18000 ODI runs, first and only cricketer to achieve this feat]]\n* [[Sunil Gavaskar]] completed 10,000 runs in Test cricket in 1986\u201387 against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]].<ref name=\"demolition\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/919559.html |title=Sardar Patel Stadium in Motera to be demolished |accessdate=11 September 2015 |work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* [[Kapil Dev]], who had taken 9 wickets in an innings in the first match on this ground, scalped his 432nd wicket in Test cricket to pass [[Richard Hadlee|Sir Richard Hadlee's]] record, thus becoming the highest wicket taker in Test cricket at that time.<ref name=\"demolition\" />\n* In October 1999, [[Sachin Tendulkar]] scored his first Test Match double-hundred in a match against New Zealand.\n* Sachin Tendulkar completed his 20 years of International Cricket here on 16 November 2009 against Sri Lanka. During the same game, Sachin Tendulkar reached a landmark of 30,000 runs in International cricket.\n* Sachin Tendulkar became the first-ever cricketer to score 18,000 runs in One day cricket in a match against [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] during [[2011 Cricket World Cup]].\n* [[AB de Villiers]] reached his first double-hundred against India during the second test of South Africa's tour to India in 2008.\n\n==Cricket World Cup==\n\nWhenever India has hosted the [[Cricket World Cup]], the stadium has hosted One Day Internationals (ODIs).\n\n===1987 Cricket World Cup===\n\n{{Limited overs international\n | date = 26 October 1987\n | daynight = \n | team1 = {{cr-rt|ZIM}}\n | score1 = 191/7 (50 overs)\n | runs1 = [[Kevin Arnott (cricketer)|Kevin Arnott]] 60(126)\n | wickets1 = [[Chetan Sharma]] 41/2 <br> [[Kapil Dev]] 44/2\n | team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n | score2 = 194/3 (42 overs)\n | runs2 = [[Navjot Sidhu]] 55(61)\n | wickets2 = PW Rawson 46/2\n | umpires = [[David Archer (umpire)|David Archer]] and [[Dickie Bird]]\n | toss = India won the toss and elected to field\n | result = {{cr|IND}} won by 7 wickets\n | motm = [[Kapil Dev]]\n | scorecard = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/65109.html Scorecard]\n | venue = Sardar Patel Stadium, [[Motera]], [[Ahmedabad]]\n}}\n----\n\n===1996 Cricket World Cup===\n\n{{Limited overs international\n | date = 14 